(20, 5, 'My Final Thoughts', NULL, 20, NULL, '2020-05-28 18:22:51', '2020-09-10 23:58:25', NULL),
(21, 6, 'Welcome to College', NULL, 20, '<p>Welcome back, reader! I&rsquo;m saying, &ldquo;Welcome Back&rdquo; in the event that you have read the previous text called <em>Ugh!?! Not Another Diversity Book</em>, but in the event that you haven&rsquo;t: Spoiler Alert -&nbsp; This book is going to be a lot of fun; this book is going to shift your paradigm regarding classes, professors, sex, drugs, alcohol, safety, life choices, and higher education. Before we get into all that, let&#39;s talk about the real reason you purchased this book. Did you purchase it because it was required for a class? Did you purchase it because it had a clever title? Ooh, &ldquo;Things I Didn&rsquo;t Tell My Mom in College&rdquo;...that sounds scandalous! What could this author, Justin Brown, not tell his mother? Most people who know Justin Brown know that he has a great relationship with his mom. So what could Justin possibly have experienced that he couldn&rsquo;t tell his mom? It&#39;s crazy! Maybe you bought this book because you wanted to get some dirt on the author. If you bought the book for that reason, you&#39;re in luck. If you bought the book because you really don&#39;t know what college students are going through today in the later 2000&rsquo;s, then congratulations, you bought a great book! If you&rsquo;re a parent and you&rsquo;re looking for some insight on how to help your child navigate the rough, crazy and interesting terrain of college, then you are also in luck!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Like we did in the previous book, we have to start from the beginning because the beginning really gives us the foundation as to when some people really start to think about college. I remember my beginning.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It started early in my 9th grade year of high school. I woke up one morning to the sound of music. In most black households, if you wake up to the sound of music, there are normally two possible reasons: 1. There&#39;s breakfast downstairs, so come down and eat because you&#39;re probably going to be having family over later; which means a busy day... or 2. You&#39;re probably going to be cleaning all day, so get yourself ready to clean. On this particular morning, as I heard the music, I said, &ldquo;Oh God!&rdquo; I ran downstairs as quickly as possible and found everyone already sitting around the table; my mom had made breakfast &ndash; Great! Super excited for mom&rsquo;s breakfast! But, as most stories go, there&rsquo;s a turning point in the story. The turning point went like this: I was asking my sister to pass the pancakes and as she passed the pancakes, my mother looked me right in the eye and said, &ldquo;So Justin, have you thought about college?&rdquo; I said, &ldquo;Oh yeah, yeah, yeah, I&rsquo;ve thought about college. I&#39;m really excited about (INSERT WHATEVER SCHOOL HERE) and I&rsquo;m really excited about going!&rdquo; My parents looked at me and said, &ldquo;So, have you thought about how you&rsquo;re going to pay for college?&rdquo; I replied, &ldquo;Oh simple. You and dad are going to pay for it.&rdquo; My parents just looked at each other and then back at me and said, &ldquo;Excuse me? Who&#39;s paying for your college?&rdquo; I repeated, &ldquo;You all are.&rdquo; And my parents said, &ldquo;Justin, no, no, no; we&rsquo;re not paying for your college?!&rdquo; I sat there, puzzled, and then I said, &ldquo;Wait, wait, wait! What do you mean you&rsquo;re not paying for my college? So and so&rsquo;s parents are paying for their college!&rdquo; My parents replied back, &ldquo;Well maybe you should live at so and so&rsquo;s house. Look around this table, you have two other siblings.&rdquo; As I looked around the table, my sisters started giving me these really silly faces and funny looks that said, &ldquo;Ha-ha, you can&rsquo;t pay for college!&rdquo; Meanwhile, I&#39;m sitting there thinking, &ldquo;Wow!&rdquo; My whole life I thought that my parents had saved up money for me to go to college.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ultimately, my parents had a little bit saved up but they certainly did not have the means to fully fund my educational experience and also take care of our family.&nbsp; The fact that most parents don&rsquo;t have $120,000 saved up to fully fund their child&rsquo;s college education is a startling revelation for most students. Some parents may, but most don&rsquo;t. So, I said to my parents, &ldquo;Well look, if we don&#39;t have the money to pay for my schooling, then maybe I just won&#39;t go to college.&rdquo; Then came the whole conversation of our background - &ldquo;Slaves died so you could go to college; a lot of people shed blood so that you could further your education; there were a lot of sacrifices made by your grandparents!&rdquo; I said, &ldquo;OK, OK, OK, relax! I&rsquo;ll be going to school, don&#39;t worry about it.&rdquo; I hoped my decision, to get an education, would make my parents happy.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you read &ldquo;Ugh!?! Not Another Diversity Book&rdquo;, you may remember my initial thoughts about going to college. Since I was a kid, I remember, my parents talking to me about college. I remember being at my grandma&#39;s house and her asking me &ldquo;Hey Justin, do you want to go to college one day?&rdquo; and my reply was, &ldquo;No, I hate school&rdquo;. I was five at the time. I remember my grandma going into a cabinet and conveniently pulling out an old assignment that my uncle completed when he was my age. The assignment asked him what he had done that particular summer and he had written, &ldquo;Nothing&rdquo;. The assignment also asked him how many books he had read that summer and his reply was, &ldquo;Not one darn book&rdquo;. I remember my grandma looking at me and telling me, &ldquo;You know your uncle also hated school at one time, but he went on to get his doctoral degree.&rdquo; Now, literally, twenty years later, I was graduating with my master&rsquo;s degree, with the aspiration of eventually getting a PH.D.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I also recall, when I was in the ninth grade, everyone had to meet with their school counselor. My counselor called me in and said she wanted to learn a little bit more about me. She wanted to get an idea of how I was doing academically. She also wanted to discuss my plans post high school. I told her that I wanted to go to college and study Psychology. My school counselor looked at me, right in the eye, and said, &ldquo;I&rsquo;m looking at your grades and it doesn&#39;t appear that you are college material. Perhaps you should look into a trade or craft? Learning a trade could certainly be beneficial for you. Maybe a trade like...cutting hair, carpentry, plumbing, or working on cars is a better direction for you to consider. These types of skills could be really useful for you in the future.&rdquo; I remember looking at her and saying, &ldquo;No. I&rsquo;m going to college&rdquo;. She explained that with my grades, it didn&rsquo;t look like I would get there. Boy was she wrong! This story makes me think about how way too many young students are treated in America. They&rsquo;re told that they can&#39;t do it. Being told you&rsquo;re not good enough and that you won&rsquo;t amount to much in life, can rob a young individual of their self-esteem. This suggests that perhaps, their maturity, their age, or even their experience makes them ill-equipped to successfully achieve their ambitions, goals and dreams. My advice to you would be, &ldquo;If your dreams aren&rsquo;t scary enough, then you&rsquo;re probably not dreaming big enough.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Soon after that conversation with my counselor, I began touring colleges. By 10th or 11th grade, I had probably visited 60 schools. I&rsquo;m sure some of you are thinking, &ldquo;<em>WHAT</em>!? Visited 60 schools?! Justin, when did you have time to do that?&rdquo; I&rsquo;m not sure where I found the time, but it was important to me and to my parents, so I made the time. At this point, my parents had decided that it was a good idea to enroll me in the &lsquo;Upward Bound&rsquo; program at Lincoln University - not far from where I grew up. For those of you who are unfamiliar with the &lsquo;Upward Bound&rsquo; program, it&#39;s a program that is funded by the U.S. Department of Education. The program is designed to help individuals and students, from low income households, have access to a college education. Ultimately, this means that I went to college during the summer!! Yup, that&rsquo;s right! I went to college during the summers of&nbsp; 9th, 10th, and 11th grades. So, while most students were at the beach getting a tan, (and since I already kind of have an all-natural tan going on), my parents decided that I should further my education.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A little history about Lincoln University: Lincoln University was the first HBCU (Historically Black College or University). You may also hear some people refer to Cheyney University as the first HBCU. Most HBCUs were established after the American Civil War, but Cheyney University of Pennsylvania (1837) and Lincoln University (Pennsylvania) (1854), were established for blacks before the American Civil War. The timeline and discussion of who was first, isn&rsquo;t relevant for this story.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Keep in mind, in the household where I was raised, there was no room for and there was no talk of NOT going to college. Both of my parents had their Master&#39;s degrees. I had an uncle and aunt who had their Doctoral degrees. Another aunt had her Bachelor&rsquo;s degree and was working as a teacher. Basically, everyone else I knew had some type of formal, higher education. There was no way that I was going to get out of going to college. When I look at the way that I was raised, my household was kind of like the Cosby show - minus the scandal. Everyone got along, everyone was happy, everyone was educated and college was more than just a concept; it was at the forefront of their thinking and it was a reality.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I think that&#39;s part of the reason why I became a college administrator. There were other people I knew, in my community, that didn&#39;t see college as a definite part of their future and in my opinion, if given the opportunity and necessary information, college can absolutely be a for-sure plan for everyone. While you&rsquo;re reading this first chapter, I want to make one perception crystal clear: College <em>can be</em> for everyone, but is not, necessarily, <em>for </em>everyone. Just because college exists, as a system, and is an option for most people, it doesn&#39;t mean that you absolutely have to go to college. News Alert: Some people don&rsquo;t want to go to college! We need blue collar workers just like we need white collar workers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When I was writing this chapter, I was on a plane, sitting next to a gentleman who has been a truck driver for about twenty years. He never went to college. We were talking about the concept of this book and he said, &ldquo;This is a great book you&rsquo;re writing and it&rsquo;s going to be very helpful for parents like me.&rdquo; I asked him what he meant and he replied, &ldquo;Well, I&rsquo;ve been driving trucks for the last twenty years of my life and I&rsquo;ve made good money, but I don&rsquo;t know a thing about college. My son absolutely wants to go to college. I&rsquo;ve been telling him, you don&rsquo;t have to go to college to be successful, but my son has his heart set on going to college. I honestly don&#39;t know what to tell him.&rdquo; What&rsquo;s the message here? Where does the message come from? Does the message come from parents? Students? College administrators?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I think everyone wants to send the same message; there&#39;s a reason for college. There are a lot of different reasons why people go to school. Some people go to college just to get the degree; some people go to learn life skills, such as leadership and development; some people go to college because their parents force them and it was either college, get a full time job or go into the army. Whatever the reason, an education and the experience while obtaining that education are invaluable. Most people go to college so they can get a better job; a better job means more money, but in order to go to college, you need more money! And you need college to get a better job to get more money! It&rsquo;s a vicious cycle. Whatever you decide to do, college or a trade, take this opportunity to elevate your future. Some people may get more than one chance to better their lives, but others only get one chance.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This reminds me of my friend Cornelius Rainer. We grew up together and Cornelius was and probably still is one of the most brilliant people that I have ever met. However, Cornelius spent most of his time developing the role of class clown. He would do whatever he could to get a laugh out of everybody. He didn&rsquo;t take school seriously, at all. In fact, Cornelius was drunk when he took his S.A.T.&#39;s!! Can you believe that? And, he still scored a 1650! That&#39;s crazy! Cornelius was one of those students where no matter what the subject was or what material we were learning, it just came easily to him; he didn&#39;t have to try hard and take his studies seriously. While it might take me 48 hours to learn a particular subject, Cornelius could read it the night before, in 20 minutes, and ace the test; meanwhile I would get a B- (if I was lucky). Even though he was a class clown, he was still successful; that always frustrated me about Cornelius. If I&rsquo;m being honest here, I was a little jealous of him.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Cornelius is an example of a person who only had one chance, he only had one shot and he didn&#39;t take that one chance seriously. College did not end well for Cornelius. When I think back to our college experience, Cornelius went to school but decided that he wanted the &lsquo;hood life&rsquo; more than the college life. His choices bothered me so much. I <em>wish</em> I had the brains he had. I wish I had the ability to effortlessly pick up on concepts like he did. If I had those skills, man, I&rsquo;d be able to take over the world! I thought that he was wasting his talents. I was pissed! I was angry! How could he have all these smarts and just throw it all away for hood life? The streets were more important to him. Cornelius not only had a full scholarship, but he also had outside scholarships that afforded him to have a completely free education. His university housing was paid for, even his meals were paid for and basically anything else you could think of! He was a class clown, he didn&#39;t take school seriously, yet he had the ability to go to college for free! Then when you looked at my situation, I was trying super-super-super hard to get into college. In fact, I went to college most of my summers and yet I had no scholarships to my name, at least not at that time.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Like I said, when we were in college, Cornelius didn&rsquo;t take school seriously at all. By the end of our first semester, his GPA had fallen below a 2.0. His goal was to get an engineering degree, yet he failed math class. How do you fail a math class when that&rsquo;s what you excel in? He just didn&#39;t take school seriously. During the second semester, Cornelius got a 1.7 GPA and had to withdraw from the university. Cornelius never went back to school. I occasionally see him and he typically says, &ldquo;Hey, I wish I had taken college more seriously. I wish someone had held me accountable.&rdquo; His words have always stuck with me; &ldquo;I wish someone had held me accountable. I wish someone would have told me. I wish that I had taken it more seriously.&rdquo; If that story isn&rsquo;t a reason to write a book like this, I don&rsquo;t know what is!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When you think about the modern day college student, they have a lot of different personalities and characteristics. They are the digital superiors, meaning that they have technology out the wazoo! Every day they&rsquo;re downloading a new app. Every single day there&rsquo;s a new iPad, iBoard, iPhone, iJar, iPrinter or whatever you want to call the latest technology that&rsquo;s coming out. And for those Android users...we won&rsquo;t talk about you right now. These students like everything and anything that can provide instant gratification. It&rsquo;s as if the days before having a microwave never existed! For these modern day college students, student loan debt is customary; they&#39;re even expecting it. Student loan debt isn&rsquo;t shocking to them, it&rsquo;s the norm; while in the past, student loan debt was insignificant and most people didn&rsquo;t encounter it. Growing older is mandatory, but for some of these students, growing up is optional. We see that a lot of these students are coming in and they lack leadership skills. It&rsquo;s hard when we&rsquo;re trying to help them learn and gain these leadership skills, but the students that are coming in are just too immature to handle these skills.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Information is also much easier to obtain for these students. Back in my day, when I was going to school, while we had computers, we still used encyclopedias, we still went to the library, and we still had to use multiple sources to gather information. Not all the information I needed was instantaneously obtainable, just by googling! We actually had to manually look up information. When referring to these modern day students, there is also a lot of multi-tasking going on. A lot of these students think that they can do many tasks, at one time. Everybody knows that multitasking isn&#39;t a real thing. If you&#39;re attempting to do multiple tasks at once, you can&#39;t give 100% attention to one specific thing you&#39;re doing; one of the tasks will suffer. I would also say that just about every single one of these students feel the need to have their lives documented. Now, I&rsquo;m not going to lie and say that I don&#39;t participate in these activities, because I do. I&rsquo;m talking about when <em>everything</em> is documented; from what they&#39;re eating, to what they&#39;re sleeping in, to whether they&rsquo;re sliding into someone&#39;s DMs (Direct Messaging), to when they&#39;re going out with their friends; everything is documented and recorded. So, you can see that the modern day, American college student is vastly different than any other college student that exists or has existed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Throughout my college experience (which was six years attending college - from my undergraduate degree and my master&#39;s degree, then working in the field for about five years), I&#39;ve gathered and collected a tremendous amount of information and stories from students, faculty, staff, people from around the country and even people from around the world. I would hear about different situations and different students; how situations went, upcoming trends, things that people need to be careful of, and circumstances that individuals really need to pay attention to. These stories became a cornucopia of knowledge for me. Through all the stories, I&rsquo;m always brought back to Cornelius&rsquo;s words, &ldquo;I wish someone had told me. I wish someone would have held me accountable.&rdquo; <em>That </em>is what this book is supposed to do.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&rsquo;ll let you know now, this book is going to reveal a lot about me personally. There will be a lot of information. Process it and feel free to start a conversation with me about any of the topics. I will tell you that everyone&#39;s college experience is different. What I went through in college and what some of my friends went through in college, may not be what your son or daughter will go through in college or may not be what <em>you </em>will go through in college. Our collective experiences will be not be the same.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I also want to explain how important college administrators are in the college experience. Are we <em>really </em>challenging our students and family and letting them know, &ldquo;Hey this is what college is like&rdquo;? College is very different than what K-12 is. If you look at K-12, we tell our students raise your hand before you go to the bathroom. Now, in an instant, we&rsquo;re bringing them into the college world and we&#39;re saying, &ldquo;OK, choose what you want to do for the rest of your life.&rdquo; These are two very different messages. College administrators will always need to stay ahead of the times and truly figure out what it takes to meet the needs of our students. How are we helping them in this process and are we really addressing student issues in the same way as everyone else? What I mean by that is, there are some college administrators who are bringing up these issues to students and making them aware and then there are others that don&#39;t seem too concerned. There&rsquo;s no consistency. This then leaves parents saying, &ldquo;Well I didn&#39;t know this was going to happen&rdquo; or &ldquo;this was very different than when I went to college.&rdquo; I think it&#39;s very reasonable for parents to think they have an idea of what goes on in college if they went to college, but the college landscape of the modern day college experience has completely changed; not just inconsequentially altered. Yes, some of the things that happened to parents when they were in college are continuing in the current day, but so much has changed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>People ask me why I wrote this text. I wrote this for a few reasons. I want to provide tips for parents and students throughout the text. You&rsquo;ll notice that there will be times when I talk directly to the parents and other times, I talk directly to students. The advice and wisdom, that I want to give to each, is vastly different. I want the students <em>and </em>their parents to be as prepared as possible. There are going to be times when your child may need your help and there will be times when you should <em>not </em>help your son or daughter and then there will be times, that maybe you should do. For the students, I want to help you understand and be aware of some circumstances you may have already gone through, you may be going through, or things you&#39;ve yet to see.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As college administrators, we&rsquo;re noticing a huge disconnect between parents and students. They&rsquo;re simply not having the necessary discussions; there&#39;s no dialogue going on. When we talk to most parents, they say they talk to their child an average of one or two times a week. That might not be you, you may talk to your son or daughter every day. I&rsquo;ve experienced both types of parents, but most parents are calling their child once or twice a week and saying, &ldquo;Hi honey. How&#39;s your day? How&#39;s your week been going? Are you eating? Are you sleeping? How are classes?&rdquo; That&rsquo;s it! That&rsquo;s the entire conversation. There&#39;s no conversations about the state of their mental health or questions like &ldquo;Are you going to parties?&rdquo; or &ldquo;Are you drinking?&rdquo; or &ldquo;Are you being safe?&rdquo; or &ldquo;Are you making sure that you get back to your residence hall in a safe way?&rdquo; or &ldquo;Are you taking time to rest?&rdquo; or &ldquo;Are you taking time to exercise?&rdquo;. These things are all important to the college experience. Many parents don&#39;t ask their son or daughter, &ldquo;Are you getting involved?&rdquo; or &ldquo;Are you doing this or that?&rdquo;. Parents are really left out of the loop when it comes to situations that students are facing on college campuses.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As college administrators, we aren&rsquo;t allowed to call parents and tell them what&#39;s going on. The Family Education Rights and Privacy Act (FERPA) prevents us from advising parents about what&rsquo;s truly going on. It can be frustrating when parents are calling and asking about their son or daughter and we&#39;re not allowed to tell them anything. Most of the time, we encourage the student to call their parent back and let them know what&#39;s going on; but most of the time, the students don&#39;t do that. Perhaps, throughout my ten plus years in higher education, I&rsquo;ve discovered this huge disconnect between parents and students. Who can help create the connection? Well, I hope that this text can help create the connection. There are a lot of different issues, concerns and overall basic knowledge that you&#39;re going to be reading in the next few chapters. There are the prominent issues that are happening in college and then there are the controversial topics and some poignant points that need to be made regarding anyone&#39;s higher education experiences.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When I think about disconnects, I think about when universities implement new student orientation. I remember observing one orientation where a college administrator asked the students in the audience, &ldquo;How many of you drink alcohol?&rdquo;. Of course, none of the students raised their hand. Why would they raise their hand and tell on themselves in front of a college administrator? The administrator let them know that it was okay to raise their hand...that no one would be in trouble. They just wanted to see how many incoming students drink alcohol. <em>Now</em>, when the college administrator asked them, &ldquo;How many of you drink?&rdquo;, the majority of the students raised their hands. The average incoming first-year student ranges in age between 17-22, so the majority of them should not be drinking yet; since the legal drinking age is 21. Then the college administrator asked them, &ldquo;How many of you do drugs?&rdquo;. No one raised their hand again. The college administrator said, &ldquo;This also includes marijuana.&rdquo;&nbsp; The majority of their hands went up. The college administrator went on to inform the students of the policies and procedures.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Later on in the day, during orientation, the college administrator met with all the parents. Similar questions were asked of the parents: &ldquo;How many of you think that your son or daughter drinks? Raise your hand.&rdquo; Only a few people (I would say about 15%) raised their hand. The college administrator looked puzzled and said, &ldquo;I want to let you know that almost 90% of the students raised their hand when I asked that same question.&rdquo; The parents looked puzzled. They looked as if they were in denial and maybe a little fearful - &ldquo;No way could my son or daughter be doing that. Not my baby. My baby would never do that&rdquo;. Then the big question came up, &ldquo;How many of you think that your son or daughter does drugs?&rdquo; Almost no one in the audience raised their hand. The college administrator said, &ldquo;There&#39;s a huge disconnect here because almost 75% of the students said they did drugs.&rdquo; The parents were in disbelief. They were saying, &ldquo;I&#39;m going to talk to my son or daughter. I can&#39;t believe they said they do drugs.&rdquo; These outcomes, from the questions asked during orientation, let me know that there was a huge disconnect between parents and students; they were not having the meaningful and engaging conversations that they needed to be having.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Everyone thinks that their son or daughter is the most precious living being that has ever walked the earth. You watch them grow up, you watch them accomplish the big milestones, and now you watch them go off to college. I&rsquo;m here to tell you that your son or daughter has definitely not told you every single thing they&rsquo;ve done while they were growing up. Why would they? Your son or daughter needs to have a life of their own and as most kids feel, they need their privacy. At this pivotal time in their lives, it&rsquo;s necessary to build an open relationship with your child and create and atmosphere of trust. College is a new frontier. College is a new life for them. You&rsquo;ll notice when your child comes home for Thanksgiving or winter and spring breaks, they may not be the same person that you dropped off at school a few months ago.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Advice for students: When you know better, you do better. The message I&rsquo;m trying to give you is, when you&#39;re pursuing a college education, make sure you get all the information that you can gather; be a thief! Now&rsquo;s the time to talk about being a thief. Most people think of a thief and think about stealing objects or priceless jewels. Students, the objects or priceless jewels in this situation that you need to steal, is information; gather as much as possible. Use that information superhighway! I say this because, the more information you have, the better your choices and better choices lead to less difficulties. Information gives you the ability to have options. This information will help you to figure out which hall you want to live in or what food plan you want or which major you want to strive towards. You don&rsquo;t want to get to your senior year of your undergraduate career only to find out that you don&#39;t want to pursue that particular path for the rest of your life. When you have the information up front, it allows you to potentially avoid the mistakes that others, before you, have made.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Throughout this text, you&#39;re going to read plenty of stories about a lot of different people. Hopefully their stories will inspire you to make different choices when it&#39;s time for your college education. Regardless of what choices you make, your decisions are yours and you have to live with them. Don&rsquo;t live life with regrets. Make sure you&#39;re doing what you want to do because that&#39;s what you want to do; not because someone else wants you to and not because you feel forced or pressured. Have an open dialogue with your parents. Having open dialogue allows your parents to have insight into your life. It helps them to continue molding and guiding you as you venture through this interesting college terrain. Then, even when you&rsquo;re in college, and beyond, continue having an open dialogue with your parents. Although they might not be physically near, it&rsquo;s important to stay in communication with them.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s a known fact that people tend to take advice from others who are not their parents; people who may not have their best interest at heart. For example: You know how your parents give you advice all the time, &ldquo;Oh you should do this or you should do that&rdquo; and you never listen? Then, when you go out on the street, someone tells you the exact same thing and you think, &ldquo;Oh I should do that!&rdquo; That&rsquo;s what I hope this text does for you - gives you the advice and instruction you need. That way, you can make the best decisions possible.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Advice for Parents: Each chapter will provide some tips or advice. This information isn&rsquo;t only for the students, but for you as well. First off, we need to continue to support and encourage students. Just because they&rsquo;ve turned eighteen and are out of the house, doesn&#39;t mean that they&#39;re now full grown adults - they&#39;re not! They still need your leadership, your guidance and occasionally your money. I know some of you may have regrets about things you were unable to do in college or actions you were unable to accomplish in life. Unfortunately, some of those opportunities may be over. You can&rsquo;t live your dreams through your child. Let your son or daughter be who they are. That means, if your child wants to be an art student, encourage them to be an art student; don&rsquo;t force them to be a business student. Don&rsquo;t threaten to not pay for their college education if they don&rsquo;t follow the path <em>you </em>want them to follow. Students, remember, your college education is based on <em>you</em> being able to fund it, not your parents.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And, parents, parents, parents! Please do not be helicopter parents. Not sure what a helicopter parent is? A hel&middot;i&middot;cop&middot;ter par&middot;ent is defined as:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>a parent who takes an overprotective or excessive interest in the life of their child or children.\r\n	<ol>\r\n		<li>Some college officials see all this as the behavior of an overindulged generation, raised by helicopter parents and lacking in resilience.</li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are parents that are here, at the university, more than their children are; you might as well enroll and live in the residence hall. Being a helicopter parent isn&rsquo;t helpful for anybody. It&rsquo;s not helpful to the staff. It&rsquo;s not helpful for the student because they can&#39;t find their own identity since their parents are constantly around. If you&rsquo;re a helicopter parent, you have to learn to let go - just a little bit. Yes, that means cutting the umbilical cord, cutting those apron strings. Pressure&rsquo;s hard, parents! There&#39;s a lot of pressure on students today. We&#39;re going to talk about it throughout the text. There&rsquo;s drugs, sex, the ability to fit in, trying to maintain mental health, making sure that all your class work and other responsibilities are done on time. The college experience itself is getting harder and harder every single year. We&#39;re seeing different trends that just keep popping up. The student experience, it takes a lot. Having pressure from parents doesn&#39;t make it easier for students; they need your support, not your pressure.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Parents: Be your child&rsquo;s supporter. The students need support, from all of us. They need us to challenge them but most importantly, they need us to support them. When they call you and they&#39;ve messed up or when they call you and they haven&#39;t done well on a test, or maybe they&rsquo;ve missed a few meals, that is not the time for you tell them why they&#39;re not a good student or why they&rsquo;re not meeting your expectations. Your children have to be able to make decisions for themselves as they&#39;re trying to find and identify who they truly are, now that they&#39;re outside of your house. Knocking them when they&#39;re already down doesn&#39;t help them. You would be surprised at the amount of meetings that I&rsquo;ve had with students where I&rsquo;ve asked them, &ldquo;Well have you told your parents about ____ _____ ____?&rdquo; And the student says, &ldquo;No. I can&#39;t tell my parents because my parents won&#39;t listen&rdquo; or &ldquo;No, my parents wouldn&rsquo;t understand&rdquo; or &ldquo;No, my parents would be really upset if I told them that.&rdquo; That pressure has got to be alleviated, otherwise you&#39;re not going to be able to have those engaging, meaningful and instructional conversations that you need to have with your child. Don&#39;t you want your child to come and talk to you? You&rsquo;re going to have to leave those lines of communication open. Now, this is coming from an individual who has no kids. No Kids Zone! However, if you think of my college students as the administrator&rsquo;s kids, over the past ten years, I&rsquo;ve probably had thousands of kids.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Another piece of advice would be: Please don&#39;t defend wrong behavior. Some of your children might come to college and find themselves in the midst of a student-conduct situation. Whether they were doing drugs or drinking alcohol, or whatever the situation may be, the last thing anyone needs is a parent calling up to say, &ldquo;Well my son or daughter did drugs or alcohol because they were stressed.&rdquo; or &ldquo;They were peer pressured.&rdquo; Support the university and the code of conduct or set of rules that have been implemented for these very reasons. Parents and students should be informed and educated regarding the code of conduct, so if a situation occurs, no one should be surprised.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is a time for your child to learn how to be accountable and take care of their own needs. Don&#39;t do everything for your student. There are times where parents come to our office and say, &ldquo;I need this done and I pay your paycheck.&rdquo; Earlier in the chapter, we discussed how this is the digital age of information, let the students fingers do their own walking.&nbsp; Sometimes students just need to take the initiative and handle situations for themselves. There have been many times when a parent calls up and is asking for information <em>for </em>their child. My reply, &ldquo;Hey, you should probably have your child call and figure this out for themselves. While this is great that you&#39;re calling and trying to get the information, we need students to be advocates for themselves, and we need you, as parents, to be able to put the responsibility and the initiative back on the student.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On the flip side, all that talk about responsibility, accountability and initiative, a reminder, we&#39;re not the students&#39; parents; although, sometimes you think we are. We do create really close relationships, but we&#39;re not the students&#39; parents - you are. There are some parents that drop their son or daughter off at school on the first day and we never see or hear from them again and neither does their child. Stay active in your child&rsquo;s education; be involved.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I know this is a lot of information for the first chapter. As the author, I want to suggest that you heed the suggestions and advice provided throughout this book and by all means, reference the information whenever you need it. There are 13 more chapters coming up and my wish is that you pay close attention to the controversial topics that we&#39;re going to be discussing. This is all about the modern day, American college student. These are the issues that they&#39;re facing. These are the trials and tribulations that your child may encounter. Some of the kids are going to have great experiences and some of them, not so much. Ultimately, after reading these chapters, I want parents and their children to feel more confident in having an open dialogue about the college experience. Are these encounters similar to the ones that you&#39;re having in college? Are these issues that you&#39;re going to have to work through as a parent? College was the most fun experience I&#39;ve ever had in my entire life and I hope that your son or daughter&rsquo;s experience in college will be as well. So, let&rsquo;s step back, let&#39;s take a look, and let&#39;s dive into this book. Welcome to college!</p>', '2020-09-07 22:38:06', '2020-09-11 00:01:21', NULL);
INSERT INTO `chapters` (`id`, `course_id`, `name`, `image`, `amount`, `details`, `created_at`, `updated_at`, `deleted_at`) VALUES
(22, 6, 'Your College Experience', NULL, 20, '<p>Congratulations reader! You have made it to Chapter 2! As in my previous book, I want to congratulate you, the reader, when you arrive at Chapter 2. This lets me know that you&#39;re interested in what you&rsquo;ve read so far and curious about what you&#39;re going to read. Full-steam ahead from this point forward! This chapter is called &ldquo;Your College Experience&rdquo; because from this point forward, it&rsquo;s all about the college experience for the average student.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When I was growing up, there were many things that I wanted to be, but a student affairs professional wasn&rsquo;t one of them. Life has a funny way of changing your aspirations. I had to adjust to life&rsquo;s transitions. I had to learn a few lessons before I decided that this is what I wanted to do for the rest of my life: To educate those who needed and wanted education.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Perhaps...If we take a trip down memory lane and see 4-year-old Justin, and you asked him what he wanted to be when he grew up, he would tell you that he wanted to be a trashman. That&#39;s right, a trashman. Some of you are probably saying to yourself, &ldquo;Ewww, that&rsquo;s gross! Why would Justin want to be a trashman? That&#39;s a terrible job!&rdquo; I remember telling my grandma I wanted to be a trashman because I thought the trucks were really cool. The trucks made really loud noises in the morning. The trashmen got to ride on the outside of the trucks; it just seemed super cool.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When I asked my grandma about being a trashman, her immediate response was, &ldquo;Hey, trashmen make good money.&rdquo; When I talked to my mom about being a trashman, she said, &ldquo;You don&rsquo;t want to be a trashman, you want to get an education.&rdquo; As I got a little bit older, maybe 10 or 11, I decided that I wanted to be a cop. Cops are cool; maybe not in 2018, but back when I was a kid in the early nineties, I thought being a cop was cool. I&rsquo;d get to have a gun and a badge and enforce the law. I thought, &ldquo;This is something that I want to do.&rsquo;&rdquo;My mom told me, &ldquo;You can&rsquo;t be a cop because you&#39;re going to get shot and I don&#39;t want to have sit around all night worrying about whether or not you&#39;re safe out there. So, no, choose something else.&rdquo; I thought, &lsquo;Ok, well maybe I&#39;ll be an actor. Acting is cool. You get to meet celebrities and be on T.V. It will be awesome!&rsquo; I decided I wanted to be an actor when I was watching my favorite show Kenan and Kel. Remember, &ldquo;Who loves orange soda? Kel loves orange soda!&rdquo; &ldquo;Is it true&hellip;. mmmm hmmmm!&rdquo; I know a lot of you know that show. It was my favorite show growing up. I wanted to be just like Kenan and Kel. I thought they were hilarious and I thought that acting was something I wanted to do. Approaching my mom again, I said, &ldquo;Hey, I want to be an actor when I grow up. What do you think about that?&rdquo; And she said, &ldquo;No. You can&#39;t be an actor because all they&#39;re going to do is stick you in stereotypical roles where you&#39;ll either be a drug dealer or pimp and I don&#39;t want to see that for you. You need to choose something else.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Why do I tell you these stories? I tell you these stories because I think a parents&rsquo; opinion can truly influence what a child chooses for their major, what field they enter and what career path they take. This story is certainly not meant to paint a picture that my mom wasn&#39;t supportive; my mom was extremely supportive. I think my mom wanted me to use my strengths and of course, as my mom, she knew more about my strengths than I did. I remember her always telling me, &ldquo;You know, when you get older, you&#39;re going to need a job where you can publicly speak because you&#39;re really good at speaking in a group setting. So, no matter what you do, you need to have a job where you can speak to the masses, speak to the crowds and inspire them.&rdquo; Well, she was absolutely right since my job, for the most part, is talking to young audiences and being a keynote speaker.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To my original point, as a parent, you can either hurt or help your child in regard to what they want their future to look like. I&rsquo;ve seen parents, many times, actually shame or discredit their children&rsquo;s dreams. Making them feel like their dreams are less than, because their child wants to major in the arts or in music or basically anything that has to do with an individualist type of career. Parents are quick to say, &ldquo;No. I don&#39;t want my child to get a degree in that. I want them to get a degree in something they can use, like math or science or business.&rdquo; Parents, your child can obtain more than one degree; they can successfully complete both types of degrees. They can get a degree in art and also get a degree in business, or get a degree in music and also get a degree in the math. Don&rsquo;t stifle your child. A lot of times, when I&rsquo;m talking to students and I ask them about their major, I find out they don&#39;t even like their major but because that&#39;s what they decided in their freshman year, they never changed it or they never changed it because they&#39;re afraid of what their parents might say. Basically, they never legitimately, one hundred percent, decide what they want for their own lives. Parents, allow your children to make those decisions for themselves. You can guide them and give them advice, but ultimately, it should be their decision. While they&#39;re young adults, take a step back and help guide them as they figure out this trajectory of life. They need our help in <em>guiding </em>and <em>advising </em>them, not <em>telling</em> them what to do. Sometimes, they just want us to have their back and let them discover the solution themselves.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Parents, another point I&rsquo;d like to mention is, you may have to take the time to re-learn your child. What does that mean? You&rsquo;ve had them, under your wing, since their birth - until about age 17 or 18, but your child will, most likely, change when they go to college. They&rsquo;ll start to learn and experience new things, make new friends, and develop in ways that you could never expect. You may feel that you have a complete stranger in your home when they come home for one of their breaks. You don&#39;t know what they&#39;re talking about. You don&#39;t understand the clothes they&rsquo;re wearing. You don&#39;t know why the tone of their conversations has changed. While they&rsquo;re away at school, they are evolving and developing into young adults.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You may notice some of their interests or activities have changed. When I went to school I thought I wanted to major in psychology. I found out a little bit about Freud during Psych and I said, &ldquo;SIKE!&rdquo;. In the end, I discovered that Communications is where I wanted to be. At the time, I didn&rsquo;t know that Communications was going to take me somewhere great, plus, psychology wasn&#39;t a good fit for me; Sigmund Freud freaked me out. I was better suited for communications. I had an advisor tell me that I could get paid for working in the communications field. The field encompassed areas such as how we communicate with each other, internally and externally, and how we take messages and make meaning out of them. I couldn&#39;t believe this was even a major! No one ever told me about it. Even at 18, I thought I was pretty knowledgeable and we&rsquo;ve already established that I like to gather a lot of information, but I had no knowledge on this topic. If I wasn&rsquo;t aware of this path, I can only imagine that most students weren&rsquo;t aware of this as an option and probably some other choices that were available. I can tell you now, &ldquo;When you know, you know!&rdquo; As soon as I started taking public relations classes and communications classes, I knew that this was the best fit for me. I was on the right path.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Bottom line, students, don&#39;t stay in a major if you&rsquo;re not passionate about it! Don&rsquo;t stick with a major just because you&#39;re afraid of what your parents might think or say. Don&rsquo;t be afraid to make a change and switch. And the sooner you make that change, the better. The longer you wait, the more time you waste and the harder it will be to make that switch. Focus on who you are doing this for. Often times, students tell me that they&#39;re in a particular major because their mom and dad wanted them to be in that major. Remember, this choice should be yours to make. At the end of the day, you are the one who has to live with the path you choose. When it&rsquo;s time for your major to guide you into a career path, you parents won&rsquo;t be the ones going to that job. At least we hope not; maybe the helicopter parents will be there, but most parents will not be. If you&#39;re going to go to college and get a degree, find something that you love, something that you&#39;re passionate about and something that you&#39;re going to enjoy.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This brings me to a very interesting story about my friend Steve. Steve&rsquo;s dad is an architect. He loves to draw full scale buildings, create designs for landscaping, and develop plans to construct new building structures. Steve&rsquo;s dad is really good at his job! Now, Steve does not like architecture; it was something that he had no interest in. I asked Steve why he didn&#39;t like it and he told me, &ldquo;My dad spent a lot of time hunched over a desk with a spotlight, drawing. He didn&rsquo;t spend a lot of time with me while I was growing up. That&rsquo;s not what I want.&rdquo; So, regardless if Steve was good at drawing and regardless if he liked drawing, he did not want to be an architect. He wanted to do something completely different; he wanted to be a physical therapist. Steve loved sports and wanted to go into athletic training in physical therapy. When the time came for Steve to choose his major and to start choosing classes, his dad was putting a lot of pressure on him about being an architect, telling him, &ldquo;Being an architect is a admirable job son, you&#39;ll make great money and you can make your own hours. You&#39;re really good at drawing; it&#39;s in the genes.&rdquo; What major do you think Steve chose? He chose architecture. His dad paid for all of his schooling and Steve came out with a degree in architecture, from a prestigious university.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Steve is now in his thirties and we frequently talk about his choice to become an architect. Steve&rsquo;s excellent at what he does, but he hates it! He hates going to his job. He hates what he&rsquo;s doing. I guess since he has that fancy degree, he may as well use it. The job affords Steve and his wife a good life, but Steve is miserable. He constantly tells me, &ldquo;If I could go back, I wouldn&rsquo;t have chosen this path just because my dad wanted me to. It feels like I&rsquo;ve missed out on a big part of my life.&rdquo; I try to encourage Steve and tell him, &ldquo;Hey, you can always go back and get another degree.&rdquo; I guess at this point, Steve feels like it&#39;s too late. He&rsquo;s married, he has a family, he has a house and he&rsquo;s settled in. It&rsquo;s not really prime time for Steve to pursue a different career path. This is a shining example of choosing a major that&#39;s right for you, after all, this is your life to live.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For students - I don&#39;t want what happened to me or what happened to Steve to happen to you. Choose wisely! I finally recognized my calling. As a Communications major, I learned a great deal about the business side of communications, as well as marketing and especially public relations. This is what really interested me &ndash; the drive to get a message out to people and the ability to stand in front of people and publicly speak. It was exactly what I wanted. It was like this major was made for me, yet I still felt unsatisfied.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Throughout my time as an undergrad, I had the opportunity to engage in many different student organizations. I worked with the Student Government Association and was a Resident Assistant for three years. I worked with student orientation and in the public relations office as a student leader. I was involved in a lot of student activities and involved in most facets of the institution outside of my academic requirements. Fast forward to my final semester of my senior year, and it was time for me to figure out what I wanted to do with the rest of my life. Like a lot of students, I didn&#39;t know what I wanted to do. I had come to discover the harsh reality that I had gotten a degree in something I ultimately did not want any part of. I couldn&rsquo;t see myself sitting behind a desk every day writing press releases. I didn&rsquo;t want to be on TV, hosting shows. I didn&#39;t want to be a voice on the radio. So, at this point, as far as I was concerned, I had a worthless degree. Had I used my degree to my fullest potential, I could have gone out there and done anything I wanted, but instead I felt stuck.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Have you ever felt like that? Putting all your hopes, dreams, passions, and ideas into something and then that something didn&#39;t produce much fruit? I felt like a seedless tree. Like a tree that had grown to its fullest potential, but without seeds. If seeds can&rsquo;t fall from a tree to the ground, then when that tree&rsquo;s longevity is over, there is no new tree to blossom in its place.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>By the time my senior year ended, I realized I was in a degree program that I didn&rsquo;t want any part of. If you ever find yourself in a major that doesn&#39;t make you happy, change it! I mentioned earlier, I&rsquo;ve spoken to many students, during that first year, about their major choice. It could be the fear of disappointing their parents, or they don&rsquo;t want to &ldquo;start over&rdquo;. I&#39;m telling you, if you&rsquo;re not happy with your major, change it! Changing it sooner rather than later still gives you the ability to catch up. Some of those classes can be used as prerequisites and you won&#39;t fall too far behind. What you don&#39;t want to do is continue to take classes in a major that you don&#39;t like because essentially what you&#39;re doing is you&#39;re letting your dreams go. Then later, as an adult, you&rsquo;ll realize that that was a mistake; like my friend Steve.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At this point in the game, my senior year, I had no idea what path to follow. I was pretty close with the Director of Public Relations at Slippery Rock University and we had several talks. She was a wonderful mentor to me. I also had a great relationship with one of the Directors of Admissions. I remember both of them telling me that it was clear as day what I wanted to do for the rest of my life and that everybody could see it but me. I said, &ldquo;Well what is it? What am I supposed to do?&rdquo; I honestly had no clue. I had a full scholarship and I had used it on a degree in something that I didn&rsquo;t have much interest in pursuing for the long term. Sure, it was a great fall back plan, but it wasn&#39;t something I was passionate about. It wasn&rsquo;t something that I could see myself really making a difference in and changing people&#39;s lives. They finally shared the secret that I was apparently missing. They said, &ldquo;Justin, you&rsquo;ve been involved in all of these different groups on campus. You definitely want to work with students. You need to go into student affairs.&rdquo; I said, &ldquo;Student affairs...what&rsquo;s that?&rdquo; That is when I first learned what this field was &ndash; supporting students, helping them through their journey, and encouraging their development outside of the classroom. I said, &ldquo;Whaaatt?!&rdquo; It was like everything finally clicked &ndash; the stars were shining and my eyes lit up. I finally realized that all I&#39;ve been doing during my four years in college was not a waste. BINGO! This is exactly what I wanted to do. And <em>that </em>is how being a student affairs professional became a clear career path for me.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;Most people go to college because they want more money. And yes, a college degree can afford you that, but a college degree cannot afford you happiness. There are a lot of people that have degrees but don&#39;t have jobs or they have jobs they don&rsquo;t like. I want to repeat, a degree does not equal jobs and a degree doesn&#39;t always necessarily equal having a lot of money. As student affairs professionals, we don&#39;t make a lot of money at all and the majority of us have master&#39;s degrees; some even have doctoral degrees. For me, it&#39;s more about helping students. I wouldn&#39;t trade money for how it makes me feel, every day, when I see a student reach a goal or I see a student overcome an obstacle or when I see a student develop from their first year all the way to their senior year. That&#39;s not something that I would change for anything in the world. Make sure the degree you&rsquo;re going after is something that you&#39;re passionate about; not necessarily something that makes a ton of money. I guess if you&#39;re someone who really, really likes money, by all means go out there and make as much money as you can; but a career in student affairs is probably not for you.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Now it&rsquo;s time for the best part of college: Classes! Raise your hand if you love going to classes. I know a lot of you probably didn&rsquo;t raise your hand, and rightfully so. This is especially true during your first year, when the majority of classes you&#39;re in are not part of your major; many are prerequisites. You may notice a theme in the naming of these prerequisite classes, names like: <em>Intro to Psych</em> or <em>Intro to Human Diversity</em> or <em>Intro to Basket Weaving</em>. Regardless of the class name, take your classes seriously. The average student is probably paying $850.00 per credit class; that&#39;s about $2550.00 per individual class. I&rsquo;m sure if you have $2550.00 in your pocket right now, you&rsquo;re not going to waste it. In that first year of college, you will find that a lot of students skip their classes. If you&rsquo;re going to skip your classes, maybe you shouldn&rsquo;t be in college in the first place. I know for me, I don&rsquo;t have an extra $2550.00 to just throw out the window.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sometimes the classes you take are not the ones that you really want. Maybe you feel like your prerequisite classes are pointless and even annoying. You may end up learning information that you think you&rsquo;re never going to put to use. As student affairs professionals and for the parents reading this, we&#39;re not supposed to tell students that some of the information they&rsquo;re learning is basically worthless. There are going to be some classes that you&#39;re not going to use or benefit from, probably at any point in your life. Some of the classes are devised to help craft you into a better overall, global citizen. Take what you can from these classes and make the best of the situation. Then when you&rsquo;re in the classes you absolutely need, make sure to pay attention and ace those classes. Get that high G.P.A! Getting a high G.P.A. from the start of your college education is a huge gift. Think about it, it&rsquo;s definitely easier for you to get a high G.P.A. and keep it up than it would be to start low and have to raise it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>During your education, you will encounter a variety of different types of professors. My best advice: pay attention to what the professor requires and wants. It&rsquo;s all about the professor&rsquo;s practice. Some professors prefer it if you don&rsquo;t miss any classes, while others don&rsquo;t really mind if you come to class at all, and even others have the 3-day rule where you can&rsquo;t miss more than 3 classes. Some professors are open to students using their cell phones during class, some are not. Some allow students to call them by their first name, others prefer you call them by their last name or with Dr. in front of it. Some professors prefer you come to their office only during office hours to discuss concerns and issues, others are more flexible. Just know that every professor is not made equal. Your experience with one will not be the same as it is with another. I&#39;ve had great experiences with professors and I&#39;ve had bad experiences with professors.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I once had a professor named Dr. Benitez and she was amazing! She really pushed me to get to where I wanted to be. She allowed students to text her. She even allowed students to come to her home. She was very hands on and extremely interactive. Some professors do well with this type of communication with their students. These are the professors that you&rsquo;ll notice have incredible relationships with their students.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&rsquo;ve also had professors that were not so good. I once had a professor named Dr. Bertha and let me tell you she was miserable. Not only was she miserable, she wanted to make sure that you were miserable as well. She gave you assignments that were virtually impossible to complete successfully and then almost triumphed over handing out terrible grades on the assignment. If you spoke to her, as she entered the classroom, she didn&rsquo;t respond; the times that she actually did come to class. She interacted in a negative fashion with many students; particularly, male students and students of color. She had a reputation and it was not a positive reputation. Students simply did not like her. I don&#39;t think I learned too much from Dr. Bertha, but the one thing I did learn from her is that professors are not made equal. Ultimately, you have to give professors what they want, regardless if you agree or not; it&rsquo;s the end to a means.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Working with some professors can actually feel like &lsquo;academic hazing&rsquo;. It&rsquo;s as if they want you to learn every single factoid about the major they&rsquo;re affiliated with, when in reality, you&#39;re only partnered with them for one class. Make sure that you know what the expectations are from each professor. They are looking to you to satisfy those expectations and reach the common end goal for the class and that&rsquo;s your job! There are only a few finite rules when it comes to having a good relationship with your professors: complete whatever they&rsquo;ve assigned to you, do it in the way they&rsquo;ve asked and do it in the timeframe they&rsquo;ve requested. There are also certain remarks you shouldn&#39;t say to your professor. For example, if you miss a class, you probably shouldn&#39;t go up to your professor and say, &ldquo;Hey, did I miss anything important?&rdquo; Well of course you did! Everything taught in the classroom is important. Another important item to remember: take notice of the office hours for your professors. Professors usually post their hours on their doors. You never know when you might need to visit them.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Did you know that every single component that you need for a particular class is probably located in your class syllabus? The syllabus is usually given out on the first day of each class. Some upperclassmen may tell you to skip the first day of your class because it&#39;s just a syllabus class and it doesn&#39;t mean anything; that is so far from the truth. That first class is usually a quick class where your professor hands out pertinent class documents; including the most important, the <em>syllabus</em>. The documents and syllabus will equip you with everything that is required and expected of you for the rest of the semester. It includes the professor&rsquo;s policies and procedures. Learn and remember everything these documents provide. It&rsquo;s a good idea to go to that class because this is how you will learn what the rest of the semester will look like for that particular class.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Another thing you want to do: make sure the professor knows who you are. You can do this by showing up for that first class. Your relationship with your professor is so important. This relationship can also vary depending on the size of the school you&rsquo;re attending. If you&#39;re at a smaller school, there&rsquo;s a good chance you&rsquo;ll build a close relationships with your professor. Larger schools sometimes make that type of relationship a bit harder. Regardless of the type and size of the institution, you want to make sure that your professor knows who you are; whether that&#39;s by name or where you sit. This was easy <em>and </em>hard for me since I was one of the only students of color in my classes. If I had missed a class, it would&rsquo;ve been quite obvious I wasn&rsquo;t there.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I had some real and authentic relationships with some of my professors. We had a lot of great conversations about their class and my understanding of the content. One professor even took me out for a meal. I went to a smaller school and I was able to build those relationships. That is definitely a benefit of going to a smaller school. At a larger school, you can still benefit from having relationships with your professors, they just may be different than what I experienced at a smaller school. Your experience won&rsquo;t be the same as mine, but the bottom line is, build those relationships!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When I was in college, I didn&rsquo;t miss a single class. Some of you are probably thinking, aww man, look at him &ndash; goody-two-shoes; he didn&#39;t miss a class. Personally, I didn&rsquo;t want to waste my money and I know a lot of you probably don&#39;t want to waste your money either. I could&#39;ve stayed at home for free, so I wanted to make the most of the opportunity I was fortunate enough to have. You gotta do what you gotta do, and for me that was going to class since that&rsquo;s why I was attending college after all. I would love to tell you that I had an &ldquo;A&rdquo; in every single class but, unfortunately, that wasn&#39;t the case. In some classes, if I managed to get a &ldquo;B&rdquo;, I was okay with that. B&rsquo;s get degrees too! Of course, you should work as hard as you can to get an &ldquo;A&rdquo;, but a &ldquo;B&rdquo; is nothing to be ashamed of. If you&#39;re looking for more ways to reach that &ldquo;A&rdquo;, it&#39;s okay to have a conversation with your professor. Set up time with them and see if there&rsquo;s anything else you can do to reach that goal. Maybe you missed something. Maybe you didn&#39;t do well on a test. Maybe they&rsquo;ll allow you to redo the test. You&rsquo;ll never know your options unless you ask and asking is much easier if you have that relationship with your professor.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What kind of relationship do you think is acceptable to have with your professor? Should it be more personal or only professional? I&#39;ve seen and had a lot of different relationships with professors. Some professors, I had strictly professional relationships with. I said &ldquo;hi&rdquo; and &ldquo;bye&rdquo; and it was strictly business and most communication was done by email. I had some professors with whom I had really close relationships with. I&rsquo;d stop by during their office hours frequently.&nbsp; We would talk about family, the weather, and sports. I know some students in college that had sexual relationships with professors. I would strongly recommend staying away from those types of relationships. Those situations never stay quiet. Even if it appears that no one knows, everyone knows! If you are approached with that type of relationship offer, stay away! These situations never end well.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Trying to figure out if a particular professor is a good fit for you? One option you have is, talk to the upperclassmen. They will definitely give you <em>their </em>opinions on professors. Keep in mind, just because an upperclassman tells you that a professor is easy, doesn&#39;t mean that&#39;s the professor for you. You should continually be challenging yourself; easier does not mean better. Another option is, check out online resources such as: <a href=\"http://www.ratemyprofessors.com/\">http://www.ratemyprofessors.com/</a>&nbsp; This website will definitely provide different views and opinions on professors. The site will tell you the overall consensus pertaining to a class or professor or how the professor teaches. Of course, as with anything, don&rsquo;t use this website as your only deciding factor. There isn&rsquo;t a website around that will provide you truly unbiased opinions. There have been times when a student receives a bad grade or has hurt feelings relating to a professor or a particular class and they use the website as a forum to personally attack the professor. In the end, if you follow what the professor requires of you, you&rsquo;ll do fine.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>People have asked me, &ldquo;Justin, what was your favorite class while you were in college?&rdquo; or &ldquo;What was the weirdest thing that happened in your college experience?&rdquo; I&rsquo;d like to share a funny story with you. Senior year - final semester: I had to take a class called &lsquo;senior seminar&rsquo;. The general concept of &lsquo;senior seminar&rsquo; is to basically take everything you learned in college and now apply all that knowledge to this class. There are labs, a final presentation, an interview, and creating a resume; all to show that you are fit to go out into society and be a productive citizen. The end result is creating a portfolio. Our last assignment was to interview a professional person, out in the real, working world. We would conduct a mock interview with that person and they would grade us. All of these elements together would determine our final grade for the class. The person I was set to interview worked in a hospital. Even though she worked in a hospital, she had been a communications major and she was an alumni from my institution, so I figured this assignment would be a breeze.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I conducted my mock interview and I did very well. At the end of the mock interview, she shook my hand and said, &ldquo;You did a great job. Would you like to grab some lunch at Panera Bread?&rdquo; I said, &ldquo;Yeah, sure.&rdquo; She and I went to Panera Bread and the conversation was easy and interesting. At one point in the conversation, she asked me, &ldquo;So, do you know anybody from department A?&rdquo; and I said, &ldquo;Oh yeah. I know some people in that department.&rdquo; Now remember, even though I was a student, I had always been extremely involved in non-academia. I worked in the admissions office, in the P.R. office and in residence life, which meant I knew a lot of people who worked on campus in some capacity. She then said, &ldquo;Well, my husband works in that department, do you know him?&rdquo; I said, &ldquo;I think there are only two guys who work in that department. There&rsquo;s the one guy that smokes and then the other guy who doesn&#39;t have a left ear.&rdquo; (Yes, you read that right! This guy did not have a left ear. He was involved in some kind of accident when he was younger and literally lost his left ear.) She blurted out, &ldquo;<em>WHAT?</em>&rdquo; I repeated, &ldquo;There&rsquo;s a guy who doesn&#39;t have a left ear and there&rsquo;s a guy who smokes.&rdquo; She replied, &ldquo;Smokes? What do you mean smokes?&rdquo; I replied, &ldquo;There&rsquo;s a guy, with dark hair, who smokes cigarettes.&rdquo; She questioned, &ldquo;And he works in that department?&rdquo; and I responded, &ldquo;Ah, yeah. I work in that department, so I know him.&rdquo; She looks me right in the eye glaring at me. At this point, I&rsquo;m hesitantly looking back at her while she asks, &ldquo;Is his name David?&rdquo; I was like, &ldquo;Yeah, yeah, David. That&rsquo;s his name.&rdquo; She said, &ldquo;When was the last time you saw David smoke?&rdquo; At that moment, I knew I had done and/or said something that I shouldn&rsquo;t have. I said, &ldquo;Well, I haven&#39;t seen him recently.&rdquo; She smacked the table loudly and said, &ldquo;Dammit! You will tell me the last time you saw him smoke.&rdquo; I replied, &ldquo;Honestly lady, I don&#39;t know.&rdquo; She then opened up her phone, pulled out a picture of her husband and questions, &ldquo;Is this the guy you&#39;re talking about?&rdquo; It was definitely him so I stated, &ldquo;Yes.&rdquo; She said, &ldquo;I knew it! I knew it! I knew he was still smoking. He told me that he quit and he&#39;s been lying to me. I&rsquo;m going to set him straight right now!&rdquo; So, yes, while we&rsquo;re sitting in Panera Bread, post mock interview, as she&rsquo;s making a scene, she starts typing a text to her husband; showing me what she was typing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As this scene was unfolding before my eyes, I had decided I wasn&rsquo;t going to say anything else. Let&rsquo;s be honest, the reason I was sitting there with her was for a grade and I wanted a good grade! She texts her husband, &ldquo;You&rsquo;re still smoking, aren&#39;t you?&rdquo; He just sent a sad face back.&nbsp; She replied, &ldquo;We&rsquo;ll talk about this later!&rdquo; She grabbed the rest of her stuff, without giving me my grading sheet, and she walked out of Panera Bread. I quickly followed behind her and asked, &ldquo;Hey, hey, hey, wait a minute. Did I do well? Did I pass?&rdquo; She turned around, glared at me, got in her car and drove off.&nbsp; In the meantime, for the entire next week and a half I was terrified. I was afraid that I was going to fail this class all because of this issue that wasn&rsquo;t even my issue. Sure, I spilled the beans, but how was I to know? I thought, &lsquo;David should get an &ldquo;F&rdquo;! He&#39;s the one who lied to his wife and said he quit smoking! Why me? I didn&#39;t do this. How did I get to this point in my education only to fail senior seminar?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At the end of senior seminar, we had to do a final presentation in front of a panel of our peers and the person that interviewed us. I figured she wasn&rsquo;t going to show up, but she did. I walked right up to her and said, &ldquo;Hi. How are you?&rdquo; In a very soft voice, she said, &ldquo;Hello.&rdquo; I replied, &ldquo;You never gave me my grading sheet.&rdquo; She looked up at me, smiled and said, &ldquo;I know.&rdquo; She then handed me the grading sheet and there was an &ldquo;A&rdquo; on it. I inquired about what happened with her situation and she said she didn&rsquo;t want to talk about it. I said, &ldquo;That&#39;s fine.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Honestly, as a student, that whole scenario freaked me out! I&rsquo;m telling you this story for a reason. Why? You need to know: Not everything will go according to your plan, choosing classes and making and sticking to a schedule is not easy. There is going to be a time when you embarrassingly walk into the wrong class or even enroll in the wrong class all together. College isn&rsquo;t some cookie cutter event. It&rsquo;s fluid, always in motion and forever changing and while it&rsquo;s changing, you&#39;re changing with it. The students change and the culture changes. When the culture changes, it directly affects everything around a college campus and you&rsquo;ll need to be able to change, learn and grow with it. Use the knowledge and wisdom you&#39;ve been acquiring since you were a child. This will help you navigate within the ever changing college setting.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For parents: Don&rsquo;t try to relive your dreams through your child. Allow them to figure it out. Allow them to succeed <em>and </em>fail <em>and </em>support them while they&#39;re doing it. Let them choose the major that they&rsquo;re interested in. Guide them and advise them but let them make the final decision. Let your child grow and evolve!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For students: Show up for your classes and make the most out of each one! The reason you&rsquo;re in college is to pursue an education. Take notes, take a lot of notes! Buy those expensive textbooks and keep them. At the end of your college experience, you&#39;ll have a nice library full of academic books. Keep those books, take notes in them, write in them. I know, the majority of you are going to sell your books back and there&rsquo;s nothing wrong with that. If you don&rsquo;t want the books, then get that money! You can utilize the university bookstore or a variety of websites designed just for this purpose. Don&rsquo;t forget to do a price match to see who will pay the most for your book. Choose a major that will land you a career in a field you&rsquo;re passionate about and develop lasting relationships with your professors.</p>', '2020-09-07 22:39:16', '2020-09-11 00:01:17', NULL);
INSERT INTO `chapters` (`id`, `course_id`, `name`, `image`, `amount`, `details`, `created_at`, `updated_at`, `deleted_at`) VALUES
(23, 6, 'Hey Bartender, Another Please!', NULL, 20, '<p>In case you didn&rsquo;t know, alcohol is extremely prevalent on college campuses. You can see this fact portrayed through the media, social media and movies like Neighbors, Superbad or Old School. Alcohol is a huge topic and an even bigger issue on most college campuses. When you go to visit most colleges, they&#39;ll say that their campus is dry. What they&rsquo;re really saying is that their campus is the wettest-dry campus that exists. That said, you will also find that everybody&#39;s experience does not include alcohol. Take me for example, I didn&#39;t drink when I was in college. I had a full scholarship and I didn&#39;t want to mess that up. For some students reading this text, this may be your situation. If you have a scholarship, providing you the opportunity to go to school,&nbsp; one night of drinking is not worth losing your scholarship over. For other students, this may not be the case.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It doesn&#39;t matter if administrators say you&rsquo;re not allowed to drink. Students do it anyway. It doesn&#39;t matter if your parents give you the rundown of things that the consequences of drinking have on campus: don&#39;t get an underage drinking charge, don&#39;t get cited, don&#39;t get arrested...students still do it. It seems to be a necessary evil of campus culture. When students go to school, we ask them, &ldquo;What are your expectations of college? What do you think happens on campus?&rdquo; They usually reply, &ldquo;Party, party, party!&rdquo; Students come, they get wasted, they go to fraternity and sorority parties, they get kegs, the whole nine. People are going to drink, you can&rsquo;t stop it. Some student&rsquo;s rooms appear to have more alcohol than your local bar. This is all very common in the campus culture. It&rsquo;s the first time most of these kids are away from their parents. All of those things that they weren&rsquo;t allowed to do at home, they can now do, while in college. Parents aren&rsquo;t around! It&rsquo;s their first taste of freedom. Students are finally getting to explore life, on their own terms.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I said earlier that alcohol consumption is a huge issue; especially because most students don&rsquo;t know how to &lsquo;drink properly&rsquo;. We find that students are indulging in heavy drinking and doing it in a short amount of time. They&#39;re not drinking water while they&#39;re doing it. They&#39;re not consuming food beforehand. They&rsquo;re mixing different types of alcohol and once they start drinking for the night, they&#39;re not taking any breaks. They are basically, for the most part, amateurs when it comes to indulging in alcohol. They&rsquo;re getting trashed often and quickly! They don&#39;t know how to just get a nice buzz; they&rsquo;re getting drunk and not being safe about it. BAC (blood alcohol content) numbers are through the roof and poor decisions are being made while they&rsquo;re under the influence of alcohol.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Think about this fact, some students are already pros at drinking alcohol by the time they even come to college. You&rsquo;re saying to yourself, &ldquo;Justin, how are they a pro when they&rsquo;re just entering college? What, are they drinking in high school?&rdquo; My answer would be, &ldquo;Yes they are. Students are drinking way before the legal drinking age.&rdquo; I believe this happens one of two ways: there&rsquo;s alcohol consumption that takes place in high schools (yes parents, your high school student is probably drinking alcohol) and there are students who are learning drinking behaviors at home. There are kids who are actually drinking with their parents. And of course, there are some kids who are raiding their parents bar. Some parents have no problem with their kids drinking as long as they stay at home and they hand over their car keys. So yeah, some of these kids show up at college already pro-drinkers. Since they&rsquo;re already pro-drinkers, they set out to show their peers what drinking is all about.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When parents drink with their underage kids, it can send a negative message. It definitely sends the complete opposite message that we, as staff, are trying to teach and instill in them. If parents are saying that it&rsquo;s okay to drink at home, then they feel it&rsquo;s okay to go off to college and drink. This can become problematic for student affairs professionals because we are attempting to provide a different message to students.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Our message is more along the lines of, we want you to be global citizens, we want and expect you to be able to follow the law and respect the rules. It&rsquo;s a thin line because the students come back to the staff saying, &ldquo;Well, I drink at home with my parents, so it&#39;s not a big deal.&rdquo; or &ldquo;My parents allow me to drink, so it&#39;s okay.&rdquo; In the meantime, we&rsquo;re trying to hip students to the alcohol culture, reasonable ways to drink or more successful methods of monitoring their alcohol consumption and these students don&rsquo;t want to hear it. They think that they already know the deal. These learned behaviors can also hinder our attempts in helping students to understand their BAC levels. BAC levels can be altered by a multitude of variables, such as: gender, weight, how much you ate during that day, how much you drank, the time frame in which you consumed the alcohol, how much is in a cup or in a shot or in a bottle, as well as the potency of the alcohol or the alcohol proof. There are a lot of factors that can change your BAC. Unfortunately, we&rsquo;re noticing a trend right now and we&rsquo;re seeing extremely high BAC levels.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When students are in my office for judicial conferences (a judicial conference is a meeting that students have with a university official when they violate policy), I&rsquo;m seeing excessively high BAC levels. The judicial conferences come with a police report and a detailed narrative of the events that took place during the occurrence. Students come and meet with a university administrator to talk about the situation. The administrator&rsquo;s responsibility is to review the files and determine whether or not a student has violated the code of conduct policy. This is a prime time when we&rsquo;re seeing extremely high BAC levels, sometimes as high as a 2.1. All 50 states have now set .08% blood alcohol concentration (BAC) as the legal limit for driving under the influence (DUI) or driving while impaired (DWI). For commercial drivers, a BAC of .04% can result in a DUI or DWI conviction nationwide. In my office, over the course of ten years, I&rsquo;ve seen BAC levels of 2.5. That&#39;s definitely way over the legal drinking limit. These students aren&rsquo;t just getting drunk, they&#39;re getting wasted! Later in this chapter, I&rsquo;ll share some anonymous stories about a few students and situations related to over-intoxication.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Drinking on campus also depends on what institution you go to. Some state schools don&#39;t allow their students to drink on campus because it&#39;s a legitimate, dry campus.. Some private schools do allow it. They own the land where the school resides and they allow their students to drink in the residence halls. This is something you definitely want to look at when you&#39;re applying to different schools. The student code of conduct and the policies in which they govern their institution can also be very different. People ask me, &ldquo;Justin, it&#39;s crazy to think that students think this is a culture. Alcohol was taken way seriously when I went to school. I would&rsquo;ve thought, in this day and age, that it would be taken even more seriously and students would be drinking less.&rdquo; I would argue that they are not drinking less.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I think there&#39;s a variety of reasons why students are drinking alcohol; especially consuming large amounts of alcohol at a quick rate. I think that one of the biggest reasons why students are drinking so much alcohol is that they want to make friends and fit in with their peers. Coming to college is an enormous transition; you leave your family behind, your siblings, your friends and the only life you&rsquo;ve known. I think this alone is an immense component to our survival as a human species; we want to be able to feel like we belong, that we&rsquo;re liked, that we have a voice that people care about us and want to be around us. Making friends is probably the most important goal when transitioning into the college life. If there are students coming in, who are already drinking, they&rsquo;ll fit in quicker. Other students will want that same feeling of belonging.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We notice that when students feel like they don&rsquo;t fit in or belong, they think, &ldquo;Look, everybody else is drinking. Why don&#39;t I just drink? I&rsquo;ll make more friends that way. At least I&rsquo;ll be involved with other people in the college community. That&#39;s the way for me to feel as though I&#39;m included in what&rsquo;s going on around me.&rdquo; Students may also be drinking out of sheer boredom - where students just don&#39;t have anything to do because they&#39;re not getting involved in campus activities. Some students may start partaking in drinking due to peer pressure. I can remember, when I was in school, people couldn&rsquo;t believe that I didn&rsquo;t drink. They immediately asked, &ldquo;Is it because of your religious beliefs?&rdquo; or &ldquo;Is it because someone in your family has a drinking problem?&rdquo; or &ldquo;Is it because you just don&#39;t want to drink?&rdquo; I usually replied, &ldquo;I tried it before, didn&#39;t like it, don&#39;t like the taste. I don&#39;t drink.&rdquo; I found that as someone who didn&rsquo;t drink, I kind of felt like an oddball or an outsider.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We call people &ldquo;basic&rdquo; if they do the same things that everyone else in mainstream society is doing. Like, basic people just do basic things; they wear the same things, they do the same things, they follow all the trends and crazes. People who don&rsquo;t follow mainstream are considered different, weird or abnormal. This is what it&rsquo;s like on a college campus too. Peer pressure, to fit in, is definitely a big issue. There may be some students who are socially awkward; they just don&#39;t know how to immerse themselves into big group settings. Alcohol gives them the ability to open up. I understand this; it makes a lot of sense. For me, I&#39;m an extrovert. You can put me in front of a room with 100 people and I&#39;ll try to command the room. But, I have friends and colleagues who are the complete opposite and they feel like they need a drink or two in order to open up, to start a conversation. They get a little anxious or a little nervous being around a lot of people. The feelings and effects from alcohol allow them to lower their inhibitions and not worry so much about what other people may think. There are also people who drink because they don&rsquo;t want to feel. They want to escape pain, misery or trauma in their life.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s a definite that kids are going through a lot in this day and age. Many of our students are coming to college with serious issues. Issues dealing with their family, background, finances, mental health, anxiety, drug and alcohol abuse are some issues our students face. They&#39;re bringing that baggage, from home, with them to campus. Some issues may start once kids get to college, but a lot developed before they arrived. Students are arriving on college campuses with their suitcase full of clothes and another suitcase full of issues. Sometimes when I&#39;m talking with students and I ask them, &ldquo;Why are you drinking?&rdquo; or &ldquo;Why did you drink so much?&rdquo; students respond with a variety of different answers: &ldquo;I&#39;m drinking because my parents are getting divorced. &ldquo;or &ldquo;I&rsquo;m drinking because I just went through a bad breakup.&rdquo; or &ldquo;I&#39;m drinking because I did poorly on a test and I really need to maintain a 3.8 GPA so I don&rsquo;t get kicked out.&rdquo; or &ldquo;I just needed an escape.&rdquo; These reasons aren&rsquo;t all that different from a grown adult who drinks, but it&rsquo;s different with the students because we would like them to learn alternative ways of coping with stress and difficult situations.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I think that some students have an inaccurate understanding regarding &ldquo;acceptable reasons&rdquo; to drink while in college. I mentioned some of the reasons students have given me when it comes to why they drink. Most of those reasons have to do with stress and coping. There&rsquo;s a whole other rationale for college drinking that I also hear about from students. They say things like, &ldquo;It&rsquo;s college man, that&#39;s what you&#39;re supposed to do&rdquo; or &ldquo;Live it up, you only live once&rdquo; or &ldquo;My parents aren&rsquo;t here.&rdquo; The students feel that part of coming to college includes getting plastered, partying and having fun. Yes, drinking is a part of college life for many students, but drinking responsibly is important. Drinking to have fun and also being safe is crucial.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Students are doing idiotic, irresponsible things because they&rsquo;re not drinking sensibly. We&rsquo;ve heard of students playing drinking games which result in drinking massive amounts of alcohol; like three red solo cups of vodka. That&rsquo;s just too much and it&rsquo;s crazy! Students are ending up in the hospital or ending up arrested or passed out or blacking out. This is putting them in tremendous danger and it&rsquo;s scary! Some students just like the thrill of breaking the law or the thrill of disobeying their parents. I&rsquo;ve had students tell me, &ldquo;My parents gave me this big old speech about why not to drink and I don&#39;t need to hear it from you, too.&rdquo; or &ldquo;Part of the reason why I drink is to spite my parents; they didn&#39;t let me do anything when I was at home.&rdquo; or &ldquo;My parents were very, very strict and now they&#39;re not here; don&rsquo;t judge!&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Let&rsquo;s move on to a story or two involving some students that I remember doing or saying things that were memorable to me. I remember being a resident assistant on campus and having to sit at the front desk for some shifts. Let me tell you, when you sit at the front desk being a resident assistant, you see some crazy things.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>One of the stories that I remember very well is: A student got so drunk that he walked into one of his neighbor&#39;s houses and stole their dog. That&rsquo;s right, the student went into his neighbor&rsquo;s house, leashed the neighbor&#39;s dog and brought it to the residence hall. What I found interesting about this situation is that the student didn&#39;t live in that particular residence hall. The student was an upperclassman and must have lived in that residence hall in years past, but now lived off-campus. Because he was so drunk, he thought that that&#39;s where he lived. I remember coming up to the window and him saying to me, &ldquo;Hey, I lost my key and I can&#39;t get into the residence hall.&rdquo; I looked down at his feet and saw a Labrador Retriever and I said, &ldquo;You can&#39;t bring that dog into the building.&rdquo; He said, &ldquo;Oh no&hellip;it&rsquo;s okay, he lives here with me.&rdquo; I said, &ldquo;No, no, no he does not live here. There are no dogs allowed here.&rdquo; At the time, service dogs or emotional support pets weren&rsquo;t a big thing yet; even seeing eye dogs weren&rsquo;t that prevalent then. You could tell that this dog wasn&rsquo;t a guide or service dog. You could see that the guy was extremely intoxicated. I told him to have a seat and someone would be there shortly to help him. Unfortunately, I had to call the police because that&#39;s what resident assistants are advised to do.&nbsp; I remember we sat there and talked and I asked him a few questions. I said, &ldquo;Where were you tonight?&rdquo; He said, &ldquo;Oh, I came from one of the fraternity houses in town.&rdquo; I replied, &ldquo;Okay. Did you drink there?&rdquo; He responded, &ldquo;Yeah man. It was a great party.&rdquo; I was like, &ldquo;That&#39;s awesome.&rdquo; He said, &ldquo;I just found this dog while I was walking the streets.&rdquo; I said, &ldquo;WHAT?!&rdquo; He said, &ldquo;Yeah man. I was walking and saw this dog was all by himself and I was by myself, so we decided to become friends.&rdquo; He looks at the dog and starts talking to the dog, saying, &ldquo;Hey, you&#39;re a good boy. It&#39;s okay, we&#39;re almost home.&rdquo; Thankfully, the dog was very friendly. The dog was licking him and it seemed like they knew each other and were friends. Eventually the police came on the scene and they handled the situation. They later found out that there was also a local report that someone had broken into a house and stolen a Labrador retriever. Well, this was the guy. Eventually he was arrested and escorted out of the building.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Why did I tell you this story? I ended up bumping into this guy later in the school year. We were both in the library. Since I&rsquo;m a silly kind of guy, when this situation happened earlier in the year, I had taken some pictures of him; just for fun, like a keepsake of the night. I said to him, &ldquo;Dude, you were in my building the day you got arrested.&rdquo; He said, &ldquo;Yeah man. I don&#39;t know what happened. I was so out of it.&rdquo; I replied, &ldquo;Look dude, I took pictures of you.&rdquo; I showed him the pictures and he laughed and said, &ldquo;I can&#39;t believe I did that. I don&#39;t even know whose dog it was.&rdquo; I asked him, &ldquo;Well what happened?&rdquo; He said, &ldquo;Man, I just drank so much I don&#39;t even know what happened that night.&rdquo; Don&rsquo;t you think that&rsquo;s a scary situation to be in? While it&rsquo;s silly about him stealing a dog and thinking the dog was his and trying to get back into his old residence hall, this is not <em>just</em> a &ldquo;funny&rdquo; situation, it&rsquo;s also very serious.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&#39;s definitely not funny when people get behind the wheel of a car and make the decision to drive drunk or when students are handling weapons like knives or lighters and they end up cutting themselves or burning something. Student injury due to alcohol consumption happens and it happens often. Students are leaving parties and walking home, tripping and falling and injuring themselves to the extent of hospitalization. They may even find themselves attempting to get into bed and they end up falling out of their bed and getting injured. Then there are the instances when a student does something that results in a major issue, like in the following story.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I remember a student who was so drunk that they passed out in their shower. Since the student was in the shower, no one came to check in on them because they thought someone was just <em>in </em>the shower. Unfortunately, the person had passed out in the shower. The only reason that anyone knew something was wrong was because the shower ran all night and the water from the shower seeped down into the next floor and flooded the building. After everyone evacuated, we had to &ldquo;key into&rdquo; the room. We found the student passed-out in the shower. The student was immediately sent to the hospital. The student could&rsquo;ve drowned, or worse.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Again, these are extreme cases when it comes to intoxication. I can say that in most instances, students go to off-campus parties, they drink, they make their way back to campus and everything is fine; but sometimes, that&rsquo;s not how the story goes. I remember another student who was in the lobby waiting for her friends and she was extremely drunk. At the time, at this institution, the policy stated that as long as the person wasn&rsquo;t a safety risk to themselves or others, we wouldn&rsquo;t call the police. I remember looking over at her and she started screaming. I had no idea why she was screaming; everything seemed fine. She stood up and I saw that she had peed herself. How do you get so drunk that you can&#39;t control your own bladder? That&rsquo;s really bad!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Students should understand that drinking alcohol can have consequences. If you&rsquo;re going to drink, do it responsibly and safely. If you plan on drinking, even if your parents have expressed that they would prefer you not to, I would encourage you to have a plan. Only drink with people you know and trust; people who will make sure you&rsquo;re okay and will have your back. If a group is all going out at one time, make sure you all come back together. Make a decision, before you go out, as to how much you&rsquo;re going to drink. If you see a friend and they&#39;re too drunk, tell them, &ldquo;It&rsquo;s time to go home.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you&#39;re traveling to a party in a car, make sure that you have a trustworthy designated driver. DD&rsquo;s are super important. I usually find in most groups that there&rsquo;s one person who doesn&rsquo;t drink or doesn&rsquo;t drink much. My advice would be: never get behind the wheel of a car if you&rsquo;ve had <em>any </em>alcohol to drink, even a sip is too much; it&rsquo;s not worth the risk. Be safe and make good decisions. When you&rsquo;re out and about, you not only have to worry about yourself, but you also have to worry about your friends and others around you. If you know you&rsquo;re going to drink, make sure you eat something. You don&rsquo;t have to go out of your way to have a full meal, but have something in your stomach, before you start drinking. You can&#39;t drink on an empty stomach. If you&rsquo;re out drinking, make sure you take breaks in between drinks. Don&rsquo;t just slam drinks continuously. In between alcoholic drinks, supplement with water or juice. My last piece of advice would be to know your limits! Some people can drink a lot and good for them, but your body may not react the same way. You don&rsquo;t have to keep up, drink-for-drink, with your friends. It&rsquo;s not a competition.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Here&rsquo;s another story and this one is pretty scary. This story involves a student who was so drunk she didn&rsquo;t know where she was. I was on duty one night and the student was arrested due to public intoxication. At this particular institution, when students got arrested and later brought back to the residence hall, it was the resident director&rsquo;s job to follow up with them the next day; just to check in and see how they were doing. Since she was arrested on a night when I was on duty, I knew I needed to follow-up with a call in the morning. I got her cell phone number and I called a few times, but there was no answer. I also called her room phone, but again, there was no answer. I decided since she wasn&rsquo;t answering, I would take a walk over to her residence hall. When I arrived at the residence hall, I found her room and knocked on her door. Her roommate answered the door. I asked if the student was there and the roommate said, &ldquo;No. I haven&rsquo;t seen her since last night. She was going to a party, but I haven&rsquo;t seen her since she left for the party.&rdquo; I said, &ldquo;Hmmm. That&rsquo;s really odd because Campus Public Safety informed me that the student was brought back to campus.&rdquo; I then called Public Safety and they informed me that the student had been brought back to the hall at 2:20 a.m. I thought this was a bit odd. The student had been brought back to her hall and now wasn&rsquo;t anywhere to be found. No one had seen her and she still wasn&rsquo;t answering her cell phone. At this point, I did what most normal people would do, I went into detective mode trying to find the missing student. Luckily, at this institution, we were able to view the security cameras from the building.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When I viewed the footage, I clearly saw Public Safety bring the student back and take her to her room. I watched the camera for another 5-10 minutes and then saw the student exit her room and exit the building. I thought, &ldquo;Hmm. Maybe she went to a friend&rsquo;s dorm.&rdquo; I went back and talked to the roommate again and the roommate said, &ldquo;No, she doesn&rsquo;t have any friends in another building.&rdquo; Now I was really worried! I called Public Safety again and they suggested that I call the borough police. Fortunately, when I called the borough police, they had the information I needed. They said they had located this student in the early morning hours. She was still drunk and now, not only had she been arrested by Campus Public Safety, she was later arrested by the borough police. The borough police informed me that the student was currently in the hospital. Her parents were trying to make their way across the state to get her. While I was on the phone with the police, I received a call from the student in the hospital. She said, &ldquo;Hello. Who is this?&rdquo; I informed her as to why I had been calling; to make sure she was okay. I asked her, &ldquo;Do you remember what took place last night?&rdquo; The student replied, &ldquo;I remember going to a party and then I woke up in the hospital.&rdquo; As the student and I talked, we tried to put the pieces together and we figured out that she had been drugged. That&#39;s another issue that comes up with students drinking on or off campus.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Be aware of your surroundings! Safety should be a priority. Know who you&rsquo;re drinking with and know who you&rsquo;re hanging out with. A good safety tip for students who choose to drink: keep your drink with you at all times. Don&rsquo;t ever accept an open drink from someone, pour it yourself.&nbsp; When the student from the last story ended up in the hospital, they did a toxicology test and while her BAC was high, there was another drug in her system. It was determined that she was definitely drugged. It&rsquo;s a tough way to learn a lesson. She just wanted to go out and have some fun, which she should be doing in college. She never expected, at the end of the night, she would end up drugged. Make sure you know who you&#39;re partying with and where you&rsquo;re partying because not everybody will have your best interest in mind.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Overall, we&rsquo;re just trying to keep your children to be as safe as possible. We hear a lot of people say, &ldquo;Well it&#39;s okay, just sleep it off.&rdquo; Sometimes sleeping it off is not the best option for a student. If they&#39;re so intoxicated that they sleep it off in a strange place, that could be dangerous. If they&rsquo;re sleeping it off and are laying the wrong way and they vomit and choke, that&rsquo;s definitely dangerous. Use common sense if you have to sleep it off. Better yet, surround yourself with people you trust and this won&rsquo;t be an issue.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you&#39;re a student and you&#39;re reading this, where do you get help if you need it? Let&rsquo;s say you&#39;re too drunk and you don&#39;t know what to do. Call Public Safety or go to the counseling center. Most campuses have safety boxes located throughout the campus. You can press the button on one of these boxes and immediately get some help. If you need a list of other resources, your institutions can provide a list.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I remember a student at one institution that I worked at who was so drunk that she pressed the emergency box button and was talking to Public Safety about how drunk she was and how much fun she had at the party. Unfortunately, she called Public Safety on herself, but at least she was safe and got help. She didn&rsquo;t mean to call Public Safety; she just saw a beautiful light that was flashing when she pressed the button. Lucky for her, Public Safety was able to find her within thirty seconds.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Remember the story I told you about the girl who peed her pants? Well let me tell you, that is not the only peeing situation I&rsquo;ve been privy to. I don&rsquo;t know why this is an issue, but it is. Students are peeing and not in the bathroom where it belongs! I remember these two roommates who were fighting because one of the roommates would get so drunk and then come home and just pee all over his roommate&rsquo;s stuff. Now, raise your hands with me, right now, if you would be absolutely furious if you came home and all your belongings were wet and smelled like pee? That&rsquo;s why these two roommates had beef. The first time it happened, I was able to bring the two roommates in for a talk, we discussed the situation and cleared it up. When it happened for the 2nd and 3rd time, it wasn&rsquo;t as easy to resolve the situation. At that point, as a resident director, I had to try to figure out the best solution for this situation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>That same day, I had another situation with a student in another hall who also had a roommate who was peeing on all of their stuff. The funniest part of the peeing situations, was the solution that we ended up with. We brought all four students together for a discussion. It was decided to put the two students who were peeing on their roommate&rsquo;s stuff, in the same room&hellip;together; that way they could swap swords and not bother anyone else. I remember one night, after putting the peeing roommates together, one of the roommates peed on their new peeing roommate&rsquo;s stuff. He later came back to me and said, &ldquo;You know Justin, I can totally understand why my old roommate was so upset with me. Now my stuff got peed on last night and it was not cool!&rdquo; I said, &ldquo;Yeah. You all are going to have to make better decisions and choices about what you&rsquo;re doing.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If I haven&#39;t told you before, I&#39;m a resident director on a university campus. I live and work on a campus. I oversee a building of 700 students. It is a very fascinating job and life! It&rsquo;s like being in a nature documentary. You get to observe students&rsquo; living habits, eating habits, bathing and hygiene habits, and (brief shudder) mating habits. I even get to see some of their tribal rituals &ndash; meaning when their herd moves. Essentially, that&#39;s on a Thirsty Thursday when I see a group of 60 students all leaving the building at one time, at 11:00pm...with their backpacks on. I guess they are going to the library and I&rsquo;m witnessing their migration patterns. Being a resident director and living amongst the students has been one of the most beneficial opportunities presented to me. You get to see your student&rsquo;s development from the first day that they move in, until they leave. The students that leave are so much different then the students that first arrived. Being a resident director is an extremely interesting job; every day is guaranteed to be different.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Another trend that I&rsquo;m seeing is the college alcohol culture creating issues for students once they graduate. We&rsquo;re starting to see that some of our students are drinking so much while they&rsquo;re in college that they&rsquo;re becoming full-fledged alcoholics. Once they graduate, their habits and behaviors just continue. I have a friend who has been sober for about three years now, but she had a huge issue with alcohol that started in college. Here she was, out in the adult world and alcohol had become a real problem in her life. In her mind, Thursday, Friday and Saturday were drinking days. Now, out of college, she had a job and worked on Friday&rsquo;s. This meant she couldn&rsquo;t drink hard on Thursday nights if she wanted to get up for work on time the next morning. She had trouble with this because for four years, that was her behavior; Thursday, Friday, Saturday = drink time!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We can clearly see that these behaviors can have long term effects. Students are unable to smoothly transition back into reality and more importantly, into functional young adult reality. A reality where drinking every day isn&rsquo;t an option and even drinking heavily on the weekends may not be a feasible option. Life changes; jobs happen. There are family and friends to think about and responsibilities to take care of. Not to mention that as you get older, your drinking habits will change organically. You won&rsquo;t be able to &ldquo;hang&rdquo; as long or as often and you probably won&rsquo;t be able to drink as much.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are other factors that come into play when we&rsquo;re talking about alcohol. Alcohol dependency can be an issue for students. They may drink to cope with stress or depression or even homesickness. Like any coping mechanism, this can result in dependency. Using alcohol to mask or lessen certain feelings that they don&rsquo;t know how to handle can end badly. Alcohol may seem like an easy solution, but it&rsquo;s not. In today&rsquo;s campus culture, there are a variety of programs and options on how to deal with stress, depression and anxiety. Most people aren&rsquo;t taught how to cope with stress and they end up looking for a quick fix. They&#39;re not looking to try yoga or meditation to improve the situation. They&rsquo;re not thinking about exercise, activity or eating right; all methods on helping ease stress, depression and anxiety. They&rsquo;re turning to alcohol, to numb the pain, instead. Coping mechanisms aren&rsquo;t really taught at a young age. As a child or young adult, you are sure to pick up on ways that others handle situations, but until you&rsquo;re in that stressful situation, you don&rsquo;t really know how you&rsquo;ll handle it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In this culture, some people don&#39;t even recognize alcohol as an issue. I remember walking into a residence hall once with a dad and a son on move-in day who were sitting back, enjoying a drink together; like it was the most normal and natural ending to move-in day. When I spoke with the son, and unfortunately the police, about the situation and why it wasn&rsquo;t okay on campus, the father had an issue with it. He said, &ldquo;How can you fine my son for this? This is a tradition. My grandfather drank with my dad before he started college and my dad drank with me before I started college; this is what I&#39;m doing with my son.&rdquo; We then had to explain the details of the university student code of conduct. I also said to him, &ldquo;I&#39;m sorry, the behaviors you&#39;re exhibiting right now and your support of under-age drinking, is just unacceptable.&rdquo; It&rsquo;s not about shaming people, it&rsquo;s more about informing people so they can make better decisions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Speaking of shaming, let&rsquo;s talk about the &ldquo;walk of shame&rdquo; or the &ldquo;stride of pride.&rdquo; These terms and behaviors are popular among students. Some students drink and then don&#39;t want to leave and go back to their residence hall. If you think about this in regard to safety, it isn&rsquo;t actually a bad thing. If you&#39;re going to drink and there&rsquo;s an option to stay the night, stay! If you drank too much, instead of trying to make your way back to your hall drunk, sleep it off, wake up the next morning and go home then. Attempting to get home while intoxicated could increase your chances of injury and definitely increases your risk level when it comes to being involved in a negative alcohol related situation. Not sure if staying put for the night classifies as a walk of shame, but it&rsquo;s certainly worth mentioning. When it comes to the walk of shame or the stride of pride, you should know that when you come back to campus, people will judge.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I remember at one of the institutions I worked at, my on-campus residence had a porch. On Saturday mornings, I would get up really early and I would make breakfast or buy donuts and I would sit on my porch and watch the students coming home from the night before. I would talk to them and ask things like,&nbsp; &ldquo;Hey, how was your night last night?&rdquo; People would come up and talk to me and reply, &ldquo;Man, last night was crazy!!!&rdquo; I would say, &ldquo;Hey, looks like you had a rough night, would you like a donut?&rdquo; Some people wouldn&rsquo;t speak to me at all, but they would give me the middle finger. Some people would just say, &ldquo;That smells really good; can I have some?&rdquo; I would reply, &ldquo;Yeah, of course.&rdquo; People would come over and chat. I would buy enough hot chocolate and donuts for everybody to enjoy. That was my opportunity to talk to students about what they were up to and the decisions they were making. Drinking alcohol doesn&rsquo;t make you a bad person. This chapter isn&rsquo;t meant to be pro-alcohol or anti-alcohol, it&rsquo;s meant to give people a general idea about alcohol from both sides.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If I could meet with students in a non-disciplinary setting, students might be able to trust me more when it comes to having those real intentional conversations about alcohol, I feel like I could make a bigger difference. As far as disciplinary situations, some students have no remorse. Most of the time when students are coming to me for judicial conferences, they&#39;re sitting with me and they&#39;re talking to me; saying things like, &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t even care.&rdquo; If I ask them if they&rsquo;re going to drink again, they usually reply, &ldquo;Yeah, most likely.&rdquo; I try to give tips and for some students, they really soak up all the information I give them; other students, they simply don&#39;t care. They say, &ldquo;I&#39;m just going to do my time. I&#39;m not going to get caught.&rdquo; Look, I get it. You&rsquo;re a young adult. You&rsquo;re trying to make your own decisions. You&rsquo;re trying to be your own person. Sometimes bending the law, but not necessarily breaking the law, can be thrilling and exciting. We really want students to avoid situations that result in judicial conferences. Our hope is that students want to make better choices and to be responsible, while having fun. If students can do this, they&#39;ll have a much better experience.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Here are a few tips for students and parents.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tips for students:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Be yourself! If you&#39;re going into school right now, you might not know yourself yet, but you will soon. I actually know some adults who still don&#39;t know themselves. Being in college is the perfect time to figure out who you are and who you want to be and why.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Follow the law! Laws are set for a reason. Look, as someone who occasionally likes to do things that technically bend the law to have fun, I&rsquo;m telling you that the law is put in place for a reason and shouldn&rsquo;t be broken.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Drink wisely! We&rsquo;ve talked about this throughout the chapter. Make sure that you&#39;re not doing things that are going to be detrimental to you now or in your future.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Be smart! Rely on your friends. If you can&#39;t rely on your friends, rely on public safety. I&rsquo;m sure some people are thinking, &ldquo;Why would I ever call public safety or the police on myself? That&rsquo;s crazy!&rdquo; At the end the day, you never want to be in a situation that turns bad, if you can help it. If you are an intentional bystander and can get someone the help they need, do it! In some states, they have an amnesty clause where if you call the police to help someone and you were also drinking, there won&rsquo;t be negative ramifications for you. Honestly, we just want the students to have fun but also have a life the next day. It&rsquo;s pretty important that you do your part to ensure that everybody&rsquo;s being safe.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;Unfortunately, some students have to learn the hard way. I&#39;m going to say this, &ldquo;DON&rsquo;T LEARN THE HARD WAY!&rdquo; Every student thinks it&rsquo;s not going to be them; it may be them, it might be YOU! It may have already been you and you&rsquo;re reminiscing right now as I tell these stories. You may be thinking to yourself, &ldquo;Man, if I could do this over.&rdquo; or &ldquo;If I had just done this, I wouldn&rsquo;t have gotten caught!&rdquo; or &ldquo;If I had just stayed put, Public Safety wouldn&rsquo;t have picked me up.&rdquo; It doesn&rsquo;t have to be so difficult! You know the rules, you know the policies so try to abide by them. If you&rsquo;re going to break the rules, be smart about it. Have good friends that will be there to tell you when you&rsquo;re out of hand. Ask an upperclassmen, they&#39;ll tell you the rules and tricks to make sure that you&#39;re safe and you&#39;re drinking responsibly. Your friends should be the ones that are around you when you&#39;re drinking.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Now for those individuals who want to have fun and drink alcohol and you&rsquo;re not phased by anything I&rsquo;ve said, that&rsquo;s okay, I didn&rsquo;t write this to scare you. This chapter was meant to provide information for everyone and from both sides. I know a lot of people who go out, have a few drinks and that&rsquo;s it; it&#39;s all good. They go home and they get up in the morning like nothing happened. That&rsquo;s responsible drinking. If more people could do that, it would be perfect. Nothing&rsquo;s wrong with getting a little buzz on! Nothing&#39;s wrong with you going out and having a good time. Nothing&#39;s wrong with any of that, if you&#39;re of legal drinking age of course. Nothing&rsquo;s wrong if you&rsquo;re being safe and making sure you&rsquo;re paying attention and are aware of your surroundings. There&rsquo;s nothing worse than endangering your life or someone else&#39;s life due to your stupidity. What I want you to get out of this chapter is that alcohol could be your best friend or it could be your worst enemy; it&rsquo;s up to you to decide.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tips for parents:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Parents, BE PARENTS! That means you can&rsquo;t break the law at home and then be upset with your child when they go to school and break the law and get in trouble. That just doesn&rsquo;t make sense! Don&rsquo;t be upset with school administrators when we&#39;ve provided you with the student code of conduct and explained the ramifications of not following the policies. The rules and policies are there for a reason. I get &ldquo;millions&rdquo; of calls from parents that are upset that we&#39;re enforcing the university policy, even though the students have signed off on a document saying that they&#39;re aware of and are going to follow university policies. Parents, back us up! Let&rsquo;s be on the same page and send the same message to your child. Being parents means that, unfortunately, sometimes you&#39;re going to have to make the unpopular choice. You&rsquo;re going to have to take a stand, just like we, as student affairs professionals, have to take a stand.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Parents, encourage your son or daughter to tell the truth! It&#39;s going to be hard for your son or daughter to come and talk to you about these things. Why? They don&#39;t want to be in trouble with their parents. They don&#39;t want to disappoint their parents. They don&#39;t want to feel the shame of having to tell their parents they have a $300.00 fine, they have to go through alcohol-related classes and complete classwork modules that deal with alcohol education and awareness. That&rsquo;s a horrible thing for a child to have to tell their parent. If your child comes to talk to you about what they&#39;ve done or something they haven&rsquo;t done, please be understanding; reacting in anger is not going to help them. In fact, it&#39;s going to reinforce the behavior and then they&rsquo;re probably not going to tell you the full situation now or in any future situation. I&rsquo;m not saying don&rsquo;t be upset, but make sure that you lend them an ear because this is a pivotal point in your child&rsquo;s life. Hear them out. They just want to be validated. They want to be understood. They want to know that they can go to you, their parent, and be certain that they are going to be heard.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If your son or daughter incurs a fine or legal trouble, take the situation for what it is. Some parents actually immediately try to &ldquo;fix&rdquo; the situation and that&rsquo;s why their child doesn&rsquo;t fear the law. They know their parents are going to fix it. My suggestion to parents would be: let your students take care of their infraction by themselves. They got the infraction by themselves, or they got the policy violation by themselves, allow them to fix it by themselves. This is the only way that they can possibly learn from the experience.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Your son or daughter is going to let you down while they&#39;re in school. Except it! Prepare for it! They may let you down by failing a class or not performing well on a test, not choosing the major you want them to choose or by getting in trouble with some type of policy infraction. We&rsquo;re all human, that&rsquo;s what we do; we let each other down. We&#39;re not perfect, or at least some of us aren&rsquo;t. We&#39;re all works in progress. This is the time for them to make mistakes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ages 18-22 can determine the trajectory of what your child is going to do for the rest of their lives. Give them an opportunity to fail. Give them the space to make mistakes, that&#39;s where the greatest learning takes place. Most importantly, please support us as university officials. We&rsquo;re not out to get your child. We&rsquo;re not out to get them in trouble and penalize them. If anything, we&#39;re upset, just like you&rsquo;re upset. You&#39;re upset because your child has to pay fines and is in trouble with the law. We&rsquo;re upset because we have more work to do! Listen, we don&rsquo;t go out of our way to find trouble, trust me, trouble finds us. If we support each other, the situation doesn&rsquo;t have to go from bad to worse.</p>', '2020-09-07 23:15:06', '2020-09-11 00:01:46', NULL);
INSERT INTO `chapters` (`id`, `course_id`, `name`, `image`, `amount`, `details`, `created_at`, `updated_at`, `deleted_at`) VALUES
(24, 6, 'drugs vs. DRUGS', NULL, 20, '<p>You can&rsquo;t have a chapter about alcohol and not follow it up with a chapter about drugs! Drugs are just as prevalent on college campuses as alcohol. People always look at me with this glazed look in their eyes when I say that. Like it&#39;s impossible for drugs to be as prevalent as alcohol on college campuses. Don&#39;t believe me? Remember the story I told you about back in Chapter 1? The story about the questions asked by a university official, to both parents and students during orientation? Let me refresh your memory.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Before school begins, freshman orientation is held for both for parents and students. The rules and policies of the campus are explained and a tour of the campus is given. They taste the food in the university dining hall, get to meet their professors for their classes and find out all of the fun stuff that&#39;s going to be happening on campus. During the orientation, a university official asked an audience of about 350 students, &ldquo;How many of you drink?&rdquo; Only 1 or 2 students raised their hands. The university administrator then said to the students, &ldquo;Come on, I&rsquo;m not stupid. I&#39;ve been working at the University for twenty years now, let&#39;s just be honest; no one&#39;s going to get in trouble. I just want to get a clear and honest poll for how many people drink. So, I&rsquo;ll ask you again, &ldquo;How many of you in this room drink?&rdquo; When the university official stated it that way, 80% of the first year students raised their hands. She said, &ldquo;That&rsquo;s great! This is cool, we&rsquo;re all being honest now.&rdquo; Then the university official asked the audience, &ldquo;How many of you do drugs?&rdquo; Of course, no one raised their hand. So she stated again, &ldquo;Let&rsquo;s just be honest here. It&rsquo;s okay, no one is going to get in trouble. Just raise your hand.&rdquo; When she phrased the question that way, about 70% of the first year students raised their hands. Then the university administrator said, &ldquo;How many of you smoke marijuana?&rdquo;&nbsp; When she asked this question, the majority of the room raised their hands.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After the students were done, the parents came in for their portion of orientation. The administrator said, &ldquo;How many of you know that your child or student participates in drinking alcohol? Raise your hand if you do.&rdquo; Only a few parents raised their hand. The administrator repeated the question, but received the same raised hands. The administrator then said, &ldquo;This is so interesting because 80% of the students who were just in here, said they drink alcohol.&rdquo; The parents were shocked. Then the administrator said, &ldquo;How many of you know that your students do drugs or smoke marijuana?&rdquo; Of course, the parents didn&rsquo;t raise their hands&hellip;again. Then the administrator said to them, &ldquo;You know 70% of the students that were in here said they did.&rdquo; The look of shock and utter disbelief on their parents&#39; faces was priceless.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The enormous disconnect between students and their parents is a major factor that motivated and inspired me to write this book. Drugs, and the potential use of drugs is an intense topic, but it&rsquo;s a topic that should be seriously discussed and not just discussed once. Parents and students should be having ongoing conversations about drugs and discuss it continuously. Drugs are a huge issue in the world, on college campuses across the country and in high schools as well. We all know it&rsquo;s a problem, yet conversations, between parents and kids, still aren&rsquo;t happening. Yes, students are doing drugs when they go to college. Sometimes they&rsquo;re experimenting with drugs, solely out of curiosity, sometimes they&rsquo;re doing drugs to fit in or maybe they see their peers doing it or some may even use drugs as a coping mechanism for issues they&rsquo;re dealing with or in an attempt to regulate a chemical imbalance.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In a previous chapter, we talked about students coming to campuses with their suitcase full of issues. We also talked about alcohol being an issue. Unfortunately, for some students, alcohol isn&rsquo;t enough. They want to do something that&rsquo;s a little bit harder; and drugs may be the option that they choose.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Did you know that some students don&rsquo;t just come to college for an education? Some students actually come to college so they can sell drugs. Yes, there are dealers, in college and they&rsquo;re selling drugs. You might be asking yourself why would a dealer spend all that money so that they can come to college? Think about it, there are a bevy of customers at their beck and call. The dealers know exactly where the customers are and students know where the dealers are. The dealers can go directly to a student&rsquo;s dorm room or they can set up a purchase/deliver system so that students can purchase drugs. Dealers are even wearing special clothes so students know who to go to for drugs. Everyone knows, look for this individual, wearing these clothes in this specific location. I mean imagine, if you go to a school that costs $20,000 a year to attend, and you&rsquo;re a dealer, you could probably make the $20,000 back within a few months and now you&rsquo;re actually making pure profit.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>People don&rsquo;t believe me, but drug dealers are a REAL thing on college campuses. It&rsquo;s happening more and more nowadays. In this day and age, I think most universities are being vigilant in their fight against drugs being sold and used on campus. There are major consequences if someone is caught selling drugs on campus. They will be disqualified as a student and more importantly, they will face criminal charges. There are certain times throughout the school year where the dealers are more readily available to their customers. In my experience, the most prevalent time for deals happening on campus is right around midterms and finals weeks. In addition to regular street drugs, dealers also sell prescription drugs (obviously, prescribed to other people). Dealers capitalize on selling drugs that enhance the ability to focus, like Ritalin or Adderall. Since extra focus may be needed during heavy test times, this is a prime opportunity for the dealers to make even more money. During the regular school year, students are sometimes using marijuana, meth, cocaine and heroin, depending on the area your school is located.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When we go back to the previous story, at orientation, what we find is that often times parents aren&rsquo;t aware of the activities their students are participating in. When the college administrator in the orientation story asks the parents, &ldquo;How many of your students do drugs?&rdquo; And the parents look around thinking, &ldquo;Not my child.&rdquo; We find that a lot of parents have this &ldquo;not my child&rdquo; mindset, meaning &ldquo;It&#39;s impossible for my child to do this. My child hasn&#39;t done it in front of me so I know they haven&#39;t done it.&rdquo; What parents have to realize is that their students don&#39;t do everything in front of you. Your child will change. The child you sent away to college is not the same one that you may be getting when they come home. Children evolve, they develop, they learn new habits and just because your child had or hasn&#39;t done something in front of you doesn&#39;t mean that they do it or don&rsquo;t do it. This is why we need to have these engaging conversations with our students to really know what&#39;s going on in their culture and their lives. We need to understand that students are making decisions and that&#39;s what life&#39;s all about. It&#39;s about making a decision: &ldquo;yes, I&#39;m going to do this&rdquo; or &ldquo;no, I&#39;m not going to do this.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ultimately, we can&#39;t hold the student&rsquo;s hands. When I go back to the story about the student who was dealing to afford college, it seems unfortunate, but she was making a choice and she knew that selling drugs was against university policies. She knew that it was going against the student code of conduct but she made the decision to continue selling drugs. The outcome of that story was that the university chose to remove the student from the institution. I recall talking to her parent about the situation and the parent just could not believe that their precious student had been selling drugs. How could this have happened? I tried giving the parent some insight, asking, &ldquo;Were you and your spouse recently divorced?&rdquo; The parent said, &ldquo;Yes.&rdquo; I said, &ldquo;Did you know that had a really big effect on your daughter?&rdquo; The parent was in shock. They weren&rsquo;t aware of the long-term effects that their situation could have on their daughter. The parent began to cry and we had a long developmental conversation concerning where her daughter might be going, because she needed some different options for her future.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For students who are reading this, I want you to know that people who are dealing drugs on campus usually get caught. Sometimes they don&#39;t, but most of the time, they do. Your university police are working overtime to find these individuals who are committing these infractions on your campuses. This is not something you want to be involved in; this is something you want to stay far away from. Look, some of you who are reading might already be doing drugs or even selling drugs. If that describes you, if you have the ability, get out now! One of the reasons I say that is because what we&rsquo;re finding is that students who are turning in the dealers are also turning in other students. If you&#39;re involved in something like this, get out as soon as you can; nothing good can come from this situation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When people are trying drugs for the first or second time, they don&rsquo;t really know what to expect. The only thing they have to base their reaction off of is what others have told them. Since they don&rsquo;t have any personal experience, their reaction is almost solely based off of other people&#39;s perception of what the drug <em>should</em> do. People sharing their personal reactions is almost subliminal to a new drug user. They&rsquo;re going to expect that same feeling or reaction, but your experience can be completely different from someone else&rsquo;s. Everyone experiences drugs and being high in many different ways.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Peer pressure has and probably always will be a huge factor when it comes to doing drugs. You may hear people may say, &ldquo;Smoke this joint; it&rsquo;ll make you feel good! Being high is great, it makes the college experience better.&rdquo; Most times when we talk to students about their experiences, they say they did it because they wanted to give it the old college try. I&#39;m sure a lot of you who have been through college can recall your own situations where you just wanted to give it the college try. Was it the best decision? If you were a little bit more mature, would you have made the same decisions that you made or would you have chosen something different? How do you advise your son or daughter who&#39;s about to enter college? Would you tell them to give it a try because you did? Again, some people like to learn things the hard way; the School of Hard Knocks. For other people, they don&rsquo;t want to learn that way; they&rsquo;d rather <em>not </em>be exposed to certain things.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Drug use in students has escalated from the lower level, more common drugs (like marijuana) to hard core drugs (PCP, heroin, meth, cocaine). I don&rsquo;t want to promote the use of any drug, but I consider marijuana to be on the same level as alcohol. Taking prescription narcotic drugs can have negative, long-term effects on your body and your mind. It&rsquo;s even more dangerous when they&rsquo;re prescribed to someone else. First, do you really know what they are? Second, do you know what dosage to take? Lastly, you should never take drugs that are not prescribed to you. Drugs like meth, cocaine, and heroin are considered hardcore. If you or someone you know is using these drugs in a long-term situation, not only is there risk of being addicted to the drug, but you could have severe physical repercussions from using, such as, respiratory failure, heart failure, loss of teeth, and/or physical deterioration.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I remember one time in a residence hall, at the institution I used to work for, where we had to do room checks. Room checks take place when we need to ensure that the students are being safe in their rooms. This means that we&rsquo;re checking to make sure that their rooms are clean, the trash is taken out, making sure there is no mold, mildew, bugs or any other safety concerns that could put the students at risk. Most institutions do about two health and safety checks per semester. These are conducted by the resident director or the resident assistants that are in the building. I recall this one time I had to do a health and safety check in a room. When I walked into the room, right in plain view, sitting on the desk, was a scale, some marijuana and some empty baggies. I asked the roommate, &ldquo;Excuse me? What is all this?&rdquo; The roommate looked me right in my face and said, &ldquo;Hey look. I don&rsquo;t want anything to do with this. I&rsquo;m not involved in this but it&rsquo;s definitely my roommate&rsquo;s. I don&#39;t have anything to do with this.&rdquo; I asked the roommate, &ldquo;How long has this been going on?&rdquo; The roommate replied, &ldquo;All year!&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As most people in this position would do, I called Public Safety. They came to the room and confiscated all of the drug paraphernalia. A few days later, I had to talk to the student, in a judicial meeting, about the events that took place. The student started crying. She told me that she had to sell drugs because her parents had just gotten divorced and this was the only way she could afford to go to school. This isn&#39;t to paint any drug dealers in a positive light. I just always, in every single text, want to give both sides of the story. That particular student didn&rsquo;t intend to be a drug dealer. She was just trying to make some money and didn&#39;t realize the bigger effect this could have on her future or the student body.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Students are consuming drugs and alcohol in a variety of new and different ways. I know some students who didn&rsquo;t want to get in trouble for drinking so they soaked all of their vodka into gummy bears. So, it appeared that they were just eating gummy bears, but in reality, they were getting drunk. Some students are even taking prescription pills in ways they were not designed to be taken. For example: Students have been known to crush up a pill, and snort it; instead of taking it the way it was intended. It just looks different today than in past years.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I remember a story about a young man at the institution I used to work at. He consumed what he thought was a pot brownie, but the pot brownie was laced with ecstasy and he wasn&rsquo;t aware. And of course, because he didn&rsquo;t know the brownies were laced, he hadn&rsquo;t just eaten one; he had eaten several. We found this student later on, praying in the middle of the street in a surrounding local city; all because he was under the influence of an unknown drug. Later on, we found the individual making very weird remarks to some of the students in the hall. He was talking to some of the residents and asking them to go look at his poop. He wanted everyone to come look at his poop in the toilet. Of course, people thought his behavior was extremely odd and it was, because he was high. Ultimately, his parents had to come and get him and he had to get a toxicology test. That pot brownie had a huge impact on his life. He ended up having to transfer schools due to the severe effects the drugs had on him. This situation was horrible. He didn&#39;t know the pot brownie was laced with other drugs because the dealer didn&#39;t tell him. It&rsquo;s not safe to take drugs from people you don&rsquo;t know. Make smart decisions when it comes to drugs because drugs can really mess you up; whether it&rsquo;s becoming addicted or having an adverse reaction to something you weren&rsquo;t even aware you took.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When we talk about drug addiction or drug dependency, some students can develop drug issues while in school. Unfortunately, when they go home for Thanksgiving break, holiday/Christmas break or Spring break, of course, the dependency goes with them. For parents, if your child comes home and they&rsquo;re acting a little odd or not acting like themselves, pay attention; better to be safe than sorry. Yes, your son or daughter will be somewhat different because they&rsquo;re in college; they&rsquo;re used to a bit of independence. But you should still recognize your child! Am I saying every single student who comes home has a drug dependency? NO! Of course not. I don&rsquo;t want your child to come home for break, walk through the door and have you sniffing and searching through their bags like Batman screaming, WHERE ARE THE DRUGS!?! That is not what I&rsquo;m suggesting at all. What I am suggesting is that if you see a significant behavioral change in your child there might be some questions that you might want to ask. Things may have changed and things may be a little different but it&rsquo;s up to you to play your role as parents and really pay attention to see if these things are extremely different.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sometimes college campuses have a huge drug bust and everyone sits around puzzled thinking, &ldquo;How could this happen on our campus? How could this ever take place?&rdquo; Well, it would be fair to say that most college campuses have a dealer, who has a lot of inventory and he or she is ready to come in to sell their supply! This scenario isn&rsquo;t just prone to certain areas. There are drugs and alcohol on every single campus. I remember at the institution of a friend of mine there was an almost one-million-dollar drug bust! When you think about this, what 20 year old has a million dollars&rsquo; worth of drugs? It happens though. You can look it up on the Internet and see that there are a lot of busts in different situations on different campuses around the country.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>They&rsquo;re also becoming more creative. Some of these drugs are labeled with emoji&rsquo;s or labeled with your favorite icon. They don&#39;t even look like drugs, they look like candy. They can be any type of drug too. Then there are the date rape drugs being slipped into drinks and when the drug actually fully dissolves, the drink still appears the same as it was originally. It doesn&#39;t even look like the drink has been tampered with. You can&#39;t just go by what your eye sees; your eyes aren&rsquo;t going to see that the drink was messed with. You can&rsquo;t even go by your taste, because a lot of the drugs are even tasteless. Be cautious about what you are considering putting in your body. Something that may seem as harmless as a piece of candy, may be more than you bargained for.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sometimes we even catch people bringing in drugs on move-in day. As a resident director, you hope that you only catch maybe a hamster, a cat or a little dog being moved into the residence hall, but on some occasions, we actually do catch students moving in and bringing drugs with them. Then we have to have a really awkward conversation with the student and their parents about why the student is going back home on move-in day and why they won&rsquo;t be attending school there. You see a whole bunch of ad campaigns about drugs. Some of the more familiar ones are: dontdoit.com or dontknowyourfacts.com. You could also try justthinktwice.gov or getsmartaboutdrugs.gov. They have these drug ads for a reason, not just to be corny. Some of them are very corny but they&rsquo;re trying to get the message out there that drugs have long-lasting effects and can be really harmful to you.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I want to leave you all with tips for parents and students.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Parents:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Have an open dialogue with your child about drugs. It&rsquo;s a real thing. You may have even done drugs in the past but to blindly assume that your student doesn&#39;t know anything about drugs, that they&rsquo;re not involved with drugs, or that your student doesn&rsquo;t have anything to do with drugs is ludicrous. Drugs have become almost a normalized part of society, so continue to have engaging conversations with our children, to discuss these uncomfortable issues. It&rsquo;s going to be uncomfortable and you&rsquo;re not going to feel cool. Your child may even give you some pretty generic answers saying they don&rsquo;t do drugs or haven&rsquo;t tried drugs and won&rsquo;t be doing drugs in the future. Ask the important questions. Their answers will probably be no. But press on. Tell them openly and honestly, &ldquo;If you&#39;re going to try drugs, I need you to be safe. If you&#39;re going to try drugs, try to stick to the milder drugs. The hard-core drugs can have life-altering effects. I don&rsquo;t want you to get hurt. I don&rsquo;t want to lose you. I care about you.&rdquo; Those conversations are more important than you saying to your child, &ldquo;Don&rsquo;t do drugs!&rdquo; From day one, that&rsquo;s what the students hear: &ldquo;Don&rsquo;t do drugs or alcohol.&rdquo; Does it stop them from doing it? No! If we told our students: &ldquo;Don&rsquo;t skateboard down the steps in a residence hall&rdquo; do you think that stops them? No! We tell students: &ldquo;Don&rsquo;t pee on the statue in the middle of the quad.&rdquo; Does it stop them? No! Why? Because just telling students not to do something isn&rsquo;t enough for the students to get those elemental learning pieces to <em>not </em>do something. Think about it yourself, how many times has an authority figure told you not to do something and you continue to do it anyway?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For me, as someone who does diversity training and speaks to students all the time, I&#39;m telling you that I don&#39;t particularly break the law but there are sometimes I like to bend the rules. I might go to a Philadelphia Eagles game and sneak into the locker room so I can take pictures with all the players...true story! I may sneak into the N.F.L draft and meet Roger Goodell, the N.F.L. commissioner&hellip;again, true story! You know, sometimes, bending the law works (Disclaimer: Don&rsquo;t break the law). The things I&rsquo;m referring to aren&rsquo;t safety issues. When it comes to the consumption of alcohol and drugs, these behaviors can be detrimental to your life and set you going backwards on your life&rsquo;s trajectory; which is to be a successful student at a university or college. We know you want to follow your dreams, make them come true and make your parents proud. Drugs and alcohol are not the way to do that.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Back to parent&rsquo;s tips:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Parents, be aware of what the effects of drugs look like. Your child could have extreme personality changes, loss of appetite, huge changes in sleeping patterns, depression, withdrawal from family members, carelessness of personal hygiene, lack of interest in hobbies, etc. Look up the symptoms if you are not sure. Pay attention and if you know that your son or daughter is doing drugs, get them the help that they need. Standing back thinking that they&rsquo;ll figure it out or waiting for them get the help on their own&hellip;not a good idea. Some people have drug dependency and they truly need someone to advocate for them. That means being a parent, stepping in when your child doesn&#39;t want you to, being invasive and making sure your student gets the assistance and resources that they need to be the most successful student.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Students:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Again, I&rsquo;m not saying I&rsquo;m pro-drugs, I&rsquo;m not saying I&rsquo;m anti-drugs, but, based on my experiences, I would say that using drugs, consuming drugs, inhaling drugs, snorting drugs and shooting up drugs has never been something where I&#39;ve witnessed a positive outcome. Yeah, that high might feel good but it&rsquo;s only a temporary feeling. Yeah, that high might take you to a place where you can escape your pain, but again, that&rsquo;s just temporary. You don&rsquo;t want a temporary fix to become a permanent solution or outcome.&nbsp; Most of the time, the pain of things that you&rsquo;re going through or stressful situations that you may encounter are just momentary. You figure out how to deal with them, how to cope with them, how to get through them, how to be a better person in spite of them. Whatever doesn&#39;t kill you makes you stronger! Sometimes, the thing that you&rsquo;re doing isn&rsquo;t killing you now but will eventually kill you. Make sure you are making the best decisions possible.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When I was growing up, the majority of advice I got regarding drugs was to stay away from them, don&rsquo;t be involved with people who are using them. I&rsquo;ve known friends and colleagues that may not have been doing drugs themselves but were around people who were doing drugs. They ended up getting caught up in situations that were violent, where individuals got robbed, stabbed, or beat up just because they were in association with individuals who did drugs. The advice I always got was: stay as far away from it as possible. If you see drugs, go in the opposite direction.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Just because you&#39;re reading this book doesn&#39;t mean I&#39;m going to be able to influence you. I will say this: I&#39;m not going to be there when you&#39;re doing drugs, your parents probably won&rsquo;t be there when you&rsquo;re doing drugs, so the best person to look out for you is YOU. Drugs weren&rsquo;t designed to create long-term happiness, only temporary happiness; not a long-term solution to your issue. Your issue could theoretically just be a minor setback or a minor situation. Drugs can ruin lives, waste your money and rob you of time that could be used to achieve your goals in life. Your focus should be on completing a two year Associate&#39;s degree, a four year Master&#39;s degree or aspire to complete a Doctorate degree. Doing drugs will not be a successful addition to your plan.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&rsquo;ll leave you with this last story. I had a friend who got caught up in using drugs. It wasn&#39;t cool and I witnessed his downfall. That&#39;s why I&#39;m saying you&#39;ve got to speak up. In this situation, my friend told me he could handle it and I believed him. Instead of being that intentional friend or an active bystander, and having the conversation, he continued on and was kicked out of the institution. Am I saying this so you can judge me and think, &ldquo;Man. Justin was a bad friend. He didn&rsquo;t speak up!&rdquo; No! At that time in my developmental state, I didn&#39;t know that speaking up was an option.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I come from a culture that says &ldquo;No Snitching&rdquo; and if your friend said using drugs was okay, then it was okay. You don&#39;t continuously get on your friend about it. But no! If you have friends, colleagues, family or loved ones that you know are on drugs and are not getting the help they need, be that positive and intrusive bystander; help them to help themselves. Sometimes intervention is the only option left. Thankfully, my friend was able to get the help that he needed and he&rsquo;s no longer on drugs. If you ask him, he would tell you that it was a very dark time in his life and if he could do it all over again, he wouldn&rsquo;t do it. Stay away from drugs. If going to college so you can be a dealer or experiment with drugs is on your To Do list, just stay home; you could be a drug dealer and a drug user for free.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you or anyone you know need help, there are many local resources available. Please seek information at your campus wellness center.&nbsp;</p>', '2020-09-07 23:15:36', '2020-09-11 00:01:57', NULL);
INSERT INTO `chapters` (`id`, `course_id`, `name`, `image`, `amount`, `details`, `created_at`, `updated_at`, `deleted_at`) VALUES
(25, 6, 'It’s Called Sex People!', NULL, 20, '<p>Let&#39;s talk about sex baby, let&rsquo;s talk about you and me! All right, most of us already know that sex is definitely taking place in college. If you didn&#39;t know, now you know! Obviously, this book is designed so that you can have open dialogue with your student or parents about a multitude of different topics. Sex can be an awkward conversation to have. It can be awkward talking to your parents about it and it can even be awkward talking to your peers. You thought you escaped another sex talk because you took the class back in your teen years and then you had the birds and bees conversation with your parents. I guess you thought that would be the end of the sex talk. When you go off to college, that&#39;s another opportunity to have a more elevated conversation about sex, since sex is basically embedded in the college experience.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>College can be a time where people go out and explore their sexuality a little bit deeper or maybe it&rsquo;s a time when you&rsquo;ll encounter your first sexual experience. Mom and dad aren&rsquo;t around and there aren&rsquo;t any rules about men or women coming into your room at any particular time. There&rsquo;s usually no curfew and you just kind of find yourself in predicaments that you previously wouldn&rsquo;t have found yourself in. When I say that sex is rampant on college campuses, I mean sex is rampant! Students are having sex and they&#39;re probably having sex with multiple partners. When you&rsquo;re in college, since you&rsquo;re a little older, you think your relationships are going to be stronger. You have more mature relationships with people. I&rsquo;m talking more mature relationships, in general, not just sexual relationships and not just the casual relationships where you meet up at the mall, to hang out, after your mom drops you off.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When I walked onto college campuses, for me as a heterosexual, cisgender male, I was shocked. I had seen women, but this was totally different. In high school, there was a dress code, but for the most part, in college, there is no dress code. And I mean NO dress code! When I saw women hanging out in the quad, wearing only bikinis, I was like, &ldquo;Whoa, look at that!&rdquo; Now <em>that </em>was a memorable moment for me. The promiscuity of men and women in college is off the charts. Mom and dad aren&#39;t there telling you to change your clothes. You can pretty much wear whatever you want; you&rsquo;re independent so you can make your own choices. You can basically do whatever you want, wear whatever you want and act however you want. Growing up, most kids were safeguarded against these types of behaviors and experiences. Kids were discouraged from acting a certain way and growing up too fast. Now, they have the ability to go out and behave any way they want.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I know for the parents who are reading this right now, you&#39;re probably freaking out! You&rsquo;re probably saying, &ldquo;No! Not my son or daughter!&rdquo; or &ldquo;My daughter is a virgin!&rdquo; or &ldquo;My son is practicing celibacy!&rdquo; You won&rsquo;t truly know, unless you talk to your son or daughter. Here&rsquo;s the other thing, you may ask them and they may lie to you. Think about it, would you tell your parents whether or not you&rsquo;re having sex while you&#39;re in college? That&rsquo;s why having open and honest conversations are so important. Rest assured, there are a myriad of sex education programs available on university campuses. One thing that happens at most of these programs is that condoms are given out. This is a good system because you want your kids to practice safe sex. Those free condoms will definitely be put to use!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are a myriad of reasons why students are engaging in sexual activity in college. Hormones are raging, it happens; it&rsquo;s part of life. Another reason could be that mom and dad aren&rsquo;t around to tell you not to. Maybe your mom and dad were strict while you were growing up and now they&rsquo;re telling you, &ldquo;When you go to college, don&rsquo;t have sex.&rdquo; Now, all of a sudden, mom and dad aren&rsquo;t there and the urge to experiment and try new things is creeping to the top of your list of &ldquo;stuff to do&rdquo;. True story, when I was visiting colleges, before I made my decision on where to go, I would literally see signs posted, on the road, saying things like, &ldquo;Thank you for your daughters. Welcome to such and such a college!&rdquo; or &ldquo;You were her daddy for 18 years; now I&#39;m her daddy, at least for tonight.&rdquo; I was thinking, &ldquo;Oh my! This is a brand-new trip for me!&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For some students who are already in college, you&rsquo;ve had a year or two years or possibly three of sexual adventures under your belts. So, when you see new people on campus, like first year students, I&rsquo;m sure it feels like the perfect time to introduce them to the sexual escapades known to college life. Intentional conversations are so important when it comes to going to college in relation to sexual intercourse and sexual promiscuity. Maybe you&rsquo;ve come from a high school that had a small number of students and now you&rsquo;re in an environment where there are a ton of diverse people to discover. There are so many different people, makes, models and genders; it can be a bit overwhelming. College students are having lots of sex with lots of different people and experiencing new adventures. That&rsquo;s why I think the conversations about sexual activity and sexual education are so important. The conversations are also a way to find out the real answers as to why people are having sex. Some people have a sexual addiction; they just need and want sex; like any addiction, it can be all-consuming. College campuses are a place they can feed those sexual desires and cravings to the max. Others are just having fun and enjoying the new-found freedoms they have.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Personal note for me, and I&rsquo;m not embarrassed about it like I used to be, I was celibate in college. I was celibate the entire time. Granted, as a cisgender, heterosexual, black male, that doesn&rsquo;t mean that I didn&rsquo;t have urges. It doesn&#39;t mean that I didn&rsquo;t mess around with women; oh I definitely did. But I didn&#39;t have sex. I had a few experiences with some women that were probably the most gorgeous women I&rsquo;ve ever seen, in my entire life and I had the opportunity to have sex with them. Again, it was <em>extremely </em>hard to say no! I was made fun of because people thought that maybe there was something wrong with me or that I was gay, because how else could I say no? &ldquo;That dude is weird&rdquo; or &ldquo;What kind of man are you?&rdquo; I&rsquo;m sure you&rsquo;re wondering why I chose to be celibate. It was a personal choice. I made that decision and I stuck to it. I didn&rsquo;t want to give myself up to just anyone. I wanted to make sure the person I decided to be with was special and the person that I would be with was going to be a lifetime person. I wasn&rsquo;t interested in a one night stand. I didn&rsquo;t want to get an STD or get someone pregnant either. For me, it was a no brainer. I found that there weren&rsquo;t many people in college who were celibate and if they were celibate, they certainly weren&#39;t telling people about it. Now that I&rsquo;m an adult, I can sincerely say, for me, it was the best choice.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&#39;m going to tell you some stories about why my choice to remain celibate was a good decision. Being celibate meant I didn&rsquo;t have to worry about contracting an STD; and believe me, some of my friends contracted STDs in college. I didn&rsquo;t have to worry about getting someone pregnant. I didn&#39;t have to worry about having or not having that spiritual and emotional connection with somebody that wasn&#39;t worthy of having those connections with me. Sex is not just a physical connection, it&rsquo;s an emotional and psychological connection as well. Think about how the act of sexual intercourse connects your mind, body and soul. Throughout your life and definitely in college, you have the opportunity to truly get to know people. Remember that the people you meet in college are, at that moment, just like you, trying to figure out who they are. Sometimes the person, standing in front of you, the person you&rsquo;ve been learning about and connecting with, may not actually be the person you think they are. My questions to you would be: Who do you really want to be connected to? Who do you know or want to get to know on that level? What do you really know about the people you&rsquo;ve previously connected with? Are they worthy of you giving them your connection? Think about these questions as you go down the path of sexual adventures.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are many topics to discuss in this chapter and they&rsquo;re all important, but sexual safety is extremely important in college and of course, throughout life. We want to make sure that if students are having sex (and they are definitely having sex!), that they&#39;re being as safe as possible. We want to make sure that they&#39;re using condoms, that all parties involved are consensual, and that, hopefully, they aren&rsquo;t drunk while they&rsquo;re having sex. I&rsquo;m sure some of you are saying, &ldquo;Drunk sex is great sex!&rdquo; That may be true (or not), but let me tell you, when drunk people engage in sex, no one is able to consent. No one is of a sober mind to make a decision to consent. Lack of consent means the action is considered rape. So, technically, any drunk sexual intercourse could and is defined as rape. Be aware of this and make the right decisions. Use condoms to prevent pregnancy and STDs! Don&rsquo;t have drunk sex where consent is absent. These tips shouldn&rsquo;t be too difficult to follow. The consequences of not following them could alter your life, forever.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We have to start teaching what constitutes consent. Think about it, boys are taught: Boys will be boys. But when it comes to consent, that&rsquo;s not acceptable. Rape is rape, people! Sexual assault is sexual assault! It doesn&#39;t matter if she was drunk. It doesn&#39;t matter if she was coming on to you. It doesn&rsquo;t matter if she was wearing a short dress. It doesn&rsquo;t matter if she was acting promiscuously. None of these things matter when it comes to consent. A yes must be a sober yes. In the statements that I just said, it sounds like I&rsquo;m implying that women are the only victims of rape and that&rsquo;s not true. There are men who are raped in college, and in the world, as well. Unfortunately, we can&rsquo;t rely on data and statistics for rape against men, because most men don&rsquo;t report rape; especially in a college setting. For some reason, it&rsquo;s looked at as embarrassing. Men don&rsquo;t want to admit that they were raped, but it does happen. When we talk about the data regarding rape, not only do we not have accurate data on men being raped, we don&rsquo;t have accurate data about women being raped either. A good amount of women, who experience rape, don&rsquo;t come forward. There seems to be an unfortunate stigma that goes hand-in-hand with rape.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When it comes to drunk sex, we need to teach people that if you want to have sex, that&rsquo;s great, but it&rsquo;s okay to wait. If you wake up in the morning and both of you are still consenting, and you&rsquo;re both sober, then by all means, have at it! But if the feelings aren&rsquo;t still there, then maybe this isn&rsquo;t a good time. This is definitely not a popular message, but it&rsquo;s a message that needs to be shared. If you ultimately choose to throw caution to the wind and engage in sexual activity when there is not a solid yes, just know there could be some repercussions, consequences and issues that come along with your actions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There is also a need for open discussions when it comes to our expectations in relation to sex. Some people like to have sex in certain ways and other people don&#39;t. Some people like to experiment sexually, others may not want to participate in experimenting. If you don&#39;t make those expectations clear, you could find yourself in a situation that you weren&#39;t prepared for and ultimately, an experience that you&rsquo;re not enjoying. I&rsquo;ve had a lot of conversations with students pertaining to sex. Conversations like a student feeling horrible because they had sex when they didn&rsquo;t really want to and now they&rsquo;re having trouble even looking at the other person. Another student expressed that they really weren&rsquo;t ready to have sex, but did it anyway. And yet another example of relationships between students that started out as nice, kind and sweet. They met in the residence hall, started holding hands and hanging out. Then the relationship turned sexual and now the relationship has soured; leaving everything uncomfortable between them and those around them.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&rsquo;m sure most of you know that sex can definitely complicate things; especially when it comes to relationships. Sex can also make relationships better. Some people need and want sex front and center in their relationships; that&#39;s how they feel connected to people. You have to realize though, when you have sex with someone, it can take the relationship to a whole new level. Some people don&#39;t view sex as just something physical; they feel that it&#39;s something more special and intimate. Others view sex as just that&hellip;.sex, no relationship. This is another reason why you should set those expectations upfront, before sex occurs. No need for broken hearts when a conversation beforehand could eliminate any hard feelings or difficult situations.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We know people have been having sex since the dawn of time, that&rsquo;s nothing new, but I think the sexual trends have changed quite drastically. Think about when the integration of dormitories and residence halls started. The halls, or at least the floors in the hall, used to be gender specific. Now, with integration, they live in the same residence hall, not usually in the same rooms, but definitely in the same hall. They can go up a floor or down a floor or even across the hallway and see each other. They&rsquo;re seeing each other constantly and they&rsquo;re observing each other in their natural element. I know some of you parents are probably getting anxious right now. You&rsquo;re thinking, &ldquo;Oh God, my son is going to be living in the same residence hall with women!&rdquo; or &ldquo;My daughter is going to be in a residence hall with guys, what was I thinking?&rdquo; According to data that is available to student affairs professionals, highlighting sex and safety on college campuses, the issues occurring with mixed-gender dorms is minimal.&nbsp; We haven&rsquo;t encountered many problems, most likely due to sexual education, event programming, security as well as the ever-present RA&rsquo;s; these measures are there to keep everyone safe.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Conversations and open dialogue are a must when it comes to sex, especially when mixed genders are living in close proximity to each other. It all depends on what kind of hall you live in. I&rsquo;ve lived in a traditional hall where there was only one bathroom on the floor. Living in that hall, there were a few times when I happened to see women walking down the hallway in just a towel. This was a new experience for me and very eye-opening, as I&rsquo;m sure you can imagine. I&rsquo;ve also lived in halls where I had my own bathroom, in my room, and didn&rsquo;t have to encounter anyone in a towel. Either of these scenarios will be different to the student experiencing them. This may be your first exposure to an in-your-face view of the opposite sex. Sometimes these situations can be arousing. Sometimes it&#39;s exciting, simply because you haven&rsquo;t been around many different types of people.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In my position, as a student, as an RA and now as a student affairs professional, I&rsquo;ve been involved in many confidential conversations, with students, regarding pregnancy scares. Let me tell you, it doesn&rsquo;t just scare them; it scares me too! This is one reason why sexual education and sexual safety are so important. I can recall a particular situation with a student I knew. She was very active and involved on campus. She kind of had everything going for her; then she got pregnant. The sad part was she got pregnant by someone who didn&rsquo;t even care about her; it was just sex for him. This situation reflects back to what I&rsquo;ve said a few times, a conversation regarding expectations could have changed the outcome of her situation. The student ended up having to drop out of school and she never finished. She was an incredibly bright student and if I saw her today, I would still encourage her to go back and finish. I was so sad to see her go. I was sad that she had to put her dreams on hold all because of one misguided choice. I&rsquo;m sure it altered the young man&rsquo;s life as well, but I didn&rsquo;t have a relationship with him, so I wasn&rsquo;t privy to that information.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is not to say that everybody who gets pregnant in college doesn&rsquo;t have a chance to continue their education or that their life is ruined. No, absolutely not! Babies are definitely a blessing. Although, having a baby during college could definitely alter the goals you wish to accomplish. Understand that one decision, good or bad, can have a lasting impact on the rest of your life; depending on what type of decision you make. This is why I continue to emphasize the importance of making good decisions.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sexual safety is also important when it relates to contracting sexually transmitted diseases and ultimately, spreading them. I would love to tell you that no one in college contracts STD&rsquo;s, but we all know that&rsquo;s not true. Ask any wellness professional, not only in a hospital or ER or clinic, but especially the ones on campus and they would tell you STD&rsquo;s are fairly common. I can recall a story where a student confided in me that he had an STD. When I asked him how he contracted an STD, he said he wasn&rsquo;t sure. When I questioned him further and asked him if he was having unprotected sex, he told me he was. I then asked him how many sexual partners he had; he told me three. I told him that it was his responsibility to figure out how to handle this situation. I did give him the following tips: First, go to the health center to make sure he definitely had an STD (he later found out that he did). Second, he would need to have an open and honest conversation with the three women he had sex with. And finally, he needed to start using condoms to prevent this type of situation from happening in the future. I know this conversation and the tips I gave the student sound a bit uncomfortable and definitely logical, but let me tell you, this is a normal day in the life of most student affair professionals. We&rsquo;re having grown, adult conversations with students who are making grown, adult decisions that don&rsquo;t always end well. We guide them as best as possible, in each situation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I remember there was a girl who lived on campus who had a reputation for having sex with a lot of different guys. I want to pause and make a note here: This is not a female-only issue. Plenty of guys, in college, also have this reputation. Even though this student went on to do many great things at this university, the bad reputation that started in her first year on campus and continued into her second year, and beyond. That initial impression can often stay with you throughout your years on campus. Sure, you can absolutely feel bad for somebody with this type of reputation or stigma, especially so early on in there campus life. But, at the same time, there has to be some sort of personal responsibility and accountability.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sometimes these reputations have merit and sometimes they don&rsquo;t. I know a lot of you are probably thinking, &ldquo;Justin, of course you&rsquo;re telling a story where the girl was sleeping around and being promiscuous!&rdquo; No, I&rsquo;m going to give you the flip side too because I think that sometimes women get a bad rap when it comes to sleeping around and guys don&rsquo;t necessarily get the same treatment. A lot of times, women who sleep around are considered easy or loose or slutty, but guys are revered for that same behavior. On college campuses, there are both promiscuous, sexually active men AND there are also promiscuous, sexually active women. It&rsquo;s not one-sided.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When we talk to students who engage in sexual activity with multiple partners, I hear a multitude of different stories and most don&rsquo;t end well. There may be the female who&rsquo;s having sex with everyone on her floor or the guy that&rsquo;s trying to have sex with every single woman in his building. These scenarios can&rsquo;t end well. Again, your reputation is at stake and may follow you throughout your college experience. Is a moment of sexual gratification worth the risk?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>One of my students once told me, &ldquo;A key that opens many locks, is a great key; but a lock that opens with many keys, is a bad lock.&rdquo; This isn&rsquo;t necessarily true and this statement definitely favors male promiscuity. Any type of sexual promiscuity comes with a reputation and consequences, whether you&rsquo;re male or female. A reminder to students, throughout your college experience, you are constantly networking, you&#39;re always interviewing, and you&rsquo;re continuously being looked at and judged by others. It doesn&rsquo;t matter if you don&rsquo;t want to be judged. People are going to see what you show them of yourself and actions speak louder than words.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My advice: I would say, don&#39;t be that person. When I have relationships with people, regardless if they were sexual in nature or just friendly, I just keep my business to myself. I&rsquo;m a very private person. You don&rsquo;t want everybody in your business, especially when it comes to college life because if you allow it, everybody will be all up in your business. It doesn&rsquo;t matter if you live on a small campus or a big campus; interesting gossip spreads like wildfire and sex still sells. This is the same reason why I would discourage you putting your business on any social media platform. We&rsquo;ve seen situations when a student seeks revenge on social media, after a sexual encounter didn&rsquo;t end well. They&rsquo;re putting up pictures, sending Snapchats and sometimes sexting to get someone jealous. Don&rsquo;t do that! Don&rsquo;t be that person! Remember, what goes on the internet, stays on the internet&hellip;.FOREVER! Put your best foot forward, your best effort out there and don&rsquo;t get caught up in that kind of nonsense. If you&rsquo;re grown enough to engage in a sexual experience, you should be grown enough to handle any repercussions that may occur.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s time for a few stories that I recall from my time on campus. One story in particular stands out, where the front desk security guard saw a male and a female walking into a residence hall. Part of his responsibilities was to make sure all guests were signed in before they entered the hall. The guard asked the male student, &ldquo;What&rsquo;s her name? You need to sign her name in the login book.&rdquo; The male looked the female right in the face and said, &ldquo;What&rsquo;s your name again?&rdquo; I think that&rsquo;s a problem, don&rsquo;t you? Let&rsquo;s not encourage that type of behavior. This is a prime example of why such rules are in place. It becomes a safety issue, for all parties involved. For real, if you&#39;re going to have sex with someone, at least have the decency to know their name. At the very least, know their name! I know this probably isn&rsquo;t a message we hear often and it may be an unpopular message, but it&rsquo;s a necessary message. You may hear something more along the lines of &ldquo;You&rsquo;re attracted to each other, have sex. This is America, you can do whatever you want to do.&rdquo; I&rsquo;m here to say that it is perfectly okay to take a step back and maybe get to know the person <em>before</em> you dive under the sheets. See what they&rsquo;re about and show them what you&rsquo;re about. Sex not only says something about them, but it says something about you, too. Again, let&rsquo;s look at both sides of the coin because it would be misleading and inaccurate for me to say that everybody who comes to college is out having wild and crazy sex and no one is being responsible or accountable. That&rsquo;s not true. My personal story tells you that&rsquo;s not the case.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&rsquo;ve also known individuals who came to college, or colleagues of mine, who had a lot of repressed sexual feelings. They came from strict, religious homes where they weren&rsquo;t allowed to even talk about sex, let alone have sex. Then, they come to college and it&rsquo;s like a free-for-all! No one there to tell them what to do and what not to do. Someone of the opposite sex starts giving them a little bit of attention, they like the way it feels and then they don&rsquo;t know what to do with those feelings. I would suggest talking these feelings through with someone. These thoughts or feelings aren&rsquo;t something you should keep to yourself because repressed sexual urges and sexual confusion can sometimes hinder you from making good and positive decisions. As humans, sometimes we make decisions based solely on how we feel. Of course we want to make logical decisions, but sometimes, in the midst of a situation, all logic is thrown out the window and feelings rule.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you are unsure about something or if you have questions that are sexual in nature, ask someone! There is nothing wrong with asking questions about your body, sex or anything else you&rsquo;re unsure of. Asking questions is important and you shouldn&rsquo;t feel funny about it. Don&rsquo;t wait and sit on those questions, especially if you&#39;re confused about something.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you need help, there are resources available to you. There is most likely, a local wellness center or clinic on or near campus, Planned Parenthood or a local community center. They have the resources, tools, kits, skills and staff designed to help students navigate this confusing and complicated and sometimes frustrating sexual world. I would highly suggest going and getting counseling at any one of those establishments, should you have questions regarding sex or your body. Issues dealing with sex should not be issues that you keep to yourself. You may end up in a situation where you&rsquo;re embarrassed or where things might not turn out the way you wanted. The situation could have been different if you had gathered some information or had a conversation with a professional.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Another scenario that comes up in college is sexual experimentation with the same gender. There&rsquo;s nothing wrong with this. If someone is going to experiment, it&rsquo;s probably going to happen in college. All the topics discussed in this chapter apply, regardless of who you&rsquo;re having sex with. The gender of your partner is irrelevant in this conversation. Make good choices and have consent!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tips for students:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Don&rsquo;t let one night of pleasure become a lifetime of regrets. What does that mean? I know a lot of people who had babies while they were in college and they didn&#39;t get to finish their education. For them, that one decision, that one night of pleasure had life-altering consequences.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Consent! Consent! Consent! Consent is so important and we don&rsquo;t talk about it enough. NO MEANS NO! Only a sober yes means yes! &ldquo;No means no&rdquo; does not mean &ldquo;no unless you keep bugging me about it until I finally give in due to the pressure and say yes!&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sexual education programs are available on most college campuses and are usually provided by the counseling center or the wellness center. I would encourage all students to go to those classes. They may teach you some things that you would never have known. They teach things like how to properly put a condom on, where to go if you contract an STD, where to get medication or birth control, and how to set up an appointment if you think that you&#39;re pregnant. &nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is not required that you have sex! Just because you&rsquo;re in college, doesn&#39;t mean you have to have sex! Just because it may seem like everyone else is doing it, doesn&#39;t mean you have to do it. Look, I&rsquo;ll keep it &ldquo;100&rdquo; with you, it was <em>extremely </em>difficult to be celibate in college, but in the end, it was the best choice for me.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Parents: What should you do in this situation? How do you guide your son or daughter to make the best decisions? Remember, you&rsquo;re not going to be there with them the entire time so you won&rsquo;t know what your child is doing 24/7.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Have open and honest dialogue about sex. Discuss questions like: What does it mean to be a sexually active young adult? What does having sex in college mean? Should you do it? Should you not do it? What about birth control options? All of these questions are important.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If your child does decide to have sex, don&rsquo;t beat them up about their decision. That&rsquo;s not a good tactic for future open dialogue. If you are lucky enough that your son or daughter opens up and talks to you about sex, please be open-minded and lend them your ear.</p>', '2020-09-07 23:16:17', '2020-09-11 00:01:44', NULL);
INSERT INTO `chapters` (`id`, `course_id`, `name`, `image`, `amount`, `details`, `created_at`, `updated_at`, `deleted_at`) VALUES
(26, 6, 'I’ll Take Safety For 300 Alex', NULL, 20, '<p>It should be of no surprise to anyone reading this book that safety is a major issue and concern on college campuses. There&#39;s theft, there&rsquo;s assault, there could be murder, there&#39;s definitely rape and sexual assault and there are also petty crimes. All of these things can happen on a college campus. I always want to keep my information factual, upfront and honest. This is never intended to scare you or to make you worry. What I hope it does is properly prepare you for what you &ldquo;may&rdquo; encounter. What is surprising is that there are a lot of parents, and students alike, who don&#39;t know these incidents are occurring on campuses; as if college campuses are exempt from these societal behaviors. Let&rsquo;s be honest, there is no place that is absolutely, 100% safe!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I have to laugh when I see college marketing materials that flaunt these impressive statistics like &ldquo;The Ten Safest Schools in the U.S&rdquo;. I think, &ldquo;Sure, they may be safer, but they&#39;re not completely safe.&rdquo; These rankings are determined by statistics and studies regarding the safest campuses - data saying this one has the most police presence, or marketing materials showing students feel most welcome in the community. That&#39;s great, but is the data 100 accurate? Are they taking into account every single crime? The answer to that is no! The answer is no because not all crimes on campuses are reported. In fact, I would even argue that most crimes on campuses aren&rsquo;t reported.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So how do they create these top ten lists? Where does the data come from? What source is the data being collected from? Most institutions pay to have an independent auditor come in and verify that campuses are actually safe. They take a look at the public safety logs and how many students report issues to campus police. They look at whether or not the university is meeting the Clery standards determined in The Clery Act. The Clery Act is a federal statute requiring colleges and universities participating in federal financial aid programs to maintain and disclose campus crime statistics and security information. Then they take all these numbers and they come up with a list of the top ten safest schools for that year.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>College campuses can be a dangerous place, especially for individuals who don&#39;t know what they&#39;re doing or people who aren&rsquo;t paying attention to their surroundings. You could be the victim of anything on a college campus. While there are resources such as: security, administrators, students and staff, remember that college exists in the real world; it&#39;s not exempt from crime solely because it&rsquo;s a college campus. There are a lot of students who go to schools that are located right in a city and I often hear them say, &ldquo;Well, it&#39;s a whole other part of the city; it has like a life of its own, separate from the city.&rdquo; No, it&rsquo;s not separate! It&#39;s in the middle of the city, therefore, it&#39;s a part of the city and crime happens there!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Be aware of what&#39;s going on around you. I had to be self-aware of a lot of different things when I was on campus or off campus. When I was an undergrad, when I would walk at night, I would make sure that I walked in well-lit areas. I would think that some of the women that were on my campus did the exact same thing. I didn&rsquo;t leave my cell phone in the cafeteria on the table to save my spot because someone could easily come through and steal it. I&rsquo;m sure, as the reader, you&rsquo;re not a thief; you wouldn&rsquo;t steal from others. But you don&#39;t know how others were raised or what people are capable of. I see petty theft like this all the time. Students leaving their backpacks, with all their books and their laptop, so they can save a spot in the cafeteria or to save their favorite spot in the union hall. Then, two seconds later, someone snatches up their items and walks away like nothing ever happened. Be aware off your surroundings.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There will be times when you find yourself in a situation that you don&rsquo;t know how to handle or a situation where you don&rsquo;t feel safe. An example of this is one night when I went to a baseball house party at an institution. I remember going into the party, with my friends, the majority of whom were of African-American descent. We had been invited by some young ladies, so we thought that was really cool. When we walked into the party, all the guys in the place just glared at us. Why? Because they didn&rsquo;t feel that we belonged! In fact, they came forward and told us that we didn&rsquo;t belong there. I remember one of the guys came up and said to me, &ldquo;What are you doing here, boy?&rdquo; I just gave him this crazy look like, <em>boy</em>? I had all my friends with me on this particular night so I was probably a little bit more testosterone-filled and big-boy pants filled that night than I normally would be. I said, &ldquo;What do you mean, <em>boy</em>?&rdquo; He said, &ldquo;You heard me, boy!&rdquo; As soon as he said that, four of his friends got up, glaring at me and started moving towards me. At this point, my friends were mingling throughout the party. One of the other guys came up to me and said, &ldquo;You don&#39;t belong here. I suggest you find somewhere else to go.&rdquo; I immediately found my friends and said, &ldquo;Yo. Look, it&#39;s time for us to go. We gotta get out of here.&rdquo; My friends said, &ldquo;No! We just got here. We&rsquo;re having such a great time! It&rsquo;s fine, Justin, chill out!&rdquo; They didn&rsquo;t know what had just transpired. Now our safety was in jeopardy because my friends weren&rsquo;t <em>hearing </em>what I was saying. I remember grabbing one of my friend&rsquo;s arms as tight as I could and I said, &ldquo;Yo! Listen! We gotta roll&hellip;now! Let&rsquo;s all leave!&rdquo; My friends all just gave me the craziest look like, &ldquo;Oookkaayyy, I guess we&rsquo;re leaving?!&rdquo; When we got outside, I explained the situation to them. I said, &ldquo;Look, we were in danger in there.&rdquo; They asked me what I meant. I explained what had happened and then they understood. They said, &ldquo;Oh my gosh, Justin! Why didn&rsquo;t you come and get us and tell us?&rdquo; I explained to them, &ldquo;At that time, all I could think about was - GET OUT OF THIS SITUATION!&rdquo; We didn&rsquo;t know what we were walking into, but think about it, most students don&rsquo;t know when they&#39;re walking into a situation like that. This is why it&#39;s essential that you make sure to pay attention to your surroundings and that you know the people around you.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Being a man on campus is much different than being a woman. There&rsquo;s kind of an unfair advantage being a male because there are a lot of safety issues that men don&rsquo;t have to worry about. I can only imagine how it feels to be a woman on a college campus. Not only do you have to fear walking around by yourself, you have to fear getting cat-called, you have to fear someone trying to sexually assault you, or someone trying to steal from you or grab you. Granted, the data shows us that most sexual assaults occur by someone that the victim knows, not necessarily some creeper that&rsquo;s hiding in a dark alley lying in wait for their next rape victim. That scenario is a folk-tale. Yes, I&#39;m sure those types of situations happen, but that&#39;s not the norm. Chances are, young college women are more likely to encounter a rape or assault situation by someone they know, someone they may be close to, such as a family member or friend. Of course sexual assaults can also just happen randomly. As a woman, how do you ensure your safety when you&#39;re walking around campus? You don&#39;t know everyone who&#39;s hanging around on campus. Do you go with friends? Do you make sure you have your cell phone on you? There&#39;s a lot of different variables to consider.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I remember some of my female friends on campus downloaded this app on their phones. It was like a walk-along-buddy app. The basic gist of the app was, if they had to walk home from the bar and they didn&#39;t want to be by themselves, the phone could connect and you could track your friend as they were walking home to make sure they got home safely. What kind of society do we live in where women have to fear walking around alone? It&#39;s unfair because, as a male, and understanding my male privilege, I didn&#39;t have that same fear. In fact, most people were scared of me when I was walking around at night. I remember walking down the sidewalk and other people walking would jump off the sidewalk before we passed each other or they would cross to the other side of the street. I felt it was because I was a male of color, but that&rsquo;s just my opinion. It&rsquo;s unfair, but it&#39;s a different kind of unfair; I wasn&rsquo;t in danger. When I go out by myself, I don&rsquo;t fear for my life. In some ways I do, as a black male, but as a male, I never have to. Women definitely have that fear and it&rsquo;s unfair.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Let&rsquo;s get back to the topic of theft. Theft is a fairly common occurrence on campus. Make sure you know where your possessions are at all times! Try to make sure that you&rsquo;re not leaving your items, unsecured, in public. Be certain, that if you do have valuables, that they are locked up somewhere safe! I know a lot of students are new to this whole safety subject. In the comfort of their own home, where most of the time their parents were ensuring their safety and paying attention <em>for </em>them, they didn&rsquo;t have to worry about it. I can recall a story at an institution when we had our first year meeting, which almost every residence hall across the country takes part in. It&rsquo;s the first time where all the residents are in the building and all the RA&rsquo;s (Resident Assistants) are present for a first floor meeting. They talk about all the rules and regulations and all the fun things they&#39;re going to do, the hours of the hall, signing out equipment, etc.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>During this particular meeting, Public Safety partnered with our residence life department. They went through each floor and every hallway while the residents were in the meetings downstairs in the lobby. They checked the locks on every door. If they found an unlocked door, they put a sign on it saying, you&rsquo;ve been robbed, please call Public Safety. When the meetings ended, the students went upstairs and of course, went right to their rooms and saw the little hanger on their door saying you&rsquo;ve been robbed. The students were immediately in a panic! &ldquo;Oh my gosh, I got robbed! What do I do? I got that on my door too! Oh my gosh, me too!&rdquo; At that moment, Public Safety would come down the hallway and say, &ldquo;Oh my gosh, what happened?&rdquo; The students explained what they found on their doors. Someone from Public Safety would smile and say, &ldquo;No, you haven&rsquo;t been robbed, but think about how you feel right now? This is exactly how you would feel if you <em>did</em> make the simple mistake of leaving your door unlocked again.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When you move onto a college campus, everybody seems nice, everybody seems friendly and it doesn&rsquo;t appear like anyone would be out to get you or your belongings. You may have been raised to not take things that don&rsquo;t belong to you, but not everybody was raised like that. Always make sure your belongings are safe, guarded and locked up! So, at the end of that story, Public Safety went on to have a small safety program talk with the residents who left their doors open. Theft can happen so quickly, like in this scenario. By the time everybody got done with the first floor meeting, your entire room could have been cleaned out.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Not only can theft happen, in a dorm, by a fellow resident, but residents and other students on campus have been known to steal books. Why steal books? Books are extremely expensive!&nbsp; We&rsquo;ve seen a trend occurring with textbook thefts. Books are being stolen for usually, one of two reasons: For a student to use in their own class, therefore, not having to purchase it themselves and at the end of the semester so the thief can sell them back for money. There are many different outlets where you can sell textbooks back online, or of course, at the campus bookstore. A lot of students rent books so they can get some money back when they return the books. There are also third party companies that just buy books back. If there&rsquo;s a random book &ldquo;sitting there&rdquo;, the company still gives cash for it. There&rsquo;s really no method to trace who the book belongs to. Some students think, &ldquo;Why not? Why not just turn in this book and make a few extra bucks?&rdquo; Then as the victim in this situation, do you even know your book was stolen or does it hit you the next time you need it?&nbsp; Are you going to have to eat the cost because you weren&#39;t paying attention?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Another popular item that is stolen on campuses are bikes. Listen, if you want to get your workout on, that&#39;s great. Use your campus recreation center or campus gym. Some students, depending on how large your campus is, like to bike around campus. Biking is really relaxing, physically beneficial and can help you get to and from classes or events on campus. I myself love to bike and own two bikes. There are some students that think they can leave their bike leaning up against the building and it will be there when they come back out of class. Nope! Don&rsquo;t do it! People steal bikes! Come on people, lock that bike up!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This should go without saying, but lock up that laptop! I see people all the time leaving their laptops in their local coffee shop or in their student union. They may ask someone, &ldquo;Can you watch this while I go to the bathroom?&rdquo; Of course, the other person says yes. Don&rsquo;t do it! You can&rsquo;t just trust individuals that you don&rsquo;t know. Don&rsquo;t leave your items unattended like that.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As mentioned previously, another common and very unfortunate incident that takes place on campuses is sexual assault and rape. Sexual assault and rape are defined separately. Sexual assault can be any unwanted sexual attention or sexual touch, without consent. Rape is defined as an event in which there is sexual penetration, without consent. Notice that both instances are equivalent regarding lack of consent. People don&#39;t like talking about these two topics because sexual assault and rape are such ugly and heinous acts. Think about it, would you like to talk about an extremely uncomfortable and painful event that took place? Be your brother&rsquo;s keeper! Pay attention to your surroundings and to the surroundings of those you love and care for.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Take a second, right now, and think about the one person in this world who you care about the most; the person who you would do anything for, at any time, the person you couldn&rsquo;t live without. Maybe open up your phone, right now, and pull up a picture of them. Picture this person being harmed in the worst possible way. How does this make you feel? It sucks, doesn&rsquo;t it? It&rsquo;s sad and it&rsquo;s depressing. It hurts and it&rsquo;s uncomfortable and heartbreaking. The thought of not being able to help this person, in that situation, is maddening. Now I want you to think about that same person, who you can&rsquo;t live without, in the same horrible situation. This time, think about what if someone had been there and could&rsquo;ve helped change the outcome of the situation, but chose not to. How does this make you feel? You&rsquo;re may be feeling angry, outraged, filled with sadness, because someone chose not to intervene on behalf of the person that you love. What if your loved one was in that horrible situation, but instead someone chose to intervene and help them? How does that make you feel? You probably feel a little bit better; you may even have a sense of relief. You may feel some gratitude and feel thankful that someone selflessly responded on that person&rsquo;s behalf.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sexual assault and rape happen every day on college campuses. These abominable crimes should remind each one of us to pay attention and be aware, not just for ourselves, but for others as well. We should be active in these situations. It&rsquo;s called being a bystander. Being a bystander, as a college student, is paramount. Why? You can&#39;t just stand on the sidelines and watch and allow these and other situations to happen. I&#39;m not just talking about sexual assault and rape. I&rsquo;m also talking about threats and stalking. I&rsquo;m talking about the use of inappropriate language or derogatory language. I&#39;m talking about theft. I&#39;m talking about any incident that prevents or could potentially prevent your campus community from flowing forward in a positive manner where the residents are safely cohabitating in harmony.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We&rsquo;ve all seen things that were wrong and we didn&rsquo;t speak up. Is it because we&rsquo;re scared? Is it because we don&#39;t want to get involved? I know we live in the &ldquo;no snitching era&rdquo; but those concepts have to change. We have to inform people and let someone know if wrongdoings are taking place. Sometimes, we may have to be invasive and take action on our own. I know some people have no problem speaking up for someone and going directly to the individual to impede a particular behavior, but not everyone is like that. If you&rsquo;re not like that and you don&rsquo;t want to get involved, or maybe you don&rsquo;t want to bring attention to yourself, then tell someone who <em>will </em>get involved! Let someone on campus know that the situation is taking place. Tell someone in Public Safety, a college administrator, a coach, someone local in the community. Someone has to know; someone needs to know. That&rsquo;s what being a bystander is all about. Making sure that you are aware of what&#39;s taking place and doing something about it. There are bystander training opportunities that are happening all around the country. One training is called &ldquo;Green Dot&rdquo;, another is called the &ldquo;It&rsquo;s On Us Campaign&rdquo; or the &ldquo;Rape and Sexual Awareness Group&rdquo;. All of these are taking place on campuses all across the country. Are these programs truly making a difference? I would like to think they are, but why don&rsquo;t you involve yourself and then let me know.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I went through a training for sexual assault awareness and I thought it was phenomenal. I didn&#39;t know too much about sexual assault and rape until I was immersed in the actual training. I personally think my lack of knowledge was due to my gender. I don&rsquo;t feel like the male gender is necessarily educated on these topics. I think the education is unequal. Think about what women are taught regarding sexual assault; they&rsquo;re at least taught all of the don&rsquo;ts; Don&rsquo;t go out alone, don&rsquo;t wear this, don&rsquo;t be flirty, don&rsquo;t wear this perfume, don&#39;t be sexually promiscuous, don&#39;t act like you&#39;re coming on to someone. They may as well be taught to wear a burlap bag when they go out so they won&rsquo;t look appealing to men. And men are taught, no means no. Then of course, they sometimes even get a pass on that in the form of &ldquo;boys will be boys&rdquo;. Alcohol doesn&#39;t cause rape; people cause rape. When there are people who are not properly educated, who are allowed to walk around and do whatever they want to do, with no repercussions that can incite the perfect opportunity for rape or sexual assault. We live in a &ldquo;rape culture&rdquo; that says, &ldquo;We don&#39;t want this one person to feel bad about this one crime that they committed! Men will be men, boys will be boys. It happened, its college! She was asking for it with that short skirt she had on.&rdquo; That type of behavior and thinking are unacceptable.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As a campus security authority on my campus, I&#39;ve talked to individuals who have experienced sexual assault or rape. I can&rsquo;t imagine the emotional, physical, and psychological feelings and pain that are associated with a traumatic event like rape. Rape culture suggests that it&#39;s okay, it&rsquo;s a one-time thing or maybe she wanted it or they were both drunk so that makes it okay or kids will be kids, they&rsquo;ll make mistakes. NO! Rape culture is a sociological concept used to describe a setting in which rape is pervasive and normalized due to societal attitudes about gender and sexuality. There should never be an instance where we give a pass to sexual assault or rape. We have to redefine and change that culture and thought process. I&#39;m sorry but we have to call men to the carpet because the majority of rapes that take place on our college campuses are acted out by men; although there are instances of male rape. A person who performs such a heinous act, like sexual assault or rape should be held accountable.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are also instances of sexual assault and rape happening in the LGBTQIA community. Those individuals are also suffering from this trauma and the assault or rape may come with added physical injury as well, especially if the act is part of a hate crime. Many times sexual assault is not reported in the LGBTQIA community at all; either because the person not only has to talk about the assault, but may have to reveal their sexual identity. Some of these individuals may not have come out yet or don&rsquo;t publicly identify with the community. It&rsquo;s almost like a catch-22.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sexual assault and rape aren&rsquo;t necessarily about the actual act of sex. For some offenders it could be about power, control or dominance over another human being. Think about it, there are plenty of ways to have sex, be aroused and ultimately climax or achieve release, but none of that constitutes sexual assault or rape. Trust me, if you&rsquo;re on a college campus and someone says no to having sex with you, there are more than enough other people who probably will say yes. Sexual assault or rape should never, ever be an option. Again, if there&rsquo;s not a sober yes being said, than there&rsquo;s no consent, therefore it&#39;s rape! Sleep it off and revisit the situation when you&rsquo;re both sober.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I know I&rsquo;ve brought up a lot of topics in this chapter that are uncomfortable and a little alarming. You are, no doubt, a little freaked out right now. You&rsquo;re probably wondering how could these things be happening on college campuses? One of the most important notions we can take away from this is to NEVER blame the victims. The victims of sexual assault, victims of theft, and victims of any type of physical assault are not at fault. It&rsquo;s not their fault if an offender makes a poor choice. These people are the victims and survivors of these situations. We should make a very serious effort to equip ourselves and those around us with the best information possible. This will help us be more compassionate and hopefully, help us make more informed choices. It&#39;s not up to the school to make sure that everyone is safe. The school can&rsquo;t be completely protected. Sometimes when I see these situations happen, people are quick to blame the university. Yes, in some cases, the universities are definitely at fault when it pertains to the overall safety of the students on campus, but other times they aren&rsquo;t at fault. We&#39;ve got to give our students the best knowledge and information possible so they can make safe and wise decisions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Let&#39;s talk about some resources that are commonly available on college campuses, across the country that students can use to enhance their safety. Almost all campuses have call boxes. These boxes are there to ensure that a student or bystander can call the university police immediately if they see something bad happening. Of course, if you have your cell phone, you can always dial 911. If you witness a theft, someone being &ldquo;cat-called,&rdquo; or a physical altercation, you should be able to utilize one of these call boxes. Your university police should respond in a timely manner. On a few campuses that I&rsquo;ve worked on, they had an emergency alert system. This could be accessed on your desktop, phone, the website, or through the T.V. monitoring systems located throughout the campus. Emergency alert systems were enabled so that students and staff would automatically know if there was a campus emergency. For example, consider the events that occurred on the Virginia Tech campus in 2007. While there was a mass shooting on campus, many individuals weren&rsquo;t aware that a violent, emergency situation was transpiring. How can we make ourselves more aware of these situations, especially when we need to get to safety?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>These safety measures are not only helpful when it comes to assault, theft, burglary or physical assault, they&rsquo;re also very helpful what it comes to inclement weather. Depending on where you are located, some campuses experience snow storms, hurricanes, tornadoes or even earthquakes. How will you know if the campus is closed or if there&rsquo;s a delay to the campus opening? If your campus has an emergency broadcasting system or emergency alert system, I would highly encourage you to sign up for the alerts to ensure that you get the notifications. It&rsquo;ll take you two seconds to sign up.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You should have Public Safety or campus security&rsquo;s phone number added as a contact in your phone. You never know when an emergency is going to happen and you want make sure that you can call public safety immediately. At the end of the day, situations happen and time is of the essence. We don&#39;t have the ability to say, &ldquo;Oh well, I&rsquo;ll just give it a few minutes to see if someone shows up.&rdquo; or &ldquo;I&rsquo;ll call as soon as I can.&rdquo; Make sure you have them on speed dial. When it comes to the favorites on my phone, Public Safety is definitely on my favorites list. And not just because I&#39;m a campus authority but because I want to make sure that if I do see something, I can help by getting in touch with Public Safety.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We need to talk about Public Safety because Public Safety has a different significance on each college campus. On some campuses, Public Safety has a really good relationship with the students and you&rsquo;ll see Public Safety, physically, around campus. They&#39;re on bikes, on foot, doing rounds in the buildings or in their patrol cars. They have a very friendly relationship with the students. On some campuses, that&rsquo;s not the case. On these campuses, students don&#39;t really like or trust Public Safety. They feel they&rsquo;re just gun-toting individuals who walk around and &ldquo;enforce&rdquo; the law. You also have to understand that some students are coming from a culture or environment where the police aren&rsquo;t trusted and they bring that same mentality to campus. Therefore, their perception of Public Safety or campus police is one of distrust. Regardless of how you feel about Public Safety, their job is to serve and protect. Most importantly, their job is to be visible and to keep you safe. Bottom line, if you see or hear something happening, that you know shouldn&rsquo;t be happening, alert someone. You have to say something and you have to do something. There should be no such thing as, &ldquo;Oh, I saw this happen but I didn&#39;t pay too much attention to it and didn&rsquo;t tell anyone.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&rsquo;m also not exempt from this. I remember one night when I saw an undergrad student walking out of the residence hall with three or four other guys. He was blindfolded and they threw him in the trunk and drove away. Me and my friend were like, &ldquo;What the heck?&rdquo; We were first year students and didn&rsquo;t know what was going on. We didn&rsquo;t know this was some crazy thing that shouldn&rsquo;t happen. We didn&#39;t say anything. Granted, it was probably part of some initiation process but at the same time we probably should have let someone know, but we chose not to. I didn&rsquo;t know enough then, but I know now.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>That&rsquo;s why I&#39;m telling you these stories. Not because I want to seem like, &ldquo;Oh, I&rsquo;m so high and mighty. Let me write this book because I never had any issues.&rdquo; No, I went through these situations. I have colleagues who went through these situations. I travel to colleges all across the country and hear the same stories, over and over. It&rsquo;s up to each one of us to do something. A couple of sentences ago, I said to you, if you see something, say something and do something. This is me telling you again. I wrote this book so you could have an instruction manual; that&rsquo;s me doing something. What are you going to do? What are you going to do to ensure that your campus is safe and you and your peers are making the best possible decisions when it comes to campus safety?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Here are some other tips for students and parents to talk about when engaging in conversations about safety. I&rsquo;m sure some of this information is going to seem trivial, like I&#39;m preaching to the choir, but what may be common sense to you or me, may not be to someone else. It is important to remain safe by using common sense and if something doesn&rsquo;t feel right, it probably isn&rsquo;t.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>*Don&rsquo;t walk down dark alleys or streets alone.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>*Make sure you stay with your friends. Make sure that someone knows where you are, and to check in with individuals. Make sure that you know where you are.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>*If a certain house on campus or certain athletic group or Greek affiliation or any type of student activity group has a reputation that&#39;s not too kosher, maybe that&#39;s not where you should be.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>*Pay attention to the signs. If you see individuals that are too drunk, get them help. If you see someone had their drink messed with, let them know. Speak up!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>*Don&#39;t go home with people you don&#39;t know. I know this sounds self-explanatory and sounds like common sense, but you&#39;d be surprised at the number of people who go home with a stranger at the end of a drunken night. That&rsquo;s completely unsafe for all parties involved.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>*If you&rsquo;re drunk, don&#39;t drive. Just because you&#39;re on campus and you live off campus, don&#39;t think you can drive. Don&rsquo;t think to yourself, &ldquo;Oh I&#39;ve done this plenty of times, I can do it.&rdquo; I can&#39;t tell you the number of DUIs I&#39;ve seen or accidents that have happened due to the consumption of alcohol. Just don&#39;t do it! Don&#39;t risk it! Stay where you are! Here&rsquo;s the thing, when you&rsquo;re out driving while intoxicated, you not only have to worry about yourself but you have to worry about the individuals around you. Be responsible and be accountable.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Why don&#39;t we have conversations about safety? Do we just assume that people know how to be safe? If that&rsquo;s the assumption, then everyone <em>would</em> be safe, right? In this day and age, most individuals are not being mindful of safety. So, if people aren&rsquo;t being safe, where&rsquo;s the breakdown in the passing of information?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Parents, are you teaching your children how to ensure that they&rsquo;re safe-guarding themselves, their belongings and those around them when they&#39;re no longer under your roof? Again, think about the fact that these students are coming to college campuses for the first time. They&rsquo;re only between 18-22 years old; they&rsquo;re young adults. Have you taught them how to protect themselves? Have you taught them what to do if they find themselves in a situation where their safety or other people&rsquo;s safety could be in jeopardy?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Students, I know sometimes you think you&#39;re a grown adult and that you can handle almost anything. Just because you can, doesn&#39;t mean that you should. This chapter is really important because I want individuals to make sure they&#39;re making the best decisions possible when it comes to their safety and the safety of those around them. Unfortunately, sometimes these decisions are regrettable and can&rsquo;t be reversed. Some situations are so bad that individuals completely ruin their entire college experience. Some individuals even have to drop out or transfer to different campuses. All because they&#39;ve made decisions, that if they had been in their right mind, or had more education, they probably wouldn&rsquo;t have made.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This chapter wasn&rsquo;t written to make you fear campus life. No, this chapter was written to ensure that you&#39;re having a dialogue about safety. These are things that you should be talking about. You should really be talking about these things <em>before</em> you even get into college. This isn&rsquo;t to make you look at people sideways and question every single person and situation (Is this person out to harm me? Is this the person who&rsquo;s going to blindfold me and put me in the trunk like Justin was talking about? Is this the person that&rsquo;s going to lace my drink?) I don&rsquo;t think most people are bad. I think that there are individuals who are at college just to have fun, get their education and party a little bit. I would say, for the most part, the majority of students that go out and have fun, do actually get home safely, but it&#39;s not a guarantee. Nothing is guaranteed! Things are not this or that; they&rsquo;re not black or white. There is a gray area. That gray area is you being aware. The gray area is you paying attention to your surroundings. The gray area is making sure that you have the knowledge and information so that you can make the best decisions possible.</p>', '2020-09-07 23:19:13', '2020-09-11 00:01:39', NULL);
INSERT INTO `chapters` (`id`, `course_id`, `name`, `image`, `amount`, `details`, `created_at`, `updated_at`, `deleted_at`) VALUES
(27, 6, 'Hear Those Church Bells Ring', NULL, 20, '<p>As a Christian, this chapter is going to be extremely difficult to write because I&#39;m not able to give both sides on particular issues because of my beliefs. Well, you would think it would be difficult. I expect that throughout this chapter, with what I&#39;ve learned while in higher education, I will be able to give an unbiased view when it comes to spirituality and students. Give it a read and let me know what you think.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Raise your hand if you were born and raised with any type of religion. Okay, I&#39;m guessing that most of you raised your hands. So, how do you apply religion to your everyday life? Is it something that&rsquo;s important to you? Do you actively participate in worship? Is it something that guides your moral compass in life&rsquo;s decision making? Most people are introduced and taught some type of religious belief, starting in childhood. Do you think that practice has changed over the years? The real question I have is, did your spiritual beliefs change while you were in college? As you grow up, mature and develop, values you once believed in, methods that guided your decision and ideals which you knew to be true, can change based on life experiences that have taken place.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For me, as a Christian, it was a no brainer. Jesus died on the cross for my sins. I no longer have to suffer the penalty of hell. I choose to believe in Him. Period! Generally, everyone that I grew up with, in my community, was also a Christian. It never even crossed my mind that I would ever be placed in a position where the majority of the people didn&#39;t feel the same way. I didn&rsquo;t want to go to a Christian school because I went to a Christian church my whole life. While I love church folk, this was my opportunity to branch out and discover new landscapes. I had no concept of the depth of what that truly meant. When I went to college (colleges!), I quickly discovered that the rest of the world doesn&rsquo;t necessarily feel the same way I do. Not everybody believes in Jesus; in fact, a lot of people don&#39;t believe in anything.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you go to school believing that everybody is going to be just like you and have the same beliefs as you, you&#39;ll be in a world of trouble. Like I said, a lot of people that I met in college didn&#39;t believe in anything. You would have loved to have seen my face the first time someone told me that they were an atheist; it was priceless! I had never talked to someone who didn&#39;t have any type of belief. I actually think the atheist student population is on the rise. Many students don&#39;t believe in any type of organized religion and can you blame them? The data and trends that we see across the country show that students see people who are in religious positions or people who take religious stances as very judgmental and mistreating of others. People, namely college students, don&#39;t like that type of behavior!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In today&rsquo;s day and age, I find students are more in the mode of advocacy or activism than they ever have been before. People saying things like, &ldquo;Oh, you&#39;re wrong. You&rsquo;re trying to force people to believe in what you believe in&rdquo;. That is totally against what most students want to experience now. Like I said, going to college was an interesting transition to begin with and then having to question my faith on a daily basis threw another monkey wrench into my day to day living.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Let&rsquo;s talk about my first college party. I can recall walking into someone&#39;s off campus apartment and everybody just welcoming me and my friends with open arms and shaking our hands. There was a lot of drinking going on, there was really loud music playing and there were multiple T.V.&#39;s blaring. There were women walking around, not wearing much clothing; leaving little to the imagination. Growing up as a Christian, this type of scenario, with these visuals wasn&rsquo;t anything I had ever experienced.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I remember walking into one of the rooms where I saw a bunch of guys hunched over a box. Of course I went over to see what was in the box. What do you think I saw? Yup, a gigantic snake in the box! I was like, &ldquo;Whoaaaaa!&rdquo; The guy said, &ldquo;Yeah, he&rsquo;s about to eat. Wait until you see this!&nbsp; We&#39;re taking bets.&rdquo; I replied, &ldquo;Taking bets on what?&rdquo; Then, out of the corner of my eye, I see a guy go into a container and pull out two mice. The guy then took out a permanent marker and on one mouse&rsquo;s back he wrote the number one and on the other mouse&rsquo;s back, he wrote the number two. They held up the mice and everybody started cheering and chanting. I was sitting there wondering what the heck was going on and what the heck was about to happen. They then proceeded to put both mice into the snake box and of course, the snake took notice right away. The snake slowly started stalking towards the mice. Everyone was cheering and screaming. The snake slowly got closer to number two. He was slithering along the side; you could see the panic in the mouse&#39;s face. All a sudden the snake got up and BAM, attacked mouse number two. While he was eating mouse number two, one of the guys took mouse number one out of the box. I guess that would be the snake&rsquo;s meal for the next time he needed to eat.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I had never seen anything like this! So now I&rsquo;ve been to a party where people were drunk, where there were scantily clad women, where there was cursing, where there was betting or gambling, I&rsquo;m fairly certain some underage drinking and probably some drug use happening. Completely different world than I was accustomed to. As a Christian male, with a religious background, how could I learn to navigate this new terrain? How could I learn to morally and socially assimilate into this community that I wasn&rsquo;t raised in? I was basically a foreigner.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As a black male who went to a P.W.I.(which is a predominantly white institution), and having Christian values, I figured the best thing I could do was to immediately attempt to find a church where I could continue to plant my roots and grow in Christ. I grew up in an all-black church, but when I started looking around for a local church in my new western Pennsylvania college area, there weren&rsquo;t many black churches. I decided church is church so I would visit a white church; color doesn&rsquo;t matter. My first visit to an all-white church was interesting, to say the least. In my home church, people are loud and their expression of their love for God is lively and exuberant. Their love for God is shown through song, dance, clapping and verbal praise. When the pastor says something, you respond to the pastor verbally or with a nod of agreement. You may shout out a &ldquo;Hallelujah!&rdquo; Someone might yell out an &ldquo;Amen!&rdquo; When I went to my first white church, everyone was kind of silent and when I yelled out &ldquo;Amen!&rdquo;, everybody just kind of looked at me like I was crazy! I thought, &ldquo;Heeeyyy, I&rsquo;m just trying to serve and worship God!&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The whole experience was intriguing. There was such a contrast in the way church people behaved and I couldn&rsquo;t understand it; we&rsquo;re all of the same faith. At that moment, I was trying to figure out what the faith meant to me in this new environment. Now that I wasn&rsquo;t beside Mom and Dad, what did the faith really mean to me? Was it something that was truly for me, that I absolutely believed in? Or was it something that I was just doing because that&#39;s what I was taught and that&rsquo;s what I knew?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I tried the Christian organization on campus; some people call them, &ldquo;Campus Crusade for Christ (or Cru)&rdquo; and it simply wasn&rsquo;t for me.&nbsp; I&#39;m a Christian and I love Christ just as much as the next person, but not every single Christian group is something you&rsquo;ll find interest in. I was learning this first hand. I felt like the people in &ldquo;Cru&rdquo; were way too happy for me; something wasn&rsquo;t right! Now look, I was happy that I was going to heaven, but I wasn&rsquo;t <em>that </em>happy! I really needed to figure this out.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Luckily for me God knew (as usual) exactly what I needed. He sent someone into my life at the exact time I needed it. I try to change people&#39;s names in my books and titles, but I figure, in this case, it was best to keep his real name. This guy&#39;s name is Michael Thornhill and he&rsquo;s a great guy! Michael Thornhill was a colleague of mine who transferred from a Christian college to a secular college. This is a very interesting story and if you ever get the chance to meet Michael, you should definitely ask him about his story. It couldn&rsquo;t have been a more opportune time for God to send him my way. At that time, I was really struggling with my faith. I was being tempted with so many new and different obstacles and challenges: women, drugs, alcohol, sex. I didn&#39;t really have anybody in my corner; someone who would hold me accountable and make sure I was still following God. I remember the day that Michael Thornhill arrived on campus. He came up to me and said, &ldquo;Hey. How you doing? I&rsquo;m Michael Thornhill.&rdquo; I said, &ldquo;Hey. I&rsquo;m Justin Brown.&rdquo; Michael said, &ldquo;Yeah, everyone told me to come talk to you. They said you&rsquo;re the guy who runs stuff around here. You&#39;re the guy that knows everything about the campus inside and out.&rdquo; I responded, &ldquo;Yeah. I guess you could say that.&rdquo; He said, &ldquo;I&rsquo;ve also been told that I&#39;m the Justin Brown of my former campus and that you&rsquo;re the person I&#39;m supposed to connect with.&rdquo; Since I had just met him, I didn&rsquo;t know much about him and didn&rsquo;t quite know how to take that statement. But I can tell you this, &ldquo;God definitely doesn&#39;t make mistakes, nor does HE <em>not</em> send individuals to you, on your behalf, from HIM.&rdquo; I knew that Michael was that person that God had sent me, right when I needed him. We talked about our faith. I remember thinking how serious Michael was about his faith, versus how I was with mine. Now, after getting to know him a little, I was confused. I asked myself, &ldquo;Was I just going through the motions or did I really want to serve God? Did I really want to follow the path that God wanted me to do?&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There was something Michael said to me that I will never forget and I doubt that he even remembers having this particular conversation, but if he does, he probably doesn&rsquo;t realize the significance and impact he had or how his words affected my life. One day, we went out to eat at this awesome place in the local town. If you ever get to Slippery Rock University, you have to eat at this delicious place called Bob&rsquo;s Subs. Michael was talking to me about faith. He asked me if I was going to church and I told him, &ldquo;I&rsquo;ve tried a few churches in the area but I haven&rsquo;t found a good fit. I tried singing and praise dancing in the churches, but the people kind of just looked at me like I was crazy! I don&#39;t think I&#39;ll be trying any more churches out here in this area.&rdquo; Michael said, &ldquo;I would challenge you to give some other churches a chance or try to find the church that&#39;s the best fit for you, while you&rsquo;re here.&rdquo; I looked at him like &ldquo;No, dude, I tried all the churches.&rdquo; Michael looked right in my face and said, &ldquo;How seriously do you want it? How seriously do you want to please God? How seriously do you want to exercise and participate in your faith?&rdquo; I remember Michael telling me, &ldquo;Look, in America, we have liberties that others around the world don&#39;t have. There are people being hunted down, exposed and killed in other countries for their beliefs and their faith. Yet, here in America, we have the freedom to believe what we want and we take that freedom for granted.&rdquo; When he said that to me, it really hit home and made me think.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As college students, sometimes you have to think about forming your own morals and values, outside of mom and dad. At this point, I didn&rsquo;t have my mom and dad beside me through these new experiences and temptations. I was going through persecution and I was going through it alone. I needed to find my own way. I had to rely on everything that I was taught, everything that was instilled in me as a child so I could return back to it when I walked away. That was the day that kicked me in my butt and jump-started me right back into my faith. Not that I had ever lost my faith, but I wasn&#39;t actively practicing. I wasn&rsquo;t actively talking to God. Ever since then, I continued to walk forward in God&rsquo;s steps.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I know some of you who are reading this chapter don&#39;t believe in God or you might not be a Christian and that is perfectly fine! This is okay because this is an opportune time to reflect on your own spiritual beliefs. How are you handling your new environment AND the beliefs you have? If you don&rsquo;t have any beliefs, what are your values? I&rsquo;m asking this because what I&rsquo;ve noticed is that there are so many students who don&rsquo;t believe in anything. This may be because of their upbringing or events that have taken place in their life or just the world in general. I&rsquo;m not saying you have to believe in God, but having a belief system or at the very least a set of values to draw from can certainly help you live your day to day life; especially in a new environment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A lot of people, regardless of whether you&rsquo;re a college student or not, have gone to religious organizations and have been judged, turned away, or had a church, synagogue or temple turn their back on them. This action goes against every single thing that the faith stands for. This could, absolutely, cause people to not want to believe or be a part of anything. Why would you want to believe in an organized religion that treats people the exact way they&rsquo;re telling people on the outside not to? If their claim is to treat their neighbor with kindness and they fail to do so, who would want to be a part of that? It seems hypocritical, right?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Many of you may not believe in God and that&rsquo;s understandable. There&#39;s a huge part of this chapter that&#39;s about you. My question to you is: if you don&#39;t believe in God, that&#39;s fine but what do you believe in? Do you believe in yourself?&nbsp; Do you believe in your own abilities? Do you believe in the cosmos of the universe to come up with decisions that are going to help you or guide your moral compass? Or do you just walk around lost? By lost, I don&rsquo;t mean you don&rsquo;t know what you&rsquo;re doing or where you&rsquo;re going, but do you feel a sense of purpose? If you don&rsquo;t have a sense of purpose, where do you find it? What guides you? If you don&rsquo;t have any guiding principles, how do you move forward in life?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The people who are atheists or the people who don&#39;t believe in anything or don&#39;t have any faith, they&#39;re not bad people. They&rsquo;re not individuals who can be measured on a scale of good or bad. I do have some questions, though. Why have people gotten to this place of no faith? Atheists that I&rsquo;ve talked to, in my opinion, are atheists because they truly don&#39;t see any signs of God or they don&#39;t see how God works in and through people&#39;s lives. They need to see some hard, tangible evidence. They don&rsquo;t believe in the faith, because believing in faith alone is putting all your hopes and dreams into something that you can&rsquo;t see, touch or feel. As a human being and as a Christian, I get that; it makes sense, its logical! I don&rsquo;t think there&rsquo;s a big difference between Christians and atheists. As a Christian, sometimes I&rsquo;ve doubted my faith. I&rsquo;ve doubted whether God was with me or if God had played a significant part in my life. Or if I prayed and it didn&rsquo;t work out like I asked, I&rsquo;ve wondered if God was really listening, as if God is a genie who&rsquo;s supposed to listen to my commands when I ask. So I get it.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Some people don&#39;t believe in religious organizations anymore because some individuals who represent religious organizations judge and persecute; they don&#39;t act any different than anybody who&#39;s on the outside. I personally know people like that in religious organizations. So yes, there are a lot of things that the atheists feel or believe that I also feel or believe, as a God-fearing Christian. That shows me that we&#39;re not all that different. We might be different in what we actually believe but we&rsquo;re not fundamentally different. How does all of this play out for college students? All of these individuals live together and are supposed to thrive together as a community. How can that work?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Regardless of what you believe, making a definitive decision is important. Are you going to make the decision to believe what you want to believe or are you going to believe in what you&rsquo;re taught to believe?&nbsp; For those who are going to college, who have religious backgrounds but now mom and dad can&#39;t force you to go to mass, church, synagogue, temple or wherever, you have to make a decision for yourself. How real is it going to be for you? I would highly recommend that you remember what you were taught. College is a huge playground for sin. It&rsquo;s a huge playground for experimenting. Things happen in college that you would probably never normally be exposed to. Remember what you were taught. Remember the values and morals that were instilled in you.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Again, it&#39;s up to you to make the decision of what you believe in. No one can do that for you.&nbsp; Ultimately, you&#39;re going to be held accountable for the decisions that you made. Therefore, pay attention to the decisions and choices you&rsquo;re making and don&rsquo;t just think you&rsquo;re in college and you&rsquo;re grown so your faith doesn&rsquo;t matter anymore. That&rsquo;s not what college life is about. It&rsquo;s more about the things that you were taught growing up and everything up to this point: do you still want to continue to hold true to your values? Or do you want to change your values to what you want them to be?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&rsquo;m sure most parents reading this chapter will be saying, &ldquo;No. My child is going to do this or my child is going to do that.&rdquo; You have to understand, during this time, your child is going to change; they will be different when they come back to your house. They&rsquo;re not going to be the same person. In fact, most kids have to be retaught by their parents and relearn some lessons because they&#39;re completely different when they return back to you. The person who you dropped off at college may not be the same person that comes home. Parents, be flexible. Be understanding. Have open and engaging conversations with your children. The conversations shouldn&rsquo;t be judgmental and they shouldn&rsquo;t be a smack-down. Your kids are trying to figure out who they are and where they belong in this crazy world. They need you during this transition. It won&rsquo;t help if you disparage your child when they make a choice you don&rsquo;t agree with. I&rsquo;m not saying let them do whatever they want; not at all. When I came home, I couldn&#39;t just tell my parents, &ldquo;Oh, hey, when I&rsquo;m at college I come home at 2am so I&rsquo;ll be home around 2am.&rdquo; It doesn&rsquo;t work like that. There are still rules. In my parents&rsquo; house, as long as I lived under my father&#39;s roof, I was going to follow his rules. At the same time, we were able to have some open and honest conversations about what was going on and what I wanted to do. For example: &ldquo;Hey dad. I think I&rsquo;m going to go out to this party tonight. The party doesn&rsquo;t start until such and such time. I know the house rules are that I need to be home by such and such time, but would you mind if I did this tonight?&rdquo; Having an open dialogue with your child makes for a more harmonious living environment; not only for your children, but for you as well. I also want to note, not everyone comes from a family that allows this type of dialogue. Some households would never support the student negotiating a change in the rules like I mentioned. This is why parents need to understand that with the change and development your child is going through in college, some things may need to change.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are several things that I would highly recommend for students who want to continue practicing their faith while on campus. I would suggest getting involved in the religious organizations that are on campus. They meet regularly and are set up and designed to talk to college students about their college experience and how the experience affects their beliefs and their faith. They go on excursions and trips. They worship together. These organizations can be invaluable to the students on campus who crave what they may be missing from their home-based religious organization. If your faith is something you want to continue while on campus, know that there are options available. For people like me, who feel a bit odd at some of these religious organizations and may think, &ldquo;Hey, these people are weird, I don&rsquo;t want to be a part of this,&rdquo; sometimes you have to step out on faith. I remember finding some of the students of color, on campus, who kind of worshiped the same way I did, so we all went to church together. We started our own Bible study and <em>that </em>worked for me. Figure out what works best for you.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Whether you&rsquo;re a student who does practice the beliefs of a particular faith or a student who does not, I would also suggest that you branch out and expose yourself to different cultures. During my time at school, while I wasn&#39;t changing my faith or changing my beliefs, I was very interested in how other religions and people of different faiths worshipped: how they collectively came together and how they worship their God. I&rsquo;ve gone to mosques. I&#39;ve gone to temples. I&rsquo;ve gone to a synagogue. I once went to a religious event, which was part of a faith I had no clue about, and I felt it was beneficial in helping me understand that particular faith. A good friend of mine invited me to a Seder dinner, which is a Jewish custom. The Seder is a feast that includes reading from the old testament, drinking wine, telling stories, eating special foods and singing; it&rsquo;s a tradition for people of the Jewish faith.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I participated in the entire Seder dinner: eating the bitters, partaking in eating the lamb and going through the entirety of the rituals. I thought it was great! My Jewish friend told me all about his background, explaining why they did this or why they did that. While the experience didn&rsquo;t change my views about what I believe in, it allowed me to learn about a different faith and their traditions. For some people, this experience I participated in might alarm you and may even cause you to ask, &ldquo;How could you ever step foot in a synagogue or go to a mosque or temple? You&rsquo;re a Christian!&rdquo; My advice to those people would be - learning doesn&#39;t take away from what you believe. If anything, learning helps you to be more appreciative of what you believe and also helps you be a globally-minded individual. If you came to campus so you could only hang out with people who look like you, go to classes with people who think like you and become friends with people who act like you, then you&rsquo;re wasting your time and, more importantly, you&rsquo;re wasting your money. A big part of college is learning about and understanding other individuals&rsquo; backgrounds, cultures and beliefs. I would suggest taking the time to get to know other people. Go to their houses, go to their religious organization, try some of the food from their culture and pay attention to the language. All of these elements help form you into a better, well-rounded person; they make you a more globally diverse student which benefits you and those around you.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In life, good things happen and of course, bad things happen too. There are going to be people on your campuses who don&#39;t understand your faith. They won&#39;t understand why you believe what you believe and they are going to challenge you. I remember telling people on campus that I was a Christian and people tried to ask me questions that were almost impossible for me to answer. They would ask questions such as, &ldquo;Okay, well if Christ is <em>your </em>God, how come you haven&rsquo;t seen him?&rdquo; or &ldquo;What about the times when you prayed to God and he didn&#39;t answer your prayers?&rdquo; or &ldquo;How does Jesus say don&#39;t drink alcohol, yet he drank wine?&rdquo; It was as if they were trying to trip me up.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Growing up as a P.K. (Preacher&rsquo;s kid) was challenging. It was difficult trying to maintain my faith and balance what the world offered. Attempting to be a role model to others was tough, while trying to answer everyone&#39;s suspicious questions. Here&rsquo;s the thing: no one knows <em>everything</em> about their religion. My dad is a pastor and sure, most of the time when I ask him a question, he knows the answer, but there are times he doesn&rsquo;t. He&rsquo;ll go and do some research or go to the word of God and figure it out. You&rsquo;re going to find that there are a lot of people in school that will try to challenge you; they&rsquo;ll try to make you rethink your faith or try to make you feel like you&rsquo;re not as big of a believer as you think you are. My feeling is, if you don&rsquo;t know the answer, you should say, &ldquo;Hey, I don&#39;t know the answer, but we can figure it out together.&rdquo; That type of reply can change the outlook of the conversation. Understand that there are going to be some people who want to make you feel that your beliefs are inadequate, simply because they don&rsquo;t agree with you. That&rsquo;s not cool!&nbsp; For those people who don&#39;t believe, listen, I feel you; I get it. I&rsquo;m not discounting anything you say. We can still respect each other.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When I was in college, I met a lot of people who didn&#39;t have any type of religious faith or background, but their reasoning was sound and it made sense. People would say to me, &ldquo;I&rsquo;m not a Christian. I don&#39;t believe in God because my mom died at a young age.&rdquo; or &ldquo;I don&#39;t believe in God because I&#39;m gay and Christians hate gays.&rdquo; When I thought about these types of comments, I thought, &ldquo;Well, I have gay friends and I don&#39;t hate them.&rdquo; But there are people who just assumed and assigned that opinion to me because I am a Christian. That type of judgement is hurtful to all parties involved. I feel sad for people who have never given God the chance to show all that He can do. I feel bad for people who have a negative view of God. It pains me to know that they think that everybody who believes in God, everybody who believes in Jesus, acts and thinks just like that. I&#39;m here to tell you, I understand why you might feel like that, but it&rsquo;s not the truth! I understand why people who have had unfavorable experiences in the church don&rsquo;t believe. Please know that it doesn&rsquo;t have to be like that.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Some of the stories I heard involved people who made decisions not to go church because they felt that the church turned its back on them. Or maybe they went through an unplanned pregnancy and the church talked bad about them or about their family. What kind of church is that? If you think about your past, when it comes to any type of religious organization you&#39;re probably thinking the same thing: &lsquo;Yup, see, this is exactly why I don&#39;t go.&rsquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Listen, not every single religious organization is like that. I don&#39;t belong to a &ldquo;religious organization&rdquo;; to me Christ is more than just a building. This is something I believe in, it&#39;s a lifestyle; it&rsquo;s following what Christ said. He said he wanted me to go into a body of believers where I can learn, grow and be held accountable, which is why I go to church. Everyone&#39;s reason for going to church is different. But I want you to know that if similar, negative situations or anything like that has happened to you, I&#39;m sorry. Christians are just like people of the world. Why? Because they are people of the world. Sometimes they do try to act like they&#39;re better and that they&#39;re without fault, but no Christian is perfect; just like no one else is perfect in the world. Christians sin, they gossip, they can be judgmental; all of those faults are the same as other people. So when you say those things about Christians, you are absolutely correct. As a Christian, I want to say that you&#39;re right. However, for the most part, at least from what I&#39;m shown, (and again, I can also be biased because I am a Christian) the thing about Christianity that might just be a little different is that people who are of the Christian faith are trying to do something different about their lives. At least they are trying too. They aren&rsquo;t perfect, but they are trying. Don&rsquo;t base your opinion on one person or one experience.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Another point, I don&rsquo;t just listen to what Christians say. Christians can say whatever they want, I watch what Christians do! If you&rsquo;re considering a different faith or you&rsquo;re considering changing or discovering something new while you&#39;re in college, I would recommend that you do it.&nbsp; Watch how people live. If you&rsquo;re part of a student group and they welcome you into their fold, watch what they do and how they treat others.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Being a student, with a religious background, is definitely an interesting experience when you get to campus. You&rsquo;re going to go through a whole lot of changes. You&#39;re going to question things that you have done or are doing. That doesn&rsquo;t make you a bad person. You <em>should </em>question, but you should also constantly be seeking God. If you come to college and everything&#39;s just fine, then that makes me question how close you are with God in the first place.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I can recall one night at my college, the dance majors had a lingerie party and they invited me to it. I probably shouldn&rsquo;t have gone, but I did. The whole time I was there I was thinking, would God be pleased that I was here? In the flesh, yeah, I was happy to participate in this new experience, but I wondered how God felt. Still today, I would probably tell you that that party was awesome and unbelievable! But, think about it, why were college students even having a party like that? Why did I feel that I needed to be part of it?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you&#39;re trying to continue your faith when you come to campus, I briefly suggested earlier in this chapter that you check out the Christian organizations which are prominent on most college campuses. I&#39;ve been to Campus Crusade for Christ and I&#39;ve been to Cru. Any type of higher education institution probably has some religious organization that will fit your needs. For me, when I went to those organizations, they didn&#39;t really fit my needs. In fact, I felt really out of place and those people were Christians and so was I. What I had to do was find my own way of being able to grow with my peers, without having to go through the organizations that already existed. I found people on campus, who I felt were just like me and who had the same beliefs that I did.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Not only will you find organizations that help with faith, you&#39;ll also find organizations that want to help tear down your faith. I remember there were two atheist organizations on my campus. I&rsquo;m sure a lot of you are thinking, &ldquo;How could you have two atheist&rsquo;s organizations?&rdquo; Well, one of the atheist groups was designed to say, &ldquo;Hey, we don&#39;t know what we believe; we just know that we believe in something&rdquo;; which, in my opinion, is more agnostic than anything. The other atheist group was specifically geared towards tearing down the religions of other people. Wow! No matter which organization or religion you&rsquo;re affiliated with, I don&#39;t believe any of them teach hate. I don&#39;t believe that any of them teach berating other people or demeaning other people.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You&#39;ll start to realize that even though you believe in <em>your </em>God, that a lot of the concepts are similar when compared. God wants to heal you, God is loving, God wants you to be part of something that&#39;s bigger than you. He wants you to rely on Him instead of relying on yourself. For any of those organizations that are developed based on hate, I don&#39;t believe that those organizations are religiously grounded or have any type of religious roots. Pay attention to those types of behaviors or activities because there are also cults on college campuses and students are some of the easiest individuals to prey on and are easily susceptible. If you&rsquo;re really trying to figure out what organization to believe in or what organization to be a part of, do some research and watch what people do, not necessarily what they say.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I can remember, on multiple campuses that I&#39;ve been to, that once a week, in the quad, they would have a campus preacher. If you&rsquo;re on a campus or have been on a campus in the past, you can probably recall a similar scenario. The campus preacher comes to campus, preaches the word of God, right out of the book. They normally preach from the Old Testament, which talks about gloom and doom &ndash; turn back from your sin now or you will receive the fiery brimstone known as Hell. Yeah, that&rsquo;s not how to win people to Christ; students weren&rsquo;t going for that. In fact, I think that the campus preacher if anything, deterred students from accepting any type of religious background or faith.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There was one organization on one of the campuses that I worked at who actively came to campus, a public institution, and would preach hate. That&rsquo;s literally what they preached&hellip;.hate! I don&#39;t know what kind of group it was. Their goal was to incite a riot on campus so that students would fight them. They did this because they were protected by the First Amendment and if a student struck them on campus, they could then sue the institution. They had nothing to do with religion or any belief system whatsoever. These people were scammers and their main goal was to sue institutions; which they had done and gotten a big payday. So, students would beat them up and the cops would come and they would sue the campus. They would get in their Lamborghini and drive away. Come on, now! These people said they were there representing God; I don&rsquo;t think so! If you&rsquo;re a believer, you know that&rsquo;s not true.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Students, watch out for religious fanatics; they&#39;re everywhere! They want you to believe what they believe and they&#39;re super crazy! Listen, I&#39;m a Christian and I love God but I would be lying if I said that I 100% eat, breathe, sleep and poop God. It doesn&rsquo;t happen that way. I&#39;m human. I have imperfections. There are times when I&#39;m not keeping God in the forefront of my mind and life. There are times when I do things that are not very godly. If anything, I feel like that makes me more human and definitely more relatable. My suggestion is to watch out for those people who act like they don&#39;t have any faults and everything that they do is for God. Look for people who are genuine and authentic when they talk to you about their God. Honestly, these are probably the individuals that have a better scope and understanding of what it means to have faith and beliefs in something other than the world or themselves. Watch out for hate groups; they exist, don&rsquo;t join them! They&rsquo;re only there for the hate! Hate isn&rsquo;t cool, don&rsquo;t drink the &ldquo;haterade&rdquo;!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Know that your experiences, in regard to your faith, are never going to be the same as someone else&rsquo;s. People may share their journey of faith with you. It will not be the same as your journey! I know a lot of people said that when they came to college, they started to question God or question their religious background. That doesn&#39;t make you a bad person and it doesn&rsquo;t make you less than any other person in your faith. What it means is that you&#39;re human. If you&#39;re not questioning your faith, if you&rsquo;re not growing, if you&rsquo;re not having any doubts, that only shows that maybe you didn&rsquo;t have much faith to begin with. Even the strongest Christian or the strongest Muslim or the strongest Jewish person or the strongest whatever, has questions and doubts. We have to have true and authentic relationships with <em>our </em>God.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Your faith may be tested in college. God might put you through some serious tests while you&rsquo;re in college. I was definitely put through the ringer. Was my faith tested? Absolutely! But it was tested for a reason. It was tested to help me grow. It was tested to teach me patience and to teach me how to rely on Him and not myself. It was tested to teach me how to withstand seduction and stand in the midst of adversity and temptation. And most importantly, it was tested to show me what Michael Thornhill was trying to show and teach me, all the way from the beginning. How badly do you want it?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Do you believe in a God? Do you have a moral compass? Are there things that give you hope when you wake up in the morning? For me, I pray before I go to bed with the hope and the faith that God will keep me and protect me throughout the night so that I&rsquo;ll be able to get up the next morning to continue to praise Him.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '2020-09-07 23:19:51', '2020-09-11 00:01:51', NULL);
INSERT INTO `chapters` (`id`, `course_id`, `name`, `image`, `amount`, `details`, `created_at`, `updated_at`, `deleted_at`) VALUES
(28, 6, 'I’m Just Depressed, No Big Deal', NULL, 20, '<p>I know a lot of you are probably thinking right now, &ldquo;How is Justin possibly going to write an entire chapter about depression?&rdquo; I can do it because depression and mental health are such complex issues that the topics can&#39;t possibly be covered in just a few pages. If you were thinking that thought, you are absolutely correct. It would be socially and academically irresponsible of me not to mention and explore depression because depression is real! That&#39;s right everybody, depression is real! For those of you who have gone through it, those who currently experience it or know someone who suffers from it, you know that it can change your entire outlook on life, your entire chemical make-up and your social perspective when it comes to dealing with other people. You may be asking yourself, &ldquo;Why is he saying it&#39;s real? Of course, it&#39;s real. Who would think that it&rsquo;s <em>not </em>real?&rdquo; You would be surprised that a lot of people think depression is not real.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sometimes when students are having a blue day or collection of bad days, they may come and chat with me. I usually say something to them like, &ldquo;Have you ever talked to anyone from the counseling center or have you talked to a therapist? You could be depressed.&rdquo; Some students are immediately in denial. &ldquo;No! I don&rsquo;t think depression is a real thing. I just need to get over this hump or I need to pray more or it&#39;s all in my head. I&rsquo;ve been thinking some negative thoughts lately. I simply need to think more positively.&rdquo; In some cases, those students are absolutely right. But when we see a prolonged negativity, consistent behavior of having down days, not acting like yourself, personality shifts, separating and isolating yourself from students, your peers and colleagues, changes in eating and sleeping habits, lack of interest in things that once brought you joy, or lack of normal interaction and conversation with others, it can be deduced that maybe there is a depression issue.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are a few tricky things when it comes to depression and if you&rsquo;ve ever gone through depression or seen someone with depression, you can probably relate. First, you never know when depression is going to manifest. For some people, like myself (and we&rsquo;ll get into that later in the chapter), you may have something called Seasonal Affective Disorder or seasonal depression. This is when everything is fine as long as the sun is out. If the sun is shining, you&rsquo;re doing great, you&#39;re flying high. But, when the season changes and the weather starts to change, when it gets a little colder, daylight is shorter, maybe the snow has started, the sky is filled with dark clouds and the sun is blocked out, you may start to feel depressed. It&#39;s not a choice, it just happens. As the seasons change, so does your mood, your attitude and your actions. The other concept is, if you&rsquo;ve been through depression, you know that it can sneak up on you.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Regardless of if the depression is seasonal or not, depression doesn&#39;t have a set time or day when it happens. It doesn&#39;t work like that. For students who are used to life happening like clockwork or if you are timeframe oriented, throwing depression into the mix can be devastating. Depression is not something you can necessarily plan for; it just happens. It can occur due to unfortunate events that have happened in your life, like doing poorly on a test or having someone in your family pass away. There are many reasons depression can occur and it can hit anyone! Depression isn&rsquo;t partial to a certain race, gender, sexual orientation or religion. Depression has no names. It can harm or affect anyone!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sometimes, when your depression is nearing, you may not even recognize it. Why is that? When it comes to college students, depression can look like a few different moods. Depression can look like homesickness, drug or alcohol issues, an eating disorder or suicidal or negative thoughts, actions or behaviors. You all know that one person who is insanely negative, about EVERYTHING! Yes, depression can also look like that too. But sometimes, depression just looks like depression.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We need to break these myths that depression is this notion where students are walking around acting like Eeyore from Winnie the Pooh or with dark rain clouds over their head. Sometimes the person doesn&#39;t look like that. Sometimes the person appears to be happy, a person who doesn&#39;t seem to let anything bother them or a person who doesn&rsquo;t seem to have anything wrong going on in their life. Sometimes depression can resemble a type of hopelessness when a student, all of a sudden, thinks, &ldquo;I don&#39;t need any of my stuff anymore. Go ahead and take something of mine that you like and you&rsquo;ll remember me by.&rdquo; That doesn&#39;t sound like someone who&#39;s depressed; that sounds like someone who might be suicidal. Depression can take form in someone who hasn&rsquo;t eaten for a while or someone who binge eats. Trends show that losing weight isn&rsquo;t traditionally what happens to college students. The majority of college students come to campus and <em>gain </em>weight. We&rsquo;ll talk more about weight gain in another chapter.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I remember a situation when I was &ldquo;on call for duty rotation&rdquo; at an institution. I received a phone call from Public Safety to go to a certain building and check on a particular student. For this story, we&rsquo;ll call this student Brett. Brett&rsquo;s friends had placed a call to Public Safety. They made the call because they felt Brett was acting irrationally. He was saying things that made them uncomfortable. Most of the people involved with the call had been friends with Brett back in their hometown, through high school and now in college. Here they were, in their sophomore year in college, and they felt that Brett was acting really odd. Brett basically had an emotional breakdown. He was exhibiting random behavior like, trying to shower from the toilet, standing over them as they were sleeping and having some really weird conversations that they couldn&rsquo;t make any sense of. He was having some mental health issues and possibly depression. I&rsquo;m certain that depression played a part in the final outcome of his breakdown. I remember meeting with Brett and talking with him. He told me he wasn&rsquo;t Brett but that he was God Brett and unless I called him God Brett, he was not going to respond to me. I needed to help him, so I called him God Brett; it sounds a little silly but that&rsquo;s what he needed at that time. He told me that he wasn&rsquo;t doing well in school and he said there were a bunch of things that were going wrong in his life, but he also said that he felt great. Throughout our conversation, he never broke his smile; it was almost forced. When I looked him in the eyes, they appeared empty; like he wasn&rsquo;t really there.&nbsp; Ultimately, God Brett took some time off, away from campus; to get himself back together psychologically. I want to tell you that the God Brett situation, not necessarily all of it, is a scenario that is happening to students on college campuses.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;Mental health is a real situation. Students need to take care of themselves, not only physically and intellectually, but also mentally. What does this mean? I know that school comes with a lot of pressure and demands on the students, especially for a student who has never had that type of pressure. We find students, coming to campus, who were able to breeze through high school easily, not study, come in, take the test and do well. In fact, some of their high schools were so small that they were probably the best in their class. Then they come to college and they&#39;re meeting the best people from all around the country and the game is a little different. Now they actually have to study, read the textbooks and take notes. Sometimes students are learning these skills for the first time, in college; not when they should have learned them in K-12. Some of this creates a lot of stress and pressure and some students can&#39;t take the pressure. Not being able to handle this pressure can absolutely hurt or harm students, especially during this transitional time, when they&#39;re trying so hard to be successful in this new environment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Support from your loved ones is important. I say this because one thing I&rsquo;ve noticed in my years in college and working on a campus is there is not enough open and honest conversation between students and their families. A lot of parents will call their student and ask, &ldquo;Hey, how are you doing?&rdquo; And the student will respond with, &ldquo;Everything is great!&rdquo; This is another reason I thought this book would be beneficial. Parents need to be aware of the situations that are happening on our campuses. Parents should be aware and be able to address this with their son or daughter. Parents usually call their students once a day, once every other day, or once a week. Here is a typical phone conversation between a parent and their child.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The conversation goes as follows:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mom: Hey Johnny. How are you doing?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Johnny: Oh, hey mom. I&rsquo;m doing good.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mom: Great, great. How are classes?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Johnny: Classes are going well.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mom: Okay. So you&rsquo;re doing okay? You&rsquo;re making friends?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Johnny: Doing okay mom. Making friends. Everything&rsquo;s good.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mom: Do you need anything?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Johnny: No, I don&rsquo;t need anything mom.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mom: Great! Well, I&rsquo;ll talk to you soon. Bye.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Little does Johnny&rsquo;s mom know, there are some bigger issues that are going on with Johnny. Johnny&#39;s parents aren&rsquo;t even aware of the situations that are going on until the next time they call Johnny and Johnny doesn&rsquo;t pick up. And they try to call Johnny again and he doesn&rsquo;t answer&hellip;again. Then the parent goes on Johnny&rsquo;s social media to see if they can figure out what&rsquo;s going on. This brings up another subject. Parents, although I&rsquo;ve previously mentioned allowing your child to figure out life on their own, if you see a dramatic change, you may want to be a bit more intrusive; especially, considering your child is away at school. You can&rsquo;t necessarily be intrusive with their academics, because as we know, The Family Educational Rights and Privacy Act<strong> </strong>prevents us, as professionals, from giving you that information, but be intrusive when it comes to their development. Going away to college is a huge change for students; socially, psychologically and mentally. Be aware of any shifts in your child&rsquo;s behavior. We, as student affairs professionals, are paying attention too; you are not alone.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are plenty of ways to alleviate mental health and depression related issues. Some people believe that you can fix the issues through prayer and, yes, sometimes that can work. While prayer can definitely help a mental health or depression situation, it&rsquo;s not a guaranteed fix. Sometimes the person needs a little more than prayer. Sometimes medication is necessary.&nbsp; I say medication with pause. I am not an advocate for anyone going out and buying pills on their own, off the street. That&rsquo;s not safe. I understand how the pharmaceutical companies work: they want you to keep buying pills, buying pills and buying more pills, until you can&rsquo;t live without them. That is not what I&rsquo;m suggesting. What I am suggesting, is that if someone does have a chemical imbalance, they might need some help which can only happen with the aid of prescribed medication. Please, please please, make sure that you also consult a counselor, therapist, psychologist or other medically trained professional, <em>before</em> you take any type of medication.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I think that support from friends and family is also extremely important. Sometimes people just want to be heard and to know that the people around them are supporting them and are there for them. People don&rsquo;t always want an answer to their problems either; they may want to just vent and talk it through.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Counseling is certainly important. There is nothing like talking to someone that you don&rsquo;t know, who is objective to your situation and has been trained to help people deal with issues and give you the professional guidance and support you need. Talking to your mom or dad or your friends is fine, but talking to a seasoned professional, who sees individuals going through mental health and depression issues every day is super beneficial. I myself have even done counseling before and I can tell you that counseling was unequivocally beneficial for me. If you know someone who needs counseling, letting them know that it&rsquo;s an option or suggesting it as an option is not a negative connotation. I think sometimes we look at counseling as a negative option, as if, &ldquo;Oh, if I go to counseling then something&#39;s wrong with me,&rdquo; or &ldquo;If I see a therapist, I&rsquo;m weak.&rdquo; No! If anything, you&#39;re going to counseling so you can get help and <em>that</em> makes you strong. When you&#39;re hungry, you go to a food store so you can get food, right? So why would you deprive yourself of going somewhere where you can be fed the nourishment you need, that will help your situation, allowing you to feel better overall?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Depression and mental health issues can really mess you up, especially if you allow it to linger, not tell anyone that you&rsquo;re feeling this way and may need help. I&rsquo;m bringing up these issues because, again, I told you that I suffer from seasonal depression. This wasn&#39;t something that I suffered from growing up as a kid. I think it was because I grew up in an area that doesn&rsquo;t see too much snow. Then I went to a school where it was completely different. Let me tell you, if there wasn&#39;t fourteen inches of snow on the ground every week, I wouldn&#39;t have known what university I was at; we always had snow. It was rare, except for the summer time, that you would see the sun (and no snow!). I think not getting enough sun exposure and always seeing the snow changed my mood and behavior.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I remember as a college student I became depressed. I&rsquo;m sure some people are thinking, &lsquo;Oh my gosh! That&#39;s so scary! You were depressed in college! You were far away from your mom and dad and nobody was around to help you!&rsquo; If that&rsquo;s what you thought, you are absolutely correct, that&rsquo;s how it was! So what happened? Well, first off, I had to get the help that I needed. I had to admit to myself that something wasn&rsquo;t right, I was not feeling like myself; I was not sleeping or eating the same way. If anything, even if I couldn&rsquo;t see my depression, my friends certainly could. If you notice significant changes in your close friends, peers, or colleagues, you have to speak up and be a bystander. Being a bystander means that you get directly involved, which also means you have to let them know what you&rsquo;re seeing. And guess what? They may not listen to you, but that&rsquo;s okay because you did the right thing. Your job is to speak up and make them aware that you noticed these changes and that you want to be there to support and help them.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Besides weather, depression can come from life changes. It can come from lack of funds or money, especially during the college years when we all know that money can be in short supply.&nbsp; Depression can come from family or school issues. Sometimes there may be a death, or maybe you&rsquo;re still affected by some baggage that you brought from home. In general, school can affect you when you&#39;re not getting the grades that you want or you&#39;re being spread around too thin or classes are new and the material is difficult. Depression can come from having a chemical imbalance. It can come from having bad relationships with people in college. It can even come from weight gain or low self-esteem.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I remember a day in particular at an institution I worked at.&nbsp; I worked with a student who had been cutting herself. I didn&#39;t know that she was cutting herself because her arm was full of band aids and she wore hoodies. It wasn&rsquo;t until one day when campus police called me and asked me to come down and speak with her. It seemed that her boyfriend had stolen her car. When I tried to talk to her about the situation, she laughed through the whole thing as if it was a joke. It wasn&#39;t until I began asking her some more pointed questions about the situation that she start breaking down and crying. The police had asked her several questions and she lied to the police. One of the questions that the police asked her was, &ldquo;Is there any abuse happening in your relationship?&rdquo; She told the police no, but when I asked her the more pointed questions, the ones that were very direct and open ended, it kind of broke down her shell a little bit. We ultimately found out that this young lady was being abused by her boyfriend and she was probably suffering from depression. She later went on to show me that she had cuts on her arm. One cut was bad enough that I suggested that she go to a medical care facility to get the wound treated. She didn&#39;t even know that that wound, which she had inflicted, was infected. She was cutting herself because of the situation with her boyfriend and because of depression. I&#39;m happy to note that after a few months of therapy, counseling, medication and some time away from her boyfriend, she was able to get herself back on track. She graduated with honors. She also got her car back, as the police later found it and they were able to arrest the young man. The man was later permanently banned from campus.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are many different resources on campus, for students, should they want to talk to somebody. Any campus student affairs professional or faculty and staff should be willing to help any student who is having an issue. If they can&rsquo;t directly help the student, they should be trained well enough to point them in the right direction to get the resources they need to be successful. Some of these resources include, but are not limited to:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Counseling center</strong> - Every campus, around the country has a counseling center. Some counseling centers have walk-in hours where you can just walk in and talk to a counselor, but others require that you have an appointment. Counseling centers can be tricky because there are a lot of students, who are bringing a bevy of problems. There isn&rsquo;t really isn&rsquo;t a quiet time of day. If you need help, make sure you go as soon as possible and get the help you need. The counseling center knows that they&#39;re spread thin and they try their best to make sure everybody is seen. I haven&#39;t had any negative experiences with a counseling center, not only as a student affairs professional but also when I utilized them as a student. The only negative I can mention is that, like I said, there are a lot of students, with a lot of problems and only a few counseling centers to utilize. They try their best to accommodate everybody, but they can only do so much. You can&rsquo;t really fault the counseling center if they can&#39;t see you on the same day you need. They also have to adhere to the gravity of each situation. Sometimes situations pop up on college campuses where the counseling center needs to intervene immediately, versus other situations where we hope the student can wait a few hours before the counselor can talk to them.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Health Care Center</strong> - You can also go to the health care center located on your local campus. They have some tools, resources and individuals available there who are willing to instruct you in the right way, in regard to your mental health and depression. You will probably experience similar trends in the staff being overloaded, but they are there to help.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As we discussed earlier, students are bringing many issues with them to campus. Students, be your own advocate. If you find that life is getting too hard, college life is too much to handle or if you&rsquo;re not finding the same joy that you used to feel before you got to college, and something is just different or feels off, I would highly encourage you to explore these feelings. Go and talk to somebody who can help you. Talk to your parents or guardians. Talk to your friends. Find out what&rsquo;s going on because it may be something that needs to be addressed. Parents, pay close attention to your children. Keep an eye out for estranged behavior, drastic changes in actions, rhythms or daily activities with your child.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Again, depression isn&rsquo;t something that has a definitive or specific look. Depression doesn&rsquo;t necessarily look like someone who&#39;s just sitting in the corner with the lights off, with a knife, in a storm, with a black cloud following them. I think that&#39;s the picture we all conjure up when we think of depression and that&rsquo;s why it always sounds so negative. Depression can happen to anyone, anywhere at any time. You would be shocked at the amount of people you know who suffer with depression, but have never brought it up or talked to you about it. This is why it&#39;s such an important issue that we need to continue to face and tackle by having open and instructive dialogues and conversations. The stigma that comes from back in the old days before depression and mental illness were properly handled, was to put sufferers in institutions and heavily medicating them! There is a certain stigma surrounding mental health that is never really acknowledged or talked about. It&rsquo;s treated as something that you should be embarrassed about. Should someone with diabetes or heart disease or even cancer be embarrassed? No! Then why would someone with mental illness be expected to feel that way? Let&rsquo;s deal with the stigma people, that way we can help those who are in need.</p>', '2020-09-07 23:20:10', '2020-09-11 00:01:35', NULL),
(29, 6, 'My Roomie Is My Bestie', NULL, 20, '<p>Roommates can be super fun! Listen, I know a lot of you are probably very anxious and hesitant about having a roommate. You may have heard about bad roommate situations and the crazy stories that go along with bad roommates, and of course, this chapter will include some of those stories. I&rsquo;m sure you&rsquo;ve heard about the life-changing, uncomfortable situations that are caused by roommates and, yes, those situations definitely happen. What you may not hear about are the good stories about the great roommates. You don&rsquo;t hear about the lifelong friends you make or that first roommate you meet in college who ends up being in your wedding and a godparent to your children. Those are not the stories you normally hear. I believe that those are the more common roommate situations that take place in college.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Having a roommate can be an intensely new experience, especially for those who didn&#39;t grow up with siblings. Now you have a shared living space; you have rules and guidelines that need to be established between the roommates sharing that space. You have to create and then ensure that the two (or four) of you are living in a unified space together and everyone&#39;s needs are being met. Without rules and guidelines, chaos and dysfunction would be produced in your otherwise harmonious living space. Believe me, no one wants to live in a dysfunctional living space. You want to be comfortable in your own room. You want to feel safe. You want to feel like your room is set up the way you like it. Why is this? For most people, your home is where your peace is. When you&#39;ve had a stressful day of classes or while you&#39;re out and about, you want to know that you can come home to a place that you feel comfortable in, you feel safe in and where you can have peace. Having that one comfortable, peaceful place is essential to your success as a student.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In order to create that harmonious living space, you have to learn people. You&rsquo;re no longer living in a room by yourself, you&rsquo;re living with someone else. Someone who might like a different air temperature than you, someone who has a different sleeping pattern than you, someone who may even have different cleaning standards than you. All of this means that you&#39;re going to have to take the time to learn a new normal in your new space. You&#39;re going to have to learn the habits of a new person and learn how to co-exist. You can only do that through engaging, interactive conversations with your roommate to learn and get to know them.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Everybody has different situations and no roommate is perfect. Sometimes you hear people say things like, &ldquo;Well, I had the perfect roommate when I was in my first year.&rdquo; or &ldquo;I had the perfect roommate in college.&rdquo; There&rsquo;s no such thing as perfect. Every situation is new and different. Some people think if they lived with a particular person, everything would be fine. As if they could change their living situation and the grass would be greener! My response to that would be that the grass can be greener on any side as long as you fertilize it; meaning that you need to put the time and effort into really learning how to live in your new space with a new person. This also means that you need to compromise. Compromising means everybody wins. You don&#39;t get 100% of what you want, but the other person doesn&rsquo;t get 100% of what they want either; it&rsquo;s a win-win!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Most universities recommend that roommates make something called &ldquo;A Roommate Contract&rdquo;. Basically, this entails you and your roommate, during the first night or week that you&rsquo;re on campus, coming up with a set of rules and guidelines that you both promise to uphold and agree to so that everybody can live in this space and be happy. Some of these rules and guidelines might include: what time you both plan on going to bed, who&#39;s going to restock toiletries, who plans on using the T.V. at a certain time, what you will do about food and trash. This contract can also include things like when guests are allowed to come over or when guests are not allowed to come over. You both need to make sure that you&rsquo;re adequately following the contract that you set up because if there is a particular situation, these contracts can really help resolve a disagreement between you and your roommate. It&rsquo;s all there in black and white.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Let me tell you a story about some residents who did not take these contracts seriously. I can remember a story where for every single question asked, the resident would reply, &ldquo;I&#39;m a do me!&rdquo; So I said, &ldquo;What time are you going to go sleep?&rdquo; Resident said, &ldquo;I&#39;m a do me!&rdquo; I said, &ldquo;What time are you going to allow guests to come over?&rdquo; Resident, &ldquo;I&rsquo;m a do me!&rdquo; I said, &ldquo;What time is phone time shut off?&rdquo; Resident, &ldquo;I&rsquo;m a do me!&rdquo; When the time came for the roommates to actually have a conversation about the issues that were bothering both of them, the only reaction to every single situation was, &ldquo;I&rsquo;m a do me!&rdquo; Now the time came for me, as the resident director, to step in, and I couldn&#39;t; I just had to do me. Do you get it now? These contracts are essential in setting up expectations and guidelines so you all can live together in a room and for it to be an incredible experience.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>People come to college from different upbringings. They come from different ways of being raised, different perspectives, cultures, backgrounds and areas. All of these differences play a part in how individuals live. When you start living with people, you&rsquo;ll see how different they are from you. It isn&#39;t only how they were raised or where they come from. They might be extremely independent and have different habits that you just might not like or may not be accustomed to. You won&rsquo;t learn or understand these habits until you start talking to the person.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I recall a story about a mother calling the Residence Life Department at the institution because she was scared that her son&rsquo;s roommate was a cannibal. Yes, you heard that right, a cannibal! How did she come to determine this? She found out this information because she went onto her son&rsquo;s Facebook page and looked up his roommate. For those of you in this situation who just found out your roommate&rsquo;s name, do not go on social media to look up stuff about them. This will only result in you making judgments about the person before you even have a chance to get to know them. That&#39;s not fair to do that; get to know them. You don&rsquo;t want someone doing that to you, do you? So, the roommates Facebook page said: Hobbies &ndash; Cannibalism. The mother was scared for her son&rsquo;s safety. When the person who told me the story looked up the cannibal&rsquo;s schedule, she also saw that he had a meal plan so he wasn&#39;t necessarily eating people. They did call him in anyway, just to see what was going on. They said, &ldquo;Hey. We have some concerns about your Facebook page. It says that you&rsquo;re into cannibalism. Do you eat people?&rdquo; And the guy just laughed and said no, but he finds cannibalism interesting and he&rsquo;s done a good amount of research and work surrounding it. So you can see how people can form preconceived notions about other people without even giving them a chance.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Roommates sometimes fight over the dumbest things. I can recall a story about two residents fighting over a towel bar. One of the girls, we&rsquo;ll call her Chelsea, had a towel bar that was on the other side of the room and Megan, her roommate, had a towel bar right above her bed. Well Chelsea decided she <em>had</em> to use the towel bar above Megan&#39;s bed. And Megan said, &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t want you to use the towel bar above my bed. I&#39;m going to use it as my towel bar. Use the one across the room.&rdquo; Chelsea didn&rsquo;t want to do that. They fought over this towel bar, for at least two months. It was crazy because I couldn&#39;t understand why these two were fighting over a towel bar. That&rsquo;s an example of one of the simplest things that roommates fight over. They can fight over the silliest things.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Some other examples of disagreements were over food, T.V. time, noise, the lights being on or off, the temperature in the room, and too many guests. All of these things come into play when it comes to living with someone. Again, what is essential is making sure you are having these conversations with your roommate before you start living with each other. If it can&rsquo;t happen before you start rooming together, make sure you do it as soon as possible. Make the expectations clear and concise. For example: On your contract, if it says what time should the lights go out, you shouldn&rsquo;t say, &ldquo;When we get tired.&rdquo; People get tired at different times at any point in the day, depending on how heavy your schedule is. Set a specific time: All lights out by 12:00 a.m. or 1:00 a.m., up for negotiation on the weekends. Both of you are a part of the contract rules and guidelines. Don&rsquo;t just agree to be agreeable.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I think the most important thing that roommates should do is communicate. How do you live, sleep and be in the same room with someone who you don&rsquo;t talk to? Isn&rsquo;t that awkward? I&rsquo;m sure people do it all the time, but in any healthy relationship, communication is key. You need to communicate your needs, your wants and dislikes. You can&rsquo;t hold someone accountable if they didn&rsquo;t know the expectation to begin with.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I remember a situation where there was a young lady who we&rsquo;ll call Alicia. She was rooming with another young lady, Jackie. Alicia had a boyfriend back at home, we&rsquo;ll say his name was Steve. Alicia and Steve had dated and had a great relationship, but he broke up with her right before the first semester started. Her roommate, Jackie, knew that Alicia and Steve had broken up, but Jackie never took the time to find out why Alicia was crying or upset. She really didn&rsquo;t communicate with her at all. Two weeks later, Jackie found a boyfriend and asked Alicia if the new boyfriend could come over to hang out and of course, Alicia said yes. Two minutes later, Jackie walked in with Steve. How crazy and coincidental is that?! It&#39;s kind of like a lightning strikes twice situation, where both roommates were dating the same guy. I know it sounds like an extreme situation, but it happened. Because the roommates didn&#39;t know enough about each other or enough about what was going on in each other&rsquo;s lives, an awkward situation arose. A little communication would have solved the whole problem of dating the same guy.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>With communication also comes realistic expectations. Some students that room together, clearly, have never lived with someone else before. I&rsquo;m sure there are a number of students who are an only child and, not to give people who are an only child a complex, but this may be the first time they&rsquo;ve ever had to share a space or share items with someone else. This is a new developmental experience for them, but having realistic expectations is certainly helpful. You can&rsquo;t come in and think you&rsquo;re going to get 100% of what you ask for and everything is going to go the way you want it to. That&rsquo;s just simply not going to happen.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I remember two young ladies who were set to be roommates. When it was time for them to make their roommate contract, the one just had completely unrealistic expectations as to how they were going to live in the room. She wanted the roommate to go to bed at 10 p.m.; all lights off. She didn&rsquo;t want the other roommate to have friends over in the room, ever! And she said she didn&rsquo;t want her to use her cell phone in the room, she had to use it in the hallway. She also didn&rsquo;t like the sound of people chewing so she didn&rsquo;t want her roommate to chew in the room. I&rsquo;m thinking, you cannot ask all these things of someone else. When the other roommate expressed that she wanted some of these liberties, the one roommate just said, &ldquo;Absolutely not! If you don&rsquo;t like it, you can move out!&rdquo; As a side note, residence life and housing services, at any institution, would not allow that, nor would they indulge that type of behavior. When roommates are together, there has to be some type of compromise or agreement and equality for both sides. That young lady had some really unrealistic expectations and that does happen.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To the students who are reading this, if you ever have a problem, go to your resident assistant, community assistant, resident director or hall advisor. That&#39;s what they&#39;re there for: to help you navigate how to have these healthy relationships with your roommate, because let&rsquo;s be honest, sometimes your roommates can be unreasonable. Students should come in with a clean slate and an open mind.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I know a lot of people say not to room with your best friend. Why not room with your best friend? People say it has the potential to ruin your relationship and it will never be the same again. As someone who has been in student affairs for about ten years and been in residence life and housing services for about five years, I will tell you that this is not necessarily 100% true. Your friendship will only get ruined if <em>you allow </em>it to be ruined. It&#39;s a great experience to room with someone you know. Yes, you will definitely get to know them in a totally different light and on a different level, just like you&#39;ll get to know any roommate. Your friendship will only fall apart and be ruined if you allow it to be. If you go into the situation with set expectations and you have open communication, you&#39;ll be perfectly fine.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I went to college and I roomed with my best friend from high school. He and I decided to go to the same university, decided to room together and, surprise, we&#39;re still best friends today. Did we have arguments and disagreements? Absolutely! We still have arguments and disagreements today and we don&rsquo;t live with each other anymore. You&#39;re going to have arguments and disagreements with people. It could be your significant other, your parents, your friends, your roommates; disagreements are going to happen.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I would be lying if I said nothing happened between me and my roommate. My roommate, who is and was my best friend, did the triple jump in Track &amp; Field. He would come home and, there would be sand in his shoes. Instead of kicking the sand off outside the room, he would kick it off inside our room. I&#39;m a neat freak! I&rsquo;m crazy! Kind of like that guy from &ldquo;The Voice&rdquo; who always uses hand sanitizer on his hands. Look, I&rsquo;m a germaphobe. I probably clean my room three times a day where he might not clean his room three times a month. We had to make a compromise. We talked about certain situations that had occurred. For me, I had to try and be realistic about it; all the sand was not going to be left outside the room. At the same time, he tried his best to make sure not to bring too much sand in the room. That&rsquo;s a compromise! That&rsquo;s an example of two people having their expectations met. That&rsquo;s being able to communicate. We took the necessary time to make sure the issue didn&rsquo;t turn into something bigger.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Like any other situation, it will depend on how you handle the situation and how mature you are about it. Yes, I&rsquo;ve seen people who&#39;ve gone to college and roomed with their best friend and it turned out absolutely ugly; it didn&#39;t work out, at all! Whether you already know your roommate or not, it&rsquo;s all about what you make of the situation. If you put the work in and have open communication, a strong contract and are able to compromise, you&rsquo;ll be fine regardless of who the roommate is. Of course, there will be some situations where you&rsquo;re just not going to be able to effectively communicate with your roommate.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I remember a situation where there was a young lady who screamed in her sleep. I don&rsquo;t know if she was experiencing night terrors. I don&rsquo;t know if it was due to something she was watching before she went to sleep. Whatever the reason, she would wake up in the middle of the night and start screaming or talking loudly in her sleep. This bothered her roommate. Not everything&#39;s going to be able to be fixed with a conversation. Ultimately, this young lady had to go on some medication and get some counseling. Again, not everything&#39;s going to be able to be fixed based on a conversation, but you have to let people know that the situation is taking place and that there are issues. The issues aren&rsquo;t going to go away just because you ignore them or because you talk about them once. Sometimes, you have to get other people involved. Bottom line - COMMUNICATE!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Advice for students: It&rsquo;s not always the other person. Point to yourself right now and say, &ldquo;Hey, sometimes it may be me!&rdquo; Ouch! I know that hurts and it&rsquo;s a hard pill to swallow. Especially because our perception is our reality and it&rsquo;s easier for it to be someone else&rsquo;s fault; that&rsquo;s human nature. As soon as something bad happens, we immediately want to point the finger at someone else. It makes sense, I get it. It&rsquo;s not only college students who do that; adults do the same thing. This is something that happens no matter how old you are. And, because perception <em>is </em>our reality, if we think its someone else&rsquo;s fault, we automatically believe that. Remember, it could be you! It may be our inability to be flexible or our inability to compromise or our unwillingness to communicate. With all that said, I&rsquo;m going to say, &ldquo;Students, be flexible! Learn how to compromise! Be open! It can&rsquo;t be a &lsquo;this or that&rsquo; thing, it can&#39;t be a &lsquo;black or white&rsquo; thing. There will always be a grey area.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I know it may be hard and some of you may not be straightforward people. You may not like experiencing confrontation or conflict or maybe you don&rsquo;t want to hurt someone else&rsquo;s feelings. That&rsquo;s not what this is about. It&#39;s about making sure that everyone has the same information, that you&#39;re being transparent and that you&#39;re having these conversations. I&#39;m not going to sit here and lie to you. It&rsquo;s not easy! How do you tell your roommate that sometimes they smell? Or how do you tell your roommate that they&#39;re not cleaning up after themselves? Or that they&#39;re using your toilet paper? Or that they&rsquo;re wearing your clothes? These are all situations that could happen. COMMUNICATE!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Advice for parents: I encourage you NOT to get involved in roommate situations, unless of course, it&rsquo;s life threatening. I can honestly say that 99.9% of the time, it is not life threatening. Don&rsquo;t get involved! Encourage your child to talk openly with their roommate. Encourage your son or daughter to talk to their resident assistant, the resident advisor, or the resident hall director. This will only help the student develop the competencies they need to have a conversation, but will also help with approaching conflict, dealing with confrontation and to be an advocate for themselves. It&rsquo;s all part of moving away to college and living with a roommate.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Don&#39;t look up your son or daughter&rsquo;s roommate on social media. Don&rsquo;t judge them before you even meet them. That will only create animosity, fear and anxiety in your heart about who your child is going to be living with. Give everyone a chance! When I say give everyone a chance, I mean give <em>everyone</em> a chance! I&#39;m also talking about people from different races and backgrounds. You have no idea how many times our office gets called because a parent doesn&rsquo;t want their child living with a particular individual because they&#39;re gay or because they&rsquo;re black or because they belong to this certain religion. Get over yourselves, okay! If this doesn&rsquo;t apply to you, don&rsquo;t wear the shoe! But, for those of you who think that your son or daughter is going to be &ldquo;tainted&rdquo; because they&#39;re rooming with someone who has a different background that is so not true! If that were the case, then they&rsquo;re going to be tainted by anybody at the university and furthermore, anyone in the world! Students come from unique and different backgrounds, sexual orientations and religions. That&#39;s what colleges and universities are: a very unique place that is worth the collective minds of the greatest students from around the country coming together. Give your student the opportunity to have a diverse experience; don&#39;t take that away from them.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Last, but not least, parents, you have to understand that not every situation is bad. Your child is going to have to figure it out on their own! What does that mean? It means, give them a chance to figure it out on their own! We want the students to think globally. We want them to experiment. We want them to figure out how to communicate. These things will only happen when we allow them to do it. We need you to help the residence hall directors and resident assistants. Why? Because those individuals are trying to make sure that they are sending the same message to your children. Don&rsquo;t work against us by sending different messages. Don&rsquo;t say, &ldquo;Well, I&rsquo;m going to call the president and make sure that this situation is fixed immediately!&rsquo; (Don&rsquo;t be that parent)! Don&rsquo;t do that because it sends mixed messages.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&#39;s so funny when parents call the president. Like the president knows your situation or knows that your son or daughter is unhappy. Don&rsquo;t start with the president. No! If you feel you absolutely <em>have </em>to get involved, start with the first line of defense; call the resident director or call someone in student life. We can handle it at our level, if necessary; that&rsquo;s what we do! That&rsquo;s not to say that if you call the president, it won&rsquo;t be handled. The president has so many things to handle, he or she shouldn&rsquo;t have to worry about your son or daughter being unhappy with the temperature in their room or your son or daughter having a towel rack issue! We understand that you spend a lot of money to send your child to school, so use the resources that you&rsquo;re paying for and go to the people who can help you; give them the opportunity to do what they&rsquo;re good at. We want to serve you. Give us the opportunity and the time to do so.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Overall, roommates are fun. They allow you to learn new things about others and about yourself. Again, a lot of roommate situations end with the individuals becoming best friends and rooming with each other again the next year. This is how lifelong friends are made. There&rsquo;s only those few times and those handful of crazy stories that you hear about that are over-the-top!&nbsp; Allow yourself to get to know someone, to grow, and to have fun. That&rsquo;s what college is all about, right?</p>', '2020-09-07 23:21:03', '2020-09-11 00:01:24', NULL);
INSERT INTO `chapters` (`id`, `course_id`, `name`, `image`, `amount`, `details`, `created_at`, `updated_at`, `deleted_at`) VALUES
(30, 6, 'Death', NULL, 20, '<p>I know this may seem pretty scary to be reading a college book that talks about death, but death can still happen when you&rsquo;re in college. No parent or student thinks that they&rsquo;re going to go to college and die. That&rsquo;s not what&rsquo;s supposed to happen at college. You go to college so that you can get a degree, learn, develop, meet new people, graduate and have fun! Unfortunately, death is a real thing that happens on college campuses. Since it&rsquo;s not sexy and can&rsquo;t be packaged with a nice bow to market to people, most institutions don&#39;t talk much about death.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Don&rsquo;t you think parents would be hesitant to send their child away to college if they thought death could become a reality while they were there? However, as an author, and as a person who works in student affairs, I try not to sugarcoat anything. Death is definitely a realistic circumstance that can happen to students all across the country. It&rsquo;s something that needs to be talked about. Why does it need to be talked about? Death doesn&#39;t stop or not happen just because the student is in college; it still happens. I know this sounds like a terrible thing to say, it&#39;s a terrible thing to hear but it&#39;s a truth. Family members can die while your child is away at college and unfortunately, sometimes students die at college.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sometimes they die off campus, sometimes they die during winter, Thanksgiving or spring break and sometimes family members die while students are away at college. Death happens. It&rsquo;s something that can be very painful, it hurts and it can definitely shake up a campus community and a family. Consider the fact that these students are interacting with each other on a daily basis. They&#39;re living with each other. They&#39;re socializing and communicating with each other. Then, poof, an incident takes place and someone is gone. A lot of these situations when death occurs, on a college campus, could have been prevented. I would like to say that the majority of them should be prevented, but some situations can&rsquo;t be.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Some of you are probably thinking, &ldquo;Justin, how does death happen on campus? What are some of the situations that you&rsquo;ve experienced?&rdquo; I can tell you this: there are some deaths that are avoidable and then some deaths that just simply aren&rsquo;t. When I mention that some deaths are avoidable, I&rsquo;m thinking of situations where a student becomes so intoxicated that they get behind the wheel of a car and they kill themselves. That situation can definitely be avoided. If you&#39;re going to drink, stay where you are and don&#39;t get behind the wheel of a car, or have a DD (Designated Driver). That&rsquo;s a type of death that could be avoided. When I think about a death that can&rsquo;t be avoided, some students may have health issues, such as cancer. Cancer is something that can&rsquo;t be avoided and could take the life of a student.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If a death occurs on campus, I want to let students know it&#39;s okay to hurt, it&rsquo;s okay to cry. I think when we&rsquo;re in college, we&rsquo;re already vulnerable with the new experience. Sometimes this makes it difficult for us to show that we are even more vulnerable, especially when death occurs. Everybody handles death differently and sometimes that grief can be triggered by different things that happen on campus. I want to give a few examples of the deaths that I&#39;ve experienced in the field, just to give you a realistic expectation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As we discussed in a previous chapter, depression and mental illness are an issue. Sometimes the pressures of being in school or the pressures of life are too hard and a student may make an attempt at taking their own life. I&rsquo;ve been on a few campuses where a student decided the pain was too much and they committed suicide.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I remember on one of the campuses I&rsquo;ve been to, a student hung themselves in a closet. It&rsquo;s so sad when a person feels there is no hope for their life. I recall a student who jumped off of an academic building. Again, a horribly sad situation where the person just didn&rsquo;t feel like they had anything left, like there was no hope. These are both awful tragedies and&nbsp; I&rsquo;m sure you don&rsquo;t want to hear about them, but this is a reality. I&rsquo;m sure some institutions try to cover these types of situations up or at least keep them from the media. A situation like that could lead to bad publicity.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>College is supposed to be a happy time for learning and exploring, not for dying. They don&rsquo;t want to talk about students dying on campus. Similar to the chapter on Safety, no one wants to talk about our campuses potentially being unsafe. If campuses are unsafe and students are dying, then the school is not going to bring in money. College is a place for learning, development, growth and of course, a degree. Colleges and universities are also money making entities. They are businesses and like any business, it almost always boils down to money.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are millions and millions of dollars in cash flow circulating through institutions across the country. There&rsquo;s no money in death. There&rsquo;s no money in a place being unsafe. Like any good marketing plan, they paint the pictures of campuses that seem like they are growing and thriving and safe places to be; and for the most part they are. However, there is no place and no college campus that is exempt from death or exempt from safety issues happening. That&rsquo;s why it&#39;s important that we have these conversations. I think that a lot of times we get so comfortable in our world, not only on college campuses but in the world in general, that we forget that there are some ugly situations happening in life. If we&#39;re not emotionally prepared for them or if we&#39;re not mentally ready for these situations, we could really be caught off guard and greatly affected.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&rsquo;d like to remind everyone that death should not be a reason for a student to dropout of school. I recall a student whose roommate passed away due to an unknown medical condition. They had become best friends. We talked about roommates in the previous chapter and a lot of people who are roommates become best friends. You come home to the same person every day. When you have a test you did poorly on, that&#39;s the first person you talk to. When you wake up that&#39;s the first person you see. When you go to bed, that&rsquo;s the last person you talk to. I remember the surviving roommate just couldn&#39;t deal. She couldn&rsquo;t take the pressure and the grief of her best friend not being there and ultimately, she dropped out of school.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Death not only happens on campus, but it can happen at home, while you&rsquo;re away at college. Students have lost a parent, sibling, grandparent or a friend and they determine that they can no longer handle the stresses of being on campus. They feel like they need to be with their family immediately, and they drop out of school.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are a lot of differing conclusions about what happens after a death. They may feel that students have to do what&rsquo;s best for them. I would argue this point. Life is hard, no one wants to deal with death, but life doesn&rsquo;t stop when someone dies, the world keeps on spinning. That&rsquo;s a hard reality to hear and it&rsquo;s a hard message to comprehend. Do you think, for one second, that the person who died wants you to stop your life and dropout of school? No! I also remember a student who had to drop out because her grandmother died and her siblings didn&#39;t have anywhere else to live. She had to go home and get a job so she could financially provide for her siblings. I understand this situation, it sucks, but it makes sense. It was painful for me to watch her drop out of school, especially because she was extremely smart and I knew she had a bright future ahead of her. I always hoped she she was able to return to her studies at some point.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I would encourage students that even if death does take place during your time in college and to that point, no matter what happens when you go to college, you need to get that piece of paper! Get certified in the field you chose. There&rsquo;s nothing in this world that should stop you from your ultimate goal. I realize school is not the end all be all and yes, there may be other things that are more pressing than an education, but if at all possible, finish your degree. There is no point in starting if you are not going to complete.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Remember that balance is key. Maybe your goal is on pause for a minute or held up for a little while due to your circumstances, but no matter what takes place, you need to ensure that you complete the objective of getting your degree. Otherwise, you went to college and gave them your money for nothing. There are even students who dropout of school because they&#39;re not doing well academically. You can sit at home for free, you don&rsquo;t have to go to school. My heart hurts and breaks for these students that come to school, spend all this money and walk away with nothing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In freshman orientation, they say, &ldquo;Look to your left. Look to your right. One of these students will not be here at the end of the semester.&rdquo; I think that&#39;s crap! I hate that they say that! I hate that colleges and universities still do that. I feel like they&rsquo;re being cruel to first year students. I wish we could say, &ldquo;Look to your left, look to your right. Everyone is going to be here in two years. Everyone is going to graduate in four years.&rdquo; Now, granted, not everyone will stay at the same institution, so it does make a little sense, but let&rsquo;s show some positivity! Some of these students will transfer or some of the students will change their major. I never want to put it in a student&#39;s&#39; mind from the beginning that someone is going to fail. No! We all need to do this together and we all need to pull together as a community.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I remember one of the sweetest students that I&#39;ve ever met. I have to bring her up in this chapter because she meant a lot to me. She died due to some health complications from having a seizure. It was so sudden. She was such a good student; never had any academic issues. She was highly involved on campus. She was sweet and kind, but she suffered from some medical issues. One night, out of no fault of her own and due to complications from her health issue, she unfortunately, passed away. I still think about her often, and fondly.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are also accidental deaths that happen on campus at institutions. I recall a student who was drunk and walked into a landfill. He was killed by one of the machines. Sure, I know students get drunk and sometimes throw up, but if you&rsquo;re watching out for your friends, this doesn&rsquo;t have to happen. I remember a situation where a student threw up but they were laying on their back. Since they were laying on their back, the vomit had nowhere to go and ultimately, they choked to death on their own vomit.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Another possible cause of death is disease. Some diseases are preventable by vaccination. If you&#39;re going to be living around other students, make sure that you&#39;re vaccinated. Not being vaccinated before you go off to college may not end well. You&rsquo;re going to have so many encounters with a lot of different people. You&#39;re shaking hands, high-fiving, touching a lot of computers, door handles, and sitting at desks. People get sick. Make sure you have all your regular immunizations and seasonal vaccinations as well.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Some campuses and universities don&#39;t even let their students on campus unless they show proof that they&rsquo;ve had all of the necessary vaccinations. It&#39;s important! The meningitis vaccination is the most important because you can get extremely sick if you come into contact with the meningitis bacteria. It&rsquo;s easily spread and can sneak up on you. I remember at one of the institutions that I lived at, one of the greatest people that I knew passed away due to contracting bacterial meningitis. He was a junior when he died, so he already had two years at the institution but had never had the meningococcal vaccination. Make sure that you are getting the proper vaccinations so that you can avoid these diseases or illnesses that you can contract being on college campuses.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I know it sounds simple, but please wash your hands people! Shower daily and see your doctor for regular check-ups. I&rsquo;m not sure if every household teaches these things, but take it from me, these are simple, yet important tips. Some students are going to be far away from home while in college. Don&rsquo;t forget to find and visit both a local dentist and a primary health care provider. You should still be mindful of your health even though you&rsquo;re away from home. This is very important. Get check-ups and wellness checks. These are things that you should keep in mind when you&rsquo;re away at school.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This chapter seems a bit scary and it doesn&#39;t appear to be as friendly or perky and optimistic as some of the other chapters, but death is real, it happens and it needs to be talked about. Death could realistically happen to any student, on any campus in the country. Death doesn&rsquo;t have any specific targets. It doesn&rsquo;t matter if you&rsquo;re a good person or a good student or not a good person; no one is exempt from death. I want to make sure that the students are equipped with the knowledge, skills and resources to make the best decisions possible so that avoidable deaths can be lessened on campus.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Death is not only hard for students, but it&#39;s also hard for the professionals who work with these students. We work with these students every single day to ensure that they&#39;re getting the utmost care and that they&#39;re having a great time. I&rsquo;m sure the students reading this can probably think of that one professional that made an impact in their lives, whether it was in high school or college. We create relationships with the students. We learn to care about them, love them, want the best for them, want to see them succeed and, ultimately, want them to live out their dreams. To have a student taken suddenly, is a really sobering experience that student affairs professionals go through as well.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Why do I say all of this to you? Because a lot of students experience their first death in college. They know someone who dies in college or there is a death of a family member. A lot of students don&#39;t know how to deal with grief and grieving is different and difficult for everyone. Not everybody experiences grief the same way. In my experience, when you have a plan in place for extreme circumstances, like death and handling grief, it can only help. It&rsquo;s important for me, as the author, to allow myself to be vulnerable to you so that you know that I&rsquo;m coming from a place of honesty and realism. I never want to pretend that these tips and suggestions are so abstract that the reader can&rsquo;t truly hone in on what I&#39;m saying.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For me personally, when I first hear about a death and start experiencing the grieving, it&rsquo;s normally just a huge shock to me. I can&rsquo;t believe that the person is gone. I don&#39;t have any other feelings at that point, only shock. I&rsquo;m not sad. I&#39;m not mad. I&rsquo;m not upset. It&#39;s just shock. I guess you could say shock is normally <em>my </em>first state of grief. Remember that each person may go through the different stages of grief, at different times and that&rsquo;s okay. The process of grief is painful, but should be embraced. It&rsquo;s not something you can hide from. It takes time to go through the process, but give death the reverence it deserves. The next stage I typically go through is utter sadness. I start to cry or I start to feel pain, loneliness and sadness. Some people who experience grief feel the pain, loneliness and sadness immediately. They miss the shock emotion and instantly go straight into sorrow. Normally, my last stage of grief is acceptance. I&rsquo;m accepting that this loved one or this student is no longer here. I&rsquo;m accepting that I won&rsquo;t see them again. I&rsquo;m accepting that anything can change at any time.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You have to know how <em>you</em> handle grief. It&#39;s really important to figure out how you handle grief, before grief happens. There is no way to properly prepare for it, but knowing that these stages will probably occur, can be helpful. Grief looks different for many people and comes in many forms. Grief for a colleague may look different than grief for a parent or close friend. There are, however, seven stages of grief that most people go through and these stages can happen in any particular order.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Stage 1- Shock</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Stage 2- Denial</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Stage 3- Anger</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Stage 4-Bargaining</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Stage 5-Depression</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Stage 6-Testing</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&middot;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Stage 7-Acceptance</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;When it comes to death, my advice to both parents and students is the same. I think that these tips could be helpful to anyone. First, be open about death and grief. To pretend that death doesn&#39;t exist, in real life or on college campuses, is ignorant. Pretending would be setting yourself up for a major disappointment. Have open conversations about death. Know that death can happen. Know that death will happen. Some deaths can be prevented, but some of them can&rsquo;t. I think sometimes, even when we talk about death, we pretend that young people are exempt from dying because they&#39;re young, that only old people die and we all know that&rsquo;s just not true.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We need to talk realistically about what happens when we have individuals in our family who are sick. Think about it, if you are a college student and a close family member is sick, do you really want to go to a school that&rsquo;s really far away? If you know that you want to be closer to your family and that these are hard times for your family, realistically you may want to go to a school that&rsquo;s a little closer to your family in the event that something happens and you need to get home quickly. I think that what&#39;s most important is not to hide from it. Don&rsquo;t hide that it could happen, that it did happen or how we feel about it happening.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What&rsquo;s also vital is the need to focus on what&#39;s important to us. What&rsquo;s important is our family, friends, and getting a degree from an institution of higher education. We can&#39;t lose that focus due to death or other situations that are out of our control. We need to lean on others. I know that while campus deaths are sad events (that we never want to see happen), when death has occurred, I have never seen a more unified campus than during that initial time of grief. That&rsquo;s the time when I see students truly coming together. Unfortunately, it&rsquo;s due to a very sad circumstance, but the togetherness that occurs is awesome. Normally, individuals who live within our campus communities make such a great impact that when they die, it triggers the campus to come together and create unity. There is almost an unspoken power when people are grieving together. We need to make sure we&rsquo;re bringing everybody together, not just when a campus crisis such as death happens. We should be embracing our togetherness all the time.</p>', '2020-09-07 23:21:24', '2020-09-11 00:02:01', NULL),
(31, 6, 'Bling-Bling, Money Is A Thing', NULL, 20, '<p>Cha-ching! If you like that sound, like most Americans do, then that means that you like money. If you can pull your purse or wallet out right now and you have a credit card or some cash in there, then this chapter is definitely for you! For colleges and institutions around the country, sometimes that&#39;s what it&#39;s all about. <em>Show me the money, baby!</em> <em>It&rsquo;s all about the Benjamins! Bling-bling, money ain&rsquo;t a thing!</em> It seems that there are some college students who have more than enough money, but there are others, like me when I was in school, who don&rsquo;t have an extra $5 to their name!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When I was in college, back in 2010, I drove a 2000 Chevy Malibu. It had over 100,000 miles on it, but it got me to and from where I needed to go. I had a friend who drove a 2011 Corvette! He, or rather his family, had a lot of money. On spring break, I went home and hung out with my family and I worked. Other students, went to France or overseas or to the islands for their spring break.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The financial situation will vary for each student. For the readers (both students and parents), if you don&rsquo;t have $40,000 in your pocket right now to pay for school this year, you&rsquo;ll find some great tips in this chapter. The majority of us don&rsquo;t have $40,000, sitting around, at our disposal. If we did, college loan debt wouldn&rsquo;t be so monumental. Due to the amount of people attending college, educational loan debt has now surpassed national credit card debt. College students don&rsquo;t have much of a choice; loans are how you achieve obtaining a higher education. You will probably be paying back these loans for the rest of your lives. In fact, your children and maybe even your grandchildren may be paying back your school loans.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There&rsquo;s an elephant in the room and we need to talk about it...DEBT! For the majority of you, you will have some form of debt for your <em>entire </em>life; whether it&rsquo;s student loans, credit cards, a car loan or a mortgage. Generally, credit cards are how a good amount of Americans survive. For the students reading this, you&rsquo;re probably going to be in debt for a long while. For the parents, if you&rsquo;re co-signing for your kid&rsquo;s loans or maybe even still paying off your own college debt, well, that&rsquo;s life; it&rsquo;s basically the norm. Everyone is going to have debt! When it comes to a college education, there are different types of debt. There are the people who only have a small amount of loan debt and then the people who have a ton of loan debt from school. It really depends on which route you take to gain financial strength during your college years.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If your move-in day experience, on college campus, is similar to what mine was, this is what might happen. You move in and you&rsquo;re greeted by a variety of credit card companies that are strategically placed throughout the campus. The offers may say something like, &ldquo;Sign up with us because we&#39;ll give you the best interest rate!&rdquo; or &ldquo;Make sure that your child always has access to funds...in case of emergency. Apply for a credit card with us now!&rdquo; Believe it or not, I did not open one credit card throughout college. What?! I know, that&rsquo;s crazy! I just didn&rsquo;t feel it would be a good idea for <em>me.</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are some benefits and a few setbacks of <em>not</em> opening up a credit card account. I knew that I could not be trusted having a credit card, so I didn&#39;t open one. I knew that if I had &ldquo;free money&rdquo; (we&rsquo;ll get back to &ldquo;free money&rdquo; in a second) I might needlessly spend. There&rsquo;s no accountability when &ldquo;free money&rdquo; is involved until the bill comes in. If you know you&rsquo;re like this or parents, if you know your child can&rsquo;t be trusted with &ldquo;free money&rdquo;, do not open a credit card; not a good move! With a credit card comes a responsibility. Let&rsquo;s make sure we are guiding the students towards being responsible, especially when they have this &ldquo;free money&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Looking back and knowing what I know now, I wish I had taken advantage of one of the many credit card offers presented to me. If you&rsquo;re responsible with money or parents, if you know your child can manage having a credit card, do it! This will help them on the road to building credit.&nbsp; Think about it, when you graduate from college, you&#39;re most likely going to want to get an apartment or get a new car, but these things require you to have credit. If you take advantage of the offers, early on, you&rsquo;ll have had four years of good credit at graduation, which is great! I wish I had built credit when I was an undergrad student because as soon as I graduated, I needed credit for so many different situations, but I didn&rsquo;t have enough.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Let&rsquo;s get back to the term &ldquo;free money&rdquo;. We all know there&rsquo;s no such thing, right?! Any borrowed money will eventually have to be paid back, with interest. This means that we need to be fiscally and financially responsible every time we swipe that card. For the students that I see pulling out their credit card at a convenience store for a pack of gum, this is not a smart idea. If you&#39;re going to swipe that credit card, at least swipe it for something you absolutely need, not a pack of gum! If you&rsquo;re going to use the card for trivial purchases, like a pack of gum, make sure you pay off the balance every month; at least you&rsquo;ll be building your credit. Swiping that card, multiple times a day, is not the answer. Sometimes you&rsquo;re going to have to do without. Sometimes you have to buy something that costs less. Sometimes purchasing name brand clothes isn&#39;t the best choice. Maybe going on that vacation over spring break isn&#39;t necessary. It&#39;s okay to get used books and it&rsquo;s also okay to rent your books. You don&#39;t have to live in the most expensive residence hall, maybe you live off-campus.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Another point I&rsquo;d like to make is that you don&#39;t need to have three, four or five different credit cards! All of those cards and actions are connected to your credit score. At this point in your life, the goal of having a credit card or open line of credit, is to build your credit score so you have the opportunity to build your future. If you&rsquo;re already having trouble affording college and affording life in general, creating extensive debt is not going to help you build a successful future.&nbsp; It seems that nowadays students are coming out of college with not only student loan debt, but credit card debt too. Sometimes those debts are almost equal. You knew going into college that you would have regular college loan debt, but now you&rsquo;re coming out with loan debt and credit card debt!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Be certain that you are fully aware and knowledgeable about any credit cards or discount programs that you have signed up for. The credit card companies have a lot of enticing gimmicks out there. Here&rsquo;s an example: &ldquo;Open a credit card with us and we&rsquo;ll give you $100 gift card that you can use anywhere on campus.&rdquo; That sounds like a pretty good deal, right? What about the credit card company that says, &ldquo;We&rsquo;ll give you huge discounts on local purchases and we&rsquo;ll give you back a percentage for every swipe that you do on campus.&rdquo; Yeah, yeah, yeah. Again, it sounds great, but if it sounds too good to be true, it probably is. Ultimately, where do these actions leave you in 3-5 years? Will you be paying more money or less money? Remember credit cards require you to pay interest if you don&rsquo;t pay them off each month. Is having a credit card or open line of credit beneficial for you? These are all questions you need to ask yourself <em>before </em>opening up a credit card. I realize that when you don&rsquo;t have access to much money, opening a credit card can feel like a valuable option for your situation, but that&rsquo;s not necessarily always the case.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Figure out the best way for you to financially make ends meet. This can only happen when you make a financial plan. It&#39;s essential that we teach students to live within their means and that starts with us showing them how to accomplish that. I realize this can be difficult, even for some adults. If we&#39;re telling the students, &ldquo;Make sure you set up a budget and that you&rsquo;re spending realistically.&rdquo; but then we&rsquo;re not living that same way, what lesson does that teach? Let&rsquo;s show and teach the students that we want them to come out of college with a reasonable amount of good credit, as minimal debt as possible and a world of opportunities ahead of them.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you don&#39;t have a budget set up, right now, you need to create one. You should know how much you&rsquo;re spending each month versus the income you&rsquo;re bringing in each month. If you&#39;re reading this chapter right now and you do not have a savings account, just stop everything you&rsquo;re doing and go open a savings account, immediately! I wish someone had told me to put away $10 each week, for my entire four years of college, but no one told me. When you get out of college, the first thing you&#39;re going to want and need, is money. I&rsquo;m telling you, students and parents, if you want to give yourself the best college gift possible, give yourself some savings. If you put $10 away per week for four years, imagine the amount of money you would have saved!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Here&rsquo;s another way to think about it. If you have money to buy alcohol, then you definitely have $10 to put away in a savings account each week. If you have money to go and buy new clothes, then you&rsquo;ve got $10 to put in your savings account. If you have money to go out to a restaurant for a meal (even if the appetizers are half price!), then you have $10 to put in your savings account. Maybe you can skip going out with your friends, or skip a night at the bar, or whatever you&rsquo;re spending $10 on each week. Put that $10 a week into a savings account. In four years, you will have $360 per yr x 4 years = $1440. I know it doesn&rsquo;t sound like a lot, but its way more than nothing! Give yourself this gift. When you get out of college, the first thing you need is a job. You may need a place to live. You might need a car. You&rsquo;re going to need some cash flow. We already talked about all the debt you can incur while in college, so do yourself a favor and gift yourself a savings account that can help your immediate future.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Be cautious and mindful of your spending habits. Our spending habits can easily take on a pattern. When I look at my spending habits, especially from when I was in college, the biggest expense was food; and I ate a lot! That is where all of my college money went. I had chosen a bank that provided quarterly meetings with me; to make sure that I was doing the best I could to save money. I remember the banker sitting down with me and saying, &ldquo;You really like to eat, don&#39;t you?&rdquo; And I said, &ldquo;Well, I think everybody likes to eat.&rdquo; He looked at me sincerely and said, &ldquo;No! You really like to eat!&rdquo; He showed me my spending habits and when he put it down on paper, I noticed that I was eating out a lot. Remember I told you in a previous chapter that, as a resident assistant, I had a meal plan. Why would I be going out and eating all this food, when I already had food that was paid for?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My loose spending habits were not benefiting me if I was also trying to save money. So, I made a budget. I decided that I would allot myself a certain amount for outside-of-my-meal-plan food consumption. Instead of going out to eat 3-4 times per week, I adjusted my spending and only indulged 3-4 times per month. Once I made this change, my extra food spending went from approximately $200 per month to about $60 per month. Just by making that one change, I was able to save an additional $120 per month. Do a self-audit. Go through your finances and see what you&rsquo;re really spending money on.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It bothers me when students become another statistic. I think about all the students who spend a ton of money, incur even more debt than imaginable and then have to drop out prior to graduating. They become a statistic. An alarming 38% of students encounter financial hardship sometime during their college years. This hardship may result in the student dropping out or having to transfer to a community college. Something like 7% of students do not have the financial means to continue college after their first semester, so they have to drop out or transfer to a community college. Unfortunately, this is the sad truth, but proper planning, ahead of time, could alleviate some of this.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you&rsquo;re reading this and thinking, &ldquo;Hey look, Justin. I don&#39;t have the money&rdquo; or &ldquo;Justin, I don&rsquo;t know how I&rsquo;m going to make ends meet.&rdquo; Let me share with you some of the alternative ways I created income while I was in college? When I was in college, living on campus, I had four jobs and I have no shame in sharing that with you. I worked in the admissions office. I gave tours and got paid per completed tour. I worked in the P.R. office (Since I was a public relations major, why not get the experience <em>and </em>get paid to do it?). I worked in orientation helping new students get acclimated to the institution. In the end, working in residence life, benefited me the most financially.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&rsquo;ve talked about residence life throughout this book and in my previous book. I&rsquo;ve revealed how residence life really helped me with many aspects of my education, while I was attending school. I don&rsquo;t think I could have done it without them. That said, being a resident assistant is extremely challenging. There&rsquo;s not a ton of money in this occupation, but if you have a love for people, a servant&rsquo;s heart, the ability to want to encourage, strengthen and develop students, this is definitely the job for you. I was an R.A. for three years while I was at school. When you&rsquo;re an R.A., they typically pay for your room and board and also food. I&rsquo;m sure it&rsquo;s different at each school but I&rsquo;m positive there is a financial benefit to being an R.A, regardless of the school. Honestly, without assistance, I don&rsquo;t know if I would&rsquo;ve been able to afford going to school.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I consider it a blessing that I was able to be a part of residence life and I think residence life is a blessing to so many people. That&rsquo;s why I&#39;m a strong advocate for residence life departments on college campuses. They do such good work and are often overlooked. Students definitely visit their R.A.&rsquo;s with issues, during the day, but at night, it&rsquo;s a whole &lsquo;nother ball game. The freaks come out at night! The people who work in residence life are equivalent to first responders when in comes to on-campus issues. We&rsquo;re the ones handling the heavy load. Handling the students&rsquo; issues, on a daily basis, can be exhausting. That said, students, if you&#39;re looking for some type of financial help while you&rsquo;re in school, check out the leadership roles in residence life. Just to let you know, they don&#39;t accept every applicant for resident assistant or community assistant. They&rsquo;re going to want to know what life skills you can bring to the table.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As a resident or community assistant, you&rsquo;ll be on duty within the halls. You&rsquo;re responsible for ensuring that the residence hall is well taken care of and everything is running smoothly. Unfortunately, there is this bogus notion that when you are resident assistant, you are a snitch; that you report students who are drinking;. That&rsquo;s a myth and not true. I tell my R.A.&rsquo;s, &ldquo;You are only a reporter. If you see something happening that shouldn&rsquo;t be, report it. If nothing news-worthy is happening, then there&rsquo;s nothing to report.&rdquo; We are attempting to create a better culture, keep everyone safe and we&rsquo;re trying to instill values of working hard <em>and</em> having fun. Working hard means you&rsquo;ll eventually get a return on your investment. Invest in yourself!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Students, there are plenty of jobs on campus! The on-campus jobs are convenient and plentiful. There are jobs as a tutor, in the dining hall, in campus recreation or even a student employee in a variety of departments on campus. The journey for one of these jobs starts before you even get to your college campus; research the jobs and apply early.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Obviously money is important during college and because it&rsquo;s important to live, sometimes students participate in illegal or less than astute activities, in order to make ends meet. We talked in a previous chapter about a girl who didn&#39;t have enough money to pay for school so she ended up becoming a drug dealer to make money. Please don&rsquo;t sell drugs to make your tuition payment; there are other ways to make money. Some students donate blood or plasma. Not the healthiest choice, but thankfully, there are rules set in place to make sure you&rsquo;re not hurting yourself and at least you&rsquo;re helping someone else.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Some students even go as far as being &ldquo;sugar babies&rdquo;. If you&rsquo;re unsure of what this term means, you may want to look it up. I realize that this isn&rsquo;t something people want to talk about, but this is a real thing! There are tons of documentaries and articles available on this topic. I actually had a friend who was a sugar baby. She wasn&rsquo;t engaging in sexual acts with the man who helped her financially; she would just spend time with him, and keep him company. She went on trips and attended fancy events with him. In the end, he basically paid for her entire schooling. He also bought her a Mercedes Benz. It made me think, what was I doing? Could I be a sugar baby? Are men sugar babies? They sure are! How do we go about doing this? I&#39;m just joking, but at the same time, that situation worked out for her and there&#39;s no judgment here.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I know some students who were strippers during college; both male and female. There is nothing illegal about being a stripper, but before venturing into this occupation to make money, exhaust all other options. Know going into this that there may be some negative backlash and consequences to being a stripper. Your reputation may also be affected and I need to mention that there is risk involved in this type of job. Risk with the people you will be around, the environment and the customers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&rsquo;m fairly certain that you can&rsquo;t add sugar baby or stripper to your resume, but by all means, do what you&#39;ve got to do so that you can make ends meet. Does this mean I&rsquo;m advocating for being a sugar baby or a stripper? No, but I also get that students will need to make money to make ends meet and stay in college. What I <em>am</em> advocating for is that students only acquire jobs that will not result in them going to jail. This means no selling drugs or robbing houses!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Whatever you decide to do for additional income, make sure that you are being a good steward of your money? The first thing you can do is to be realistic about the institutions you choose to attend. When I first started researching colleges, I was looking at the biggest and best names in the college biz and not paying any mind to the cost on my pockets. Sure, these schools I was looking into were great schools, if I could even get into them, but where was I going to get $45,000 a year? You already know I didn&rsquo;t have that kind of money. Even with the four jobs I had at the institution, I still wouldn&rsquo;t have made $45,000 a year. I started looking at smaller schools, not necessarily D1 schools, but more in the D2 or D3 range. (The difference between D1, D2 and D3 colleges has to do with the number of sports programs they promote and the caliber of athletes that participate in those sports.) I ultimately settled on a D2 school where it would cost me anywhere between $22,000-$30,000 a year. This was a much more financially responsible choice for me and for my pockets.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Another way to help your financial situation is to apply for as many scholarships and grants as possible. Listen to me, there are so many different scholarships and grants available, it&#39;s ridiculous. There are scholarships and grants for just about any circumstance you can think of. For example: If you create your entire prom dress out of duct tape, there&rsquo;s a scholarship for you! There is, literally, a scholarship or grant for everyone. There are scholarships and grants that aren&rsquo;t even being distributed because no one is applying for them. For example: Look at the D.A.P program; The Diversity Awareness Program. I created a $200 scholarship to give away. I know that&rsquo;s not a lot, but this is just the start to the newly founded scholarship program, which began in 2017. Again, not a lot, but that $200 will take care of a book or maybe two books or maybe help with someone&rsquo;s tuition. I advertised everywhere. The scholarship was up for grabs for two months and not one person applied.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I got a lot of these types of scholarships when I went to school solely because no one else applied. Shoot, I was applying for college scholarships that I knew I didn&#39;t even qualify for and because there were no other applicants, I got the scholarships by default. That actually happened to me 3-4 different times. Apply for scholarships! If you have time to be on the Gram, sliding in people&rsquo;s DM&rsquo;s, or be on Facebook, you definitely have time to apply for some scholarship money. It&rsquo;s free money! That&#39;s the only type of money that&#39;s free: grants and scholarship money! Take advantage of the ones that are available to you and use them for your benefit.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In college, there are many components that will require you to spend money: tuition, a place to live (on or off campus), possible commuting costs, books, food, a gym membership, club/organization membership fees, and so much more. College is more expensive now than it has ever been. This is a fact; doesn&rsquo;t matter which part of the world you&rsquo;re from. The cost of tuition and books has increased exponentially in the past 20 years. The cost of living is greater and college-incurred debt is at an all time high. Make sure you&rsquo;re spending money appropriately, making wise decisions when it comes to your credit and putting a little away in a savings account for your future.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tips and reminders for students:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Don&rsquo;t spend money on dumb stuff.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Open a savings account and put $10 in it, every week!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Don&rsquo;t do anything illegal to make extra money.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Get a job while in high school.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Apply for jobs and do it early.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Apply for grants and scholarships.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Open one credit card.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tips and reminders for parents:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Create a college savings plan for your child as soon as they&rsquo;re born.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Instill healthy financial savings habits in your kids&hellip;.early in life.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Help them create a savings plan.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If it&rsquo;s feasible, save money for their education.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Encourage them to get a part time job on campus.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Show them how to be financially responsible.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As always, with all of the topics in this book, open and honest dialogue and conversation is a must. Money can be tricky but there&rsquo;s a science to it. Learn the science and you&rsquo;ll be successful.</p>', '2020-09-07 23:21:44', '2020-09-11 00:02:06', NULL);
INSERT INTO `chapters` (`id`, `course_id`, `name`, `image`, `amount`, `details`, `created_at`, `updated_at`, `deleted_at`) VALUES
(32, 6, 'Freshman 20', NULL, 20, '<p>I know a lot of you reading this book probably love food and I am no different. I am definitely a foodie! I love food! When I got to college, I struggled with eating well-balanced meals. When you&rsquo;re in college, you can literally have pizza, cheeseburgers and chicken patties every day. I know a lot of people who go to college also eat ramen noodles and things like that on a daily basis. You&rsquo;ll hear a lot of people say, watch out for the freshman fifteen. Now a days, the freshman 15, has without a doubt, become the freshman 20!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&#39;s hard because in college there aren&rsquo;t too many choices when it comes to food options. There&rsquo;s the dining hall, there&rsquo;s off-campus eating and then of course, fast food. I know for a lot of people who are eating the trending gluten-free or vegetarian options, this can be an additional challenge. However, if you live in a city, these places and these food options are plentiful. If you&rsquo;re on a college campus, not located in the city, those types of food are really hard to find and get to. If you&#39;re at a college campus and you need a special diet, you probably have to see the campus nutritionist to figure out how to accomplish this. And yes, campuses across the country do have campus nutritionists. If you need someone to help with a specialized diet, definitely inquire at your local dining hall. Food allergies are a real thing and people&#39;s diets are constantly shifting, changing and developing. Perhaps...Most campuses are trying to change and evolve with the changing food and dietary restrictions to include options such as sugar free, gluten free, dairy free, and trans fat free. All those things are really important, especially to the people affected by a food allergy.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As a college student, you&rsquo;ll need to figure out what&#39;s going to be more advantageous for your wallet: eating on-campus or off-campus. If you&rsquo;re a first year student, for the most part, you will probably be eating in your dining hall the most. You&rsquo;ve already paid for it and, sometimes, you&rsquo;ve overpaid for it, but it&rsquo;s paid for nonetheless. I&rsquo;m often mystified when students have a meal plan but they eat the majority of their food off-campus, as if they didn&#39;t pay for their food once already!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When I was an undergrad, I had a friend who paid for a meal plan but ate out every single day. Granted, he had the money to do that, but why pay for a meal plan if you&#39;re going to eat off-campus? Every day I would say, &ldquo;Hey. Let&rsquo;s go get something to eat.&rdquo; And every day, he would say, &ldquo;Yeah man. I&rsquo;m going to such-and-such, off-campus.&rdquo; I would say, &ldquo;Well, I&rsquo;m going to the dining hall.&rdquo; He would always try and talk me into going to eat off-campus. Sometimes I would go with him, but I started to discover that the majority of the time he was eating off-campus, as if off-campus was the only option. I later figured out that he just didn&#39;t like the meal plan.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>An important discussion, between parents and their child, should include figuring out which meal plan fits best; both financially and nutritionally. An average meal plan consists of 14 meals per week, I would say that&rsquo;s a great plan; especially since most students are probably only going to eat two meals per day on-campus. Unless they have early classes, most students sleep in and probably miss breakfast, which means that they&#39;re going to need lunch and dinner. Or, let&rsquo;s say you do wake up early and you have breakfast and lunch on-campus, but then you decide to either go out for dinner or make your own food. The majority of upperclassmen students who live off campus do not use meal plans. However, if you are an upperclassman and you don&#39;t like to cook, a meal plan is definitely the way to go.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You should absolutely be mindful of what you eat. I&#39;m telling you, when you come to campus, it&rsquo;s like a smorgasbord or a buffet; there are a lot of different foods to eat. The majority of the foods are &ldquo;fast food&rdquo; types of foods like: burgers, fries, pizza and chicken patties. Those are just some of the foods available; there are healthier options as well. Making sure you only eat those &ldquo;fast food&rdquo; types of food occasionally is necessary. Balance the junk food out with more nutritious foods. Just because you don&rsquo;t have mom and dad watching what you eat, doesn&rsquo;t mean that all of a sudden, you stop eating greens, aka &ndash; vegetables!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Eating a well-balanced diet is really important, especially to your digestive system. I know that sounds gross but, a lot of students come to campus and aren&rsquo;t eating the foods their bodies are accustomed to and need. They get backed up and then they get sick! You also need to drink water and lots of it. Continue getting enough rest and eating well balanced meals. I say all of this because I have a friend who, in undergrad, when we first came to campus, he went wild with sweets! Growing up, his mom didn&rsquo;t let him eat sweets. We had a bakery on our campus and you could use your meal plan there. Well, let me tell you, my friend went crazy! He would get cakes; one time he got a whole cake! He would get cookies, ice cream, sherbet and cheesecake! He would just eat sweets, all the time. I guess he was making up for lost time. Most of the time, when I was sitting there eating a full meal, he was eating sweets. I didn&rsquo;t quite understand it, but to each their own. Over a short period of time, after arriving on campus, he developed really bad eating habits. His cholesterol level shot up and he got really sick. The moral of that story: Be mindful of what you&rsquo;re eating and how much you&rsquo;re eating!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When you get to campus, the food is going to be different from the majority of foods you&rsquo;re accustomed to from back home. Consider how much you&#39;re eating, how quickly you&rsquo;re eating, how often you&rsquo;re eating and when you&#39;re eating. Think about it: new college schedules are completely different. Students aren&rsquo;t eating at 8 a.m., 12 p.m. and 6 p.m. Students may eat at 8 a.m., 2 p.m. and then not eat again until 2 a.m. Or, maybe they eat at 12 p.m. as their first meal and then not again until 1 a.m. There really aren&rsquo;t &ldquo;regular&rdquo; eating habits on campus. Students have crazy schedules, thus their eating schedules are equally as crazy! On most college campuses, you can eat as much as you want. Just because you can eat as much as you want doesn&#39;t necessarily mean you should.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Statistics show that there has been an unusual increase in the last 10 years when it comes to eating disorders on college campuses. Increased stress and the change of leaving home and living on a college campus can be attributed to this increase. Eating disorders don&rsquo;t discriminate and can develop in any gender or race. Bulimia can be defined as an eating disorder in which large quantities of food are consumed in a short period of time, resulting in feelings of shame or guilt. Those feelings can lead to self-induced vomiting, purging or fasting, in order to feel &ldquo;normal&rdquo; again. Another eating disorder is anorexia. Anorexia is defined as an emotional disorder characterized by an obsessive desire to lose weight by refusing to eat. Both of these disorders are harmful to a person&rsquo;s mind and body. These disorders are common in college-age students who are attempting to transition into a new way of life, new schedules and new eating habits. If you or anyone you know are experiencing traits from either of these disorders, please seek help at your campus counseling center. The lack of acceptance of such a severe disorder can morph itself into many other psychological and physical health problems.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In addition, you may see some students that develop new workout habits because they&#39;re trying to maintain their weight with exercise. Sometimes people take working out way too far. They try to work out multiple times a day and for some, access to a gym may be new to them. We also find that some of our students are taking workout supplements or even using steroids to meet the needs of the goal they have in mind and what they want to achieve for their body. If this describes you, make sure you are using the right supplements. If you&#39;re not sure, ask someone. Visit your campus recreation center or talk to the campus nutritionist; either one you go to should be able to help you in making this type of decision. Obviously, steroids should be avoided at all cost. The effects can be devastating to your body and your mind; not to mention they are illegal in the U.S.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>One psychological problem that comes to mind, whether there is an eating disorder present or not, is body image. Body image can directly affect your self-esteem. Having a healthy mind can result in feeling good about your image, no matter what it looks like. If you have an exercise regimen, do it to meet your physical <em>and </em>emotional needs and do it in the healthiest, safest and most natural way possible. Adopting a healthy physical fitness regimen can help you stay focused, relieve stress, decrease depression and it&rsquo;s good for your overall health. It doesn&rsquo;t matter what your level of expertise is when it comes to physical activity. I know it can be easy to get up, go to class, come back and stay in your room studying. In fact, a lot of students follow that routine. Being sedentary can cause your metabolism to slow down, making weight gain a definite outcome. Movement of any kind is better than no movement at all. Do cardio or strength training; stay active!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tips for parents:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s important that when you&#39;re checking in with your son or daughter, don&#39;t just call them for two seconds to say &ldquo;hi&rdquo; and ask how classes are going. Ask your student about everything. Ask what they&#39;re doing in regard to their studying. Ask how they&rsquo;re sleeping. Ask about what they&rsquo;re eating and when. Ask if they&rsquo;re staying active. Ask them if their getting out of their room and moving! This is really important for their overall health and success.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tips for students:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Be mindful of what you eat, how much you eat and when you eat.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you have a meal plan, use it!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s okay to have a healthy balance of nutritious food and junk food.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If stress is getting to you, seek help immediately. An eating disorder is life altering and can develop from triggers such as stress and change to your &ldquo;normal&rdquo; life.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Don&rsquo;t compare yourself to others; love you!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you&rsquo;re not happy with your weight or your physical appearance, make a healthy change. Take care of yourself. No one is going to be able to take care of you more than you can. Your parents can call and check up on you all they want, but if you&rsquo;re not being honest with them (or honest with yourself), ultimately your health care, self-care and self-worth can suffer. It&rsquo;s all dependent upon you! We all know that weight gain can affect your mood, progress in school, confidence and self-esteem. A healthy lifestyle, a healthy mind and a healthy heart lead to better choices and ultimately, a better college experience.</p>', '2020-09-07 23:21:59', '2020-09-11 00:01:53', NULL),
(33, 6, 'Let’s Get Involved', NULL, 20, '<p>Look, I&#39;m going to be honest with you, if you&#39;re only going to college so that you can get a degree, so that you can get a better job, or so that you can make more money, then you&#39;re wasting your time. Do you realize how many people get degrees and can&rsquo;t find a job in their field? Or how many people get degrees and are not making the amount of money they anticipated? Going to college is not <em>solely </em>about getting a piece of paper that says you&#39;re certified to do what you&#39;ve been trained for. Going to college also has to do with you finding out who you are; about you developing and growing into the person that you want to be. Think about it, if college is just about getting certified, why are there so many non-academic engagements to get involved in while you&rsquo;re in college? That&rsquo;s why I think this chapter is so important. I find it crazy that there are some students who go to college and they don&#39;t get involved in anything; they literally go to class and that&#39;s it. My point here is that if you only want to go to class and go home, you could do that at home...for free! Why pay all that money and live on a college campus if you&rsquo;re not going to be involved?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&rsquo;m not saying that every student needs to have the same experience I had; not at all. In fact, when I was in school, I was probably involved in too much. When people say that they were stretched way too thin, they were talking about the definition set by Justin Brown. When I was in school, I was involved in about ten different organizations; one of those organizations I was the president, founder and creator of. I told you in another chapter, when I was on campus, I had four jobs. Why was being involved so important to me? For me personally, being involved gave me a variety of skills to add to my resume. It gave me the ability to work on teams and really focus on developing into the person I wanted to be. Being involved gave me the opportunity to get the necessary outside experience that I needed, in order to be the person who I am today. College is not just about what&#39;s happening inside the classroom, it&#39;s also about the opportunities and experiences that are happening outside of the classroom. The outside of the classroom involvement complements what you&#39;re doing in the classroom.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you&#39;re reading this and you&rsquo;re a first year student or a parent, I&rsquo;m not saying you have to be involved in everything. I know a lot of people who went to school who weren&rsquo;t involved in many outside the classroom experiences and they went on to have very successful lives. But, did they get the most out of their college experience? Think about it, do you go to a fast food restaurant, order a meal from the value menu and then only eat the fries; forgetting about the drink and the burger. I know that&rsquo;s not what I do, yet it seems that a lot people do just that when they go to college. If you just want to go to class and go home, you may want to consider commuting or online college; it&rsquo;ll save you a lot of money. If you&#39;re going to school and living on campus, make the most out of your experience. Learning and development may start inside the classroom, but it continues to take place outside of the classroom. Sure, your classroom experience is going to give you all the instruction that you need on particular subjects, but other meaningful skills, attributes and experiences come from your learnings outside of the classroom.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;If you&rsquo;re like me and want to see and experience everything available, that&rsquo;s great! I used to tell people that I was a thief in high school and I was a thief in college. What I meant by saying that is, I made it my job to steal every single opportunity that was available and let me tell you, I was a master thief. Any time a scholarship came out, I applied. If a job opportunity became available, I filled out an application. If there was an option to be a part of a student group, I was there! Looking back, I&#39;m so glad that I took advantage of all the opportunities presented to me; I had a lot of great experiences. I will say to all those go-getters out there, spreading yourself too thin has consequences. You may have to sacrifice sleep, time with your friends, or time with your family. Sometimes you&rsquo;re not eating well or exercising enough, but most importantly, you&#39;re not taking care of yourself properly. Ensure that you&#39;re taking time for yourself and you&#39;re doing what you need to do so that you remain healthy.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As many groups as there are on student campuses, you can be involved in almost anything. In fact, most schools allow you to create your own groups. If you see something that&rsquo;s missing on campus that you want to be a part of, create it. That&rsquo;s how my diversity program got started. When I got to my college campus, I realized there weren&rsquo;t many groups formed with the mission of bringing people together and creating unity; that was something I had an interest in. I had an advisor who guided and advised me, and a few others, on what types of events to do with the group and the advisor made sure that we were setting the group up correctly.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>One element you don&rsquo;t want to miss, if you want to start a student group on campus, is finding a good advisor. Find someone who will hold you accountable and make sure that your group is following the missions, goals and rules in order to be a successful campus group. Most campuses are looking for extra groups and new groups. If there was something that you did in high school or something you wanted to do but couldn&rsquo;t do, rest assured, you can try it on a college campus. In fact, most ideas presented to the Student Government Association result in some free funding to help you accomplish the task. You&rsquo;re already paying the money for tuition, you might as well get the most out of it and if someone is offering free money, then I would definitely hop on that.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Friends that I graduated with that I remain in contact with have expressed their disappointment in not taking full advantage of their college experience. Not saying that their college experiences were bad, just that they wish they would have done more, outside the classroom, while they were in school. They regret not taking advantage of the many opportunities available. Some mentioned their envy when they saw what I had accomplished. College goes by so fast. I think the longest college year is your first year. You&#39;re still trying to figure out who you are. Probably for the first time, you&rsquo;re away from your parents, your town and everything that&rsquo;s familiar to you. I thought it was the longest year out of all of them. After your freshman year, it happens in the blip of a second; it goes by so quickly. Before you know it, you&#39;re a senior and you&rsquo;re graduating. College is the only time in your life that will ever be like this. The only time where you just wake up, go to class, maybe have a job, participate in student groups, eat when you want and basically have minimal responsibilities. After college, life happens and boy does it happen fast! When you graduate college, it&rsquo;s time to start adulting; time for a little bit more responsibility. Make the most out of your college years and experience all that your heart desires; it only happens once.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Time management is key! If you don&#39;t measure time right, you could really find yourself messed up. I could tell you a whole bunch of stories about how I don&#39;t think that my friends used their time correctly, which they didn&rsquo;t &ndash; hint, hint - those friends know who they are. For this discussion, I&#39;m going to pretty much talk about myself. I think it&#39;s important for you, as the reader, to know that even though I&rsquo;m being honest and sharing my knowledge in the form of this book, I don&#39;t know everything. Here&rsquo;s some honesty for you: I put a lot more time into my campus jobs and into my campus leadership positions than I ever did in my academics. I tell people this and they don&#39;t believe me. I can honestly tell you that I don&rsquo;t remember my sophomore year of college. People think that&#39;s crazy, but I&#39;m serious; I really don&#39;t remember. It was the first year I became an R.A., the first year I became an orientation ambassador, the first year I started working for the public relations office at my university, and I had recently created my diversity program. I put so much effort into everything outside of my academics that the only reason I know I had a sophomore year is because I can go into my computer and see that I actually did homework assignments that year. I don&#39;t remember going to class. I don&rsquo;t remember what classes I took. I don&rsquo;t remember any assignments or any group work that I did. To some of you that may sound funny, but really, it&rsquo;s just plain sad. Why don&rsquo;t I remember? I was stretched way too thin.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As a student, make sure you&#39;re taking care of yourself. Administration, faculty and staff look for students to accomplish tasks and assignments all the time. If you&#39;re someone who&#39;s always raising your hand to take on extra, trust me, they will use you to get the task accomplished. I know I said to take advantage of as many opportunities as possible, but you also have to be realistic. I also told you I don&rsquo;t remember my sophomore year because I took on too much. Looking back, I should&rsquo;ve done a tiny bit less. Just because an opportunity comes up, it doesn&#39;t mean <em>you </em>have to do it. In fact, whenever something popped up, I&#39;m pretty sure the student body didn&#39;t even attempt to sign up because they already knew &ldquo;Justin&#39;s going to sign up for that.&rdquo; I&rsquo;m trying to advocate both sides. I&#39;m advocating for you to be the best student that you can be, but I&#39;m also advocating that you are realistic in your goals and that you&#39;re taking time for yourself.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Parents, if you see that your son or daughter is not involved, don&rsquo;t harp on them. This is not the time to say things like, &ldquo;You need to get involved, we&rsquo;re not paying all this money so you can just sit around after class &ndash; blah blah blah!&rdquo; They don&rsquo;t need us telling them what to do; we can simply guide and advise them. If your son or daughter is one of those individuals who will probably only go to class and not much more, it&rsquo;s okay! It&#39;s actually very common for first year students to not get too involved; their world is changing. Give them time to get acclimated to their new surroundings. Let them work it out.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Then there are the students who are heavily involved in their first year. The data and studies show that if we can grab students in their first year, or even better yet, in their first week of college, it increases their ability to stay at the college and to complete their education. If students feel that they are owning their university, their campus culture and their experience, they&rsquo;ll want to stay. All we need to do as staff and parents is gently encourage students to get involved and give them ideas of what they can get involved with.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If at first, you don&#39;t see a group you want to get involved in, keep looking. There are a lot of student groups that I was a part of as a first-year student that I didn&#39;t necessarily care for. I went to a couple of meetings and decided, &ldquo;Nope, not for me.&rdquo; I&#39;ve attended student groups and left the meeting thinking, &ldquo;What the heck? How is that even a group?&rdquo; I attended this one student group called, &ldquo;Larping&rdquo;. I only attended one time. Larping is live, action role play. The members dressed up like they belonged in kingdoms. They had these foam swords and they were trying to knock each other out. It only took one hit to the face, with one of those foam daggers, and I was out! I never showed up again! There may also be times when you get involved in a student group and invest a lot of time and then the group ends up not being what you wanted or thought it would be. Find activities that interest you. If you don&rsquo;t find a group or activity that interests you, create a new group. Honestly, like I said, I never thought when I went to college that I would be creating a diversity group, but it happened. Sometimes, you don&#39;t find groups; sometimes the group or the idea find you!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you&rsquo;re bold enough to start your own student group, it will definitely involve a good amount of your personal time. And, if you&rsquo;re like me, the group will become your brainchild. You will feel an almost abnormal attachment. When I was in college, I felt that leaving a legacy was important. I founded, developed and was the president of the groups I created; of course, I had the help and support of other students and our advisor. When I graduated, I left those groups in the hands of other people. When you create great things and other people take up your legacy, after you leave, it&#39;s so satisfying knowing that your legacy is going to continue on. It was important to me and I was proud of the accomplishment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Another topic we should discuss is: Greek life. Greek life is huge on college campuses. Why? Greek life contributes to student leadership, community service and philanthropy. They also make a significant contribution to the diversity of the student body. You may be reading this thinking, &ldquo;I&rsquo;m a part of Greek life and there is <em>nothing</em> like the bonds you form.&rdquo; Or maybe you&rsquo;re thinking, &ldquo;No, I had a bad experience with Greek life; I would never be a part of that.&rdquo; I had a very interesting experience pertaining to Greek life. When I first arrived on campus, I saw a lot of people trying to pledge fraternities. I can tell you this, pledging white fraternities and pledging black fraternities are two totally different things. if you don&rsquo;t know, you should probably look up the differences between the two .</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I remember a member from one of the two historically black fraternities came up to me and said, &ldquo;Hey we want you to be a part of our fraternity.&rdquo; I went to the meetings and they told me what a great opportunity this would be for me. I was all over this opportunity! I wanted in! With anything major in life, if you&#39;re going to be a part of Greek life (sorority or fraternity), do your research. Honestly, up front, most of the groups appear to be great, and some of them are, but sometimes things aren&rsquo;t always what they seem. After doing a little bit of research and talking to a few people, I was on the fence; did I want to join or not? I remember one of the fraternity brothers came up to me and said, &ldquo;You know what? I think this fraternity would be a really good fit for you.&rdquo; I asked him why and he replied, &ldquo;I think it&#39;ll be good for you because I don&#39;t really see you out in the black community much. This would provide you with some much needed face-time.&rdquo; This statement not only rubbed me the wrong way; it rubbed me in the complete opposite direction of that fraternity. In fact, I think this fueled the fire for the reason why I got so involved on campus, and not with Greek life. If the way to show my &ldquo;blackness&rdquo; was to be a part of this fraternity, then I wanted no parts of it. No matter what, me and the guys in that fraternity will probably have the same struggles in life. It doesn&rsquo;t matter if I was part of the fraternity or not. Now, I wanted to prove that I could do it without Greek life. I&rsquo;m sure others have experienced similar situations and they&rsquo;re able to accomplish the goals they set during their college career, without Greek life. Still others, will use Greek life as a launching pad in setting up their success on college campuses.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I think that a lot of fraternities and sororities get bad raps because of all the recent media reports regarding hazing and pledging. In my experience, every fraternity or sorority says they don&rsquo;t haze; they don&rsquo;t make people pledge. We know that&rsquo;s not true though. I do know a few people who have conveyed that they were <em>not</em> hazed during their pledging process. In my opinion, (and I feel it&rsquo;s about 90% true) hazing has gone underground. In recent years, there has been a lot of publicity around hazing events going very wrong, resulting in some new laws being created. The laws were set to make sure people don&rsquo;t get hurt or suffer from health issues (either mental or physical), due to what takes place during the pledging process.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are many different Greek groups. There are honors fraternities and sororities, academic honors fraternities and sororities, and sports fraternities and sororities. There are a lot of different groups you can join. In relation to Greek life, I can recall one crazy hazing situation that I witnessed. I remember one night me and my friend Terrece were walking into our residence hall. It was just a normal night. We saw some guy and he was blindfolded. He was getting picked up and dragged out of the residence hall. Terrece and I just sat there watching the whole thing. They threw the guy in the trunk of a car. They slammed the trunk door closed and all four of the brothers got in the car and they drove off. We never knew what happened to that guy. Looking back on it now, we probably should&rsquo;ve said something to someone.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My friend Terrece and I went to school together and are best friends. We talked about our different fraternity situations. In his situation, he was told to come to a certain building, at a certain time for a meeting. He didn&#39;t know what the meeting was for but he was given the specific location and time of the meeting and it was implied he <em>should </em>be there. He showed up at the specified meeting location, at the requested time. He showed up to a dark room. The light was then shockingly turned on and he saw the whole room filled with a bunch of fraternity brothers. They all had paddles. They were loud and extremely aggressive in trying to sell him on the fraternity. I think their tactics really turned him off as well.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Again, do the research! Before joining, look up the history on any fraternity or sorority you&rsquo;re considering. Talk to other students on campus, about their experiences with Greek life at your college. Greek life may not even exist on your campus. There are campuses, across the country, that don&#39;t support Greek life and don&rsquo;t have it represented at their university. Consider your path, with information based off of the fraternities and sororities reputations. People will tell you what their reputations are. And listen, every fraternity and sorority has a reputation. Don&rsquo;t pledge a group just because your friend is pledging that group.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Think about the cost factor of joining a fraternity or sorority. This is not a cheap endeavor. There are dues to pay each semester. The dues go towards trips, shirts and swag, events and parties and a lot of other related items. Don&rsquo;t choose Greek life because it&rsquo;s the popular choice. Choose it if it&rsquo;s something that interests you. Some of the groups may not have the same morals, values and beliefs that you&#39;re looking to surround yourself with. You might be signing up for a college experience you weren&rsquo;t looking for.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Greek life does has some great benefits. Obviously, there&rsquo;s the philanthropy aspect and who doesn&rsquo;t want to help others? Philanthropists do a good amount of service for the community they live in. There seems to be endless networking opportunities. Just because I chose not to go that route, don&rsquo;t discount it; that direction may work for you. Greek life gets a bad rap but for the most part, you see fraternities and sororities doing a lot of good work on campus. Bottom line, do your research and figure out exactly who and what these groups are and what they represent. Do what you want to do for you, not for anyone else!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lastly, I want to talk about finding a mentor and becoming a mentee. Getting involved isn&rsquo;t only about you. It&rsquo;s also about making sure that you line yourself up with people that are going to help you succeed and in turn, you can do the same for someone else. While I was at my institution, I had plenty of mentors. Why do I feel so strongly about this topic? These mentors came up before me and they knew of potential pitfalls and obstacles. They helped me gain successes that I had no clue were even there. I would be amiss or a liar if I told you that I went through my entire college process by myself and I didn&rsquo;t need any help. I had individuals who were a huge part of my success. They helped me to succeed and helped me make the most out of my skills and situations.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Make finding a mentor one of the first things that do when you come to a college campus. Hopefully you&rsquo;ll find that one mentor, and you&rsquo;ll know when you&rsquo;ve found that special person. That person is going to become someone you could never, ever forget. Those are the individuals that make a long lasting impact on your life. These are the individuals that you&#39;ll keep in touch with and call long after you graduate.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I had two of those people in my world; the director of public relations and one of the directors of admissions, both at Slippery Rock University. I still call and email with them today. We still check-in with each other; just to see how things are going and to catch up. I would not have become the man I am today without their leadership, guidance and support. You have to pay homage to those who took the time to help you. How do you pay homage? Do for someone else, what they did for you; become a mentor!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In my first year of school, those people played a key part in me being successful. But when I became a junior and then a senior there were people who were coming up under me that needed the same help. Even though I was only a student, I could still help. I had some great experiences and had learned a lot and I could certainly share that information with someone else. I was able to use the skills I acquired from the people who mentored me. I paid it forward and became a mentor. I was actually a mentee and a mentor at the same time. I know a lot of you coming in from high school probably had mentors in high school; continue to utilize those people as well. They don&rsquo;t need to be on your campus to continue to provide knowledge, advice and wisdom. Keep those relationships open and valid. Those people can play key roles in your life as you will in someone else&rsquo;s life. Ultimately, what you get out of your college experience outside of the classroom will be dependent on your skills, drive and personality. Make your experience what you want it to be. Don&rsquo;t wait for others to get you out there, you get yourself out there. Get internships, job experience and tools to be as successful as you can. It&#39;s up to you.</p>', '2020-09-07 23:22:17', '2020-09-11 00:01:31', NULL);
INSERT INTO `chapters` (`id`, `course_id`, `name`, `image`, `amount`, `details`, `created_at`, `updated_at`, `deleted_at`) VALUES
(34, 6, 'My Final Thoughts', NULL, 20, '<p>Congratulations! You made it to the last chapter of the book! I like to offer my congratulations because sometimes people start books and they don&#39;t finish or they get into the middle of a book and it&#39;s really good and juicy, but then life interrupts. I&#39;m really happy that you took the time to read the book. I mentioned that this is my second book and I never thought I would write one book, let alone two. Sharing my knowledge and experiences with you has been such a blessing for me.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In my previous book, I wrote a chapter on final thoughts. A lot of people contacted me and said that the final thoughts chapter was probably the most inspirational part of the book. I never want to end the conversation on, &lsquo;Things I didn&#39;t tell my mom in college&rsquo;. I think to end the conversation about college, student development, life&rsquo;s changes and overall well-being of students might allow people to think that these conversations can be ended, and they can&rsquo;t be ended; it&rsquo;s imperative we continue talking. These conversations can&rsquo;t end because we should be having these conversations on a regular basis; simply because the content is ever-changing, ever-fluid and ever-developing. As trends in higher education are changing, so are the students, the parents, the staff and society. In order to ensure that everyone is making the most of their college experiences and to ensure that we are hitting all the necessary topics and not missing anything important, we all should be changing right along with the trends.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So again I leave my final thoughts to you, my readers. I leave to you a compilation of all things Justin, words of wisdom, tips, tricks and everything I&#39;ve learned up to this point in my life to help you be as successful as possible during your college years. I don&rsquo;t confess to knowing everything; that would be completely untrue. But I do hope that you&#39;re able to take some of these life lessons and apply them to your lives and I hope that the information provided to you is beneficial to your life.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>College changed me. When I was in high school, I was that extremely happy and eccentric kid. I had endless energy and a lot of raw potential, but it was never really centralized, in one place, for me to focus on. College gave me the skills and abilities to figure out how to use everything that God had given me, to the best of my ability. That&rsquo;s what college is supposed to do. It&rsquo;s supposed to mold and shape you into the best person you can be. Allow this development to happen. Allow yourself to make the most out of your college experience. College is going to be a series of ups and downs, successes and failures; it&#39;s not going to be a perfect trip. I don&rsquo;t want this book to be presented as if college is this perfectly paved road with no potholes. You&rsquo;re definitely going to have some heartbreaks. You&rsquo;re going to have some setbacks. You&rsquo;re going to fail some tests. You&rsquo;re going to meet some people that hurt you and ultimately, you&rsquo;re going to have some days when you don&rsquo;t want to do any of it anymore. There were <em>many </em>times I wanted to drop out. There were times that I didn&#39;t want to <em>do</em> college anymore and there were plenty of times I just wanted to give up. But, as with anything else in life, you have to keep pushing forward. You have to keep taking all those experiences and let them mold you, shape you and develop you so you can become the best person possible.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you think there&rsquo;s a possibility that you&#39;re not going to do anything with your degree, don&#39;t go to college. Trust me, it would be a waste of your time and your money. You&rsquo;re only going to college so that you can be certified in something. A degree, after all, is just a piece of paper, people!&nbsp; But, it&rsquo;s the most expensive piece of paper you&rsquo;ll ever pay for! If you&rsquo;re going to do something with your degree, make sure that you&#39;re getting a degree in something that interests you; something you think you can do in your future. <em>You </em>have to choose your path and do it for yourself because being an adult is challenging and demanding, so you may as well enjoy what you do for a living.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Someone once told me that being an adult is basically just emailing someone back and forth saying, &ldquo;Sorry for the delayed response!&rdquo; until one of you dies. Come on! For real? Life has got to be about more than that! Life should be a thrilling ride. A ride where you take a hold of the reins and have fun!&nbsp; Otherwise, you&rsquo;re wasting your time. It&rsquo;s inevitable, we&rsquo;re all going to die. You may as well take this time in your life and make it the best it can be. Life can be hard. Most people don&rsquo;t have it easy and most are not born with a silver spoon in their mouth. I figure if life is going to be hard and challenging, why not punch life right in the mouth with a fistful of success? Some of the best revenge you can have is success. With a show of hands, how many of you have had people that did you wrong, hurt you, turned their back on you or told you that you couldn&rsquo;t do something or wouldn&rsquo;t amount to anything? The best revenge is success. Go out there and knock life right in the mouth!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>People are going to betray you; it happens. It&rsquo;s going to happen when you&rsquo;re in college too. This will happen in life after college as well. Don&rsquo;t hold onto those feelings of betrayal. Find something in the situation and create a learning experience. You&rsquo;ll also meet people in college who will end up being your best friends. You&rsquo;ll stay in contact way after you graduate. Keep the people that matter close, don&rsquo;t let those people go. I understand that life happens; people get married, have kids, get new jobs, and move away. Keep those valuable friendships intact so you can make a lifetime of memories with them.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Look, no one is going to make you go to class; class is optional. You&#39;re paying your money to go to school and you&rsquo;re only going to go if you want to. I&#39;m saying that you have to take it seriously and if you&rsquo;re taking your college education seriously, you&rsquo;ll go to class. For some of you, you only get one shot and like I stated earlier in this text, you miss 100% of the shots you don&rsquo;t take. So step up to that line, dribble the ball and shoot for success! If you&#39;re not interested in going to class, you could&#39;ve stayed at home for free. Don&rsquo;t waste your time or your money; take it seriously. Show up and be present; physically, mentally and emotionally.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Life usually doesn&#39;t provide you with chances. You need to create chances and take them! Go out there and get it! Live! No one is going to give you opportunities if you&#39;re not putting yourself in a place to receive those opportunities. Sign up for something new. Apply for things you wouldn&#39;t normally do. Do an internship. Do a practicum. Go out there and make new friends. Have lunch with someone you don&#39;t know. Get out there and experience different groups. Go see shows, go to a play. Do something new. You can find endless fun during your college years but you won&rsquo;t find it sitting in your dorm room. Get out there and make it happen.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You will have failures and setbacks, but choose to fail forward, not backwards. Failures teach you valuable life lessons; they&rsquo;re an important factor in your continued learning. I think I learned the most valuable lessons during my college years, when I wasn&#39;t successful or when I had failed at something. I can&rsquo;t stress it enough, put yourself out there. Sometimes you need to bite the bullet and start caring about something new, with all your heart and energy. But you can&rsquo;t care about something if you continue to hold yourself back, anticipating the scenario not working out. Take the skills you learn from failures and apply them to every aspect of your life.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Look, your parent&rsquo;s advice is wise, but it&#39;s not the end-all-be-all nor is it the only advice out there. Parents, I know that you&#39;re trying to guide your son or daughter the best way that you know how, using all the knowledge that you had about college and that&rsquo;s great, but the landscape has changed, drastically. If you&rsquo;ve read anything in this book, you&rsquo;ve probably realized, by now, that college is nothing like you remember. You can only advise your child the best way that you can. Your kids are not going to take every single piece of information that you give, and quite frankly, they shouldn&rsquo;t. They have to start making decisions for themselves. For the student, take the wisdom your parents are offering, add it to the morals and values they&rsquo;ve instilled in you, and create your own set of morals and values. That will help make you the successful person you want to be.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Why stop at one degree? A lot of people go to college to get their undergraduate degree, bachelor&#39;s degree or associate&#39;s degree and then say, &ldquo;I&#39;m done, I&#39;m out, peace-out, sayonara.&rdquo; What I&rsquo;m saying is, if you really want to make the most out of any career or any situation, keep learning and keep moving forward. Keep getting certifications. Go get your master&rsquo;s degree. Move on and get your doctoral degree. Education can provide you with a variety of opportunities, so why stop with just one degree? Continue to push forward. Continue to broaden your mind. Continue to expand your knowledge. Continue to go through different trainings. Continue to learn and grow.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sometimes in college you have to learn to stand alone. Not everybody is going to be on the same side as you. There are many times I had to take stances in college and I lost friends. There were times when I had to make important decisions; whether it was social injustice issues, dealing with group relations in team projects or just a run of the mill issue. Not everybody&#39;s going to have your back, so learn to stand alone. People can suck sometimes. No one said you have to be friends with everybody; choose your friends wisely. At most schools, there are thousands and thousands of students. It doesn&#39;t mean thousands and thousands of students are going to be your friends. In fact, you shouldn&rsquo;t <em>expect</em> anybody to be your friend. Everybody is running the same rat race as you are. Everybody&#39;s trying to earn a degree (or more) and be successful. Buckle down, keep your head up and be sure that you&#39;re doing what you need to do to be successful. Colleagues and friends will come and go along the way, regardless. Some people you meet in college will only be a part of your life for a season; others for a lifetime. Enjoy them either way and keep moving forward to your future successes!&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I want everybody who&#39;s reading this final chapter to know that you <em>have to</em> be better than the most recent generation. I know a lot of you are looking at the current generation and thinking, &ldquo;We&rsquo;re doomed!&rdquo; There has to be someone out there who&rsquo;s going to change the entire facet of how the country runs or someone who really pushes us into the next era. We have got to be better than what was here before us. If not, we&rsquo;re all just going to fall down as fools. I know that sometimes when you&#39;re looking back at it all and thinking about what could have been, sometimes it sucks and it may seem hopeless. Students, if you spent this whole time thinking that you want to be a grown up, stop! Take the time you have now and really enjoy it! Think about it, a lot of people who are older look back and say, &ldquo;Man - I really wish I would have taken the time that I had when I was younger and made the most out of it.&rdquo; Don&#39;t be in such a rush to get older! It will happen; it&#39;s inevitable. So take the time now, do what you need to do, and enjoy it!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Don&#39;t waste time while you&rsquo;re in school! We talked about school being such a short amount of time; for the majority of you it will be four years, some of you - five years. Don&#39;t waste the time that you have there, it&#39;s important to make the most of it. Unfortunately, there may be some events that happen to you while you&#39;re in college, like the death of a loved one, lack of money, or lack of motivation, but no matter what happens, don&rsquo;t let those obstacles hold you back. Keep moving forward. Go for what <em>you </em>want and not for what your parents want for you. Stay true to yourself and allow yourself to grow and to be challenged.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When you&#39;re going to college, regardless of if you&rsquo;re joining a student group, choosing a major, or whatever, do something you love! Don&#39;t base your choices solely on what your parents are telling you or, for that matter, what other people are saying you should do. If you choose something that you love, you&rsquo;ll never work a day in your life. That means that you have to be smart when choosing a major and also be smart when you&rsquo;re planning financially for school. Do the research to make sure that you&#39;re choosing the best school, as well as making sure that the school is financially available to you.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I have to tell you, I met a lot of moronic people in college. College is not just made up of the best minds in the entire world, trust me. Going to school does not measure your level of intelligence. Some of the most simple-minded people I&#39;ve met, I met in college. I can also tell you that some of the wisest people I&rsquo;ve ever met were blue collar workers who never stepped foot on a college campus. Having a degree does not categorize you as smart! It doesn&#39;t mean that you&#39;ve arrived or that you&#39;re better than anybody else. I&rsquo;ve seen people flaunting their degrees as if they&#39;ve made it. College isn&rsquo;t for everybody. I am not advocating that every single person should go to college. A lot of successful people became successful without college and have made it without gaining a formalized degree; experience can be invaluable. If you choose to go to college and get a degree, it&#39;s your responsibility to go out there and change the world, create better policies, and make something new that the world hasn&#39;t seen. Don&#39;t continue to regurgitate the same mess that the world already sees every single day. We have to make the most of it and time goes by so quickly.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Be kind to everybody. You never know what&#39;s going on in someone&rsquo;s life. College students are dealing with a lot of things. If this book hasn&rsquo;t shown you that college has its own baggage, then I don&#39;t know what you were reading. You don&#39;t know what someone else is going through and you don&#39;t know the amount or type of baggage that they&rsquo;re carrying. Go out of your way, every day, and pay it forward; be kind. If we all practiced paying it forward, the world would be a much better place.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Students, you can do this by creating unforgettable moments and making unforgettable, life-long memories. You do this by putting yourself out there and embracing things that are new and uncomfortable. Make the most out of every situation and learn from your mistakes. Team up with people who are doing the same things as you and network with them; network your butt off! Meet new people who are going to open doors for you. College doesn&rsquo;t make you better than someone else, but it does give you more responsibility; the world is depending on you to be different. Love yourself, love your education, love your family and love what you do.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Parents, I know that you&#39;re trying to teach your kids some valuable lessons; trying to hone in on what they should expect when they go off to college. By all means - hammer away! If you don&#39;t, you&rsquo;re leaving it up to chance. You might be sending your child off to an institution and setting them up for failure. That&rsquo;s certainly not something any of us want. Not teaching your children and preparing them the best way you know how could result in your child going in the complete opposite direction of what you both had planned. Be realistic. Don&#39;t be in denial that your child may come home a changed young adult. I&rsquo;m sure throughout this book you&rsquo;ve probably thought, &ldquo;That won&rsquo;t happen to my child&rdquo; or &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t need to tell my child about this.&rdquo; No! The purpose of this book is to help you have an open dialogue with your children, before, during and after they are in college, to ensure that they stay the course.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Let&rsquo;s make sure we are ALL setting the students up for success. The best way to do this is by having that open dialogue and preparing them with all the knowledge that we can; the rest is up to them. The rest is on you, student! You have to take everything you&rsquo;ve been given and taught and put it into practice. Your parents have spent about 18 years trying to instill certain values, wisdom and knowledge in you that will, hopefully, help you to navigate this weird terrain known as college. Look, parents, you&#39;re not perfect and neither are your kids. Give your students room to grow and make mistakes. Just because they don&#39;t get something the first time doesn&rsquo;t mean that they&#39;re not going to get it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ultimately students, the power is in you. I wrote this book because I wanted to give people hope. I also wanted to give people an inside look at some of the things that I see on a daily basis; some I experienced myself and some I witnessed firsthand. I know a lot of educators around the country probably see the exact same things. Students, it&#39;s up to you! You&#39;ve been given all the tools and skills that you need in order to be successful. We&rsquo;ve talked about all of the big topics that there are to talk about when it comes to entering higher education and we want you to make sure that you&#39;re making the best decisions possible. I look forward to seeing all of the wonderful things you create in this world and I know that you will be able to! It won&rsquo;t be because you read this book, but because the greatness is inside you: the greatness to be strong and the greatness to succeed and the greatness to do amazing things. What I know is that you&rsquo;ll be able to take what you&rsquo;ve learned and you&rsquo;ll be able to create greatness!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I hope you will refer back to this text if you ever need anything, because that&#39;s where I&#39;ll be. Whenever you need advice or wisdom about college, I&rsquo;ll be here; right in the words inside this book. If you&rsquo;re done with the book and you personally don&rsquo;t need it anymore, make sure you pass it on to somebody who&#39;s coming up behind you, because, like I said before, it&#39;s great to pay it forward. When you know better, you do better.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Peace!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Justin L. Brown</p>', '2020-09-07 23:23:01', '2020-09-11 00:01:28', NULL);

